{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Calabarzon", "text_new": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Calabarzon of the Philippines}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Philippine English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Calabarzon\n| map1            = COVID-19 pandemic cases in Calabarzon.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Confirmed cases in Calabarzon by province (as of April 3){{refn|group=note|name=PHmapnote|Breakdown of confirmed cases is according to the [https://www.doh.gov.ph/covid19tracker COVID-19 Case Tracker] of the Department of Health.}}}}\n{{legend|#510000|100+ confirmed}}{{legend|#900000|71\u201399 confirmed}}{{legend|#c80200|51\u201370 confirmed}}{{legend|#ee7070|21\u201350 confirmed}}{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u201320 confirmed}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Calabarzon]]\n| first_case      = [[Cainta, Rizal]]\n| arrival_date    = March 5, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China (via Metro Manila)\n| recovery_cases  = 29\n| deaths          = 59\n| confirmed_cases = 747\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Calabarzon]], Philippines on March 7, 2020, when the first case of coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) was confirmed in [[Cainta, Rizal]]. All provinces in the region has confirmed cases. The region is second most affected region by COVID-19 with more than 700 confirmed cases and at least 50 deaths.\n\n== Background ==\nThe first confirmed COVID-19 case in [[Calabarzon]] is a 62-year-old male, a resident of [[Cainta, Rizal]], who frequented a Muslim prayer hall in San Juan, Metro Manila. The patient was admitted at the Cardinal Santos Medical Center in San Juan, Metro Manila on March 1 and was diagnosed with severe pneumonia. The case was confirmed on March 5 and the man was referred to the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] in [[Muntinlupa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/cainta-rizal-coronavirus-philippines.html|title=Cainta, Rizal steps up coronavirus measures amid confirmed case|first=Elmor|last=Santos|work=CNN Philippines|date=March 7, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The individual's case is also the first confirmed local transmission of COVID-19 in the country having no travel history abroad.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000450/doh-first-local-transmission-wife-among-three-new-covid-19-deaths|title=First local COVID-19 transmission case, wife among 3 new deaths in Philippines|first=Ratziel|last=San Juan|work=The Philippine Star|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The patient's wife also contracted the disease.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribune.net.ph/index.php/2020/03/13/cainta-couple-die-from-covid-19/|title=Cainta couple dies from COVID-19|first=Neil|last=Alcober|work=Daily Tribune|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Kit Nieto]] of [[Cainta]], ordered the immediate provision of face masks and disinfectants in areas near the residence of the patient. The patient's family, as well as his neighbors, were placed under quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Eimor |title=Cainta, Rizal steps up coronavirus measures amid confirmed case |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/cainta-rizal-coronavirus-philippines.html |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> Nieto suspended classes in Cainta from March 7 to 10 and placed the city under community quarantine since March 15.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hallare |first1=Katrina |title=Cainta, Rizal suspends classes, distributes face masks over coronavirus threat |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1238217/cainta-rizal-suspends-classes-distributes-face-masks-over-coronavirus-threat |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cainta mayor to place town under quarantine over 3 confirmed cases of COVID-19 |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/Cainta-mayor-to-place-town-under-quarantine-over-three-COVID-19-cases.html |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAside from Rizal, all provinces have confirmed cases. The first case per province by date of confirmation as is as follows:\n*[[Cavite]] - March 10<ref>{{cite news |title=Cavite confirms first COVID-19 case |url=http://tempo.com.ph/2020/03/10/cavite-confirms-first-covid-19-case/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Tempo}}</ref>\n*[[Batangas]] - March 13 <ref>{{cite news |title=Batangas confirms 2 COVID-19 cases, suspends classes in all levels |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/729535/batangas-confirms-1st-covid-19-case-suspends-classes-in-all-levels/story/ |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Laguna (province)|Laguna]] and [[Quezon]] - March 15<ref name=\"Inquirer-CovidLaguna\">{{cite news |last1=Molina |first1=Carlo Jacob |title=Laguna confirms second coronavirus case |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1246384/laguna-confirms-second-coronavirus-case |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 22, 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Quezon province confirms first COVID-19 patient |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/15/quezon-province-first-case-coronavirus.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>; the first two cases in Quezon is from [[Lucena, Philippines|Lucena]], which is geographically part of Quezon but is administered independently from the province. The first Quezon case outside Lucena is linked to the town of [[Sariaya]].<ref>{{cite news |title=2 new COVID-19 cases in Quezon traced to Lucena, Sariaya|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247198/2-new-covid-19-cases-in-quezon-traced-to-lucena-sariaya |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n<!---\n== Timeline ==\n\n== Statistics ==\n--->\n\n== Response ==\nCalabarzon is under the scope of the [[Luzon enhanced community quarantine|enhanced community quarantine in Luzon]] imposed by the national government on March 16.<ref name=\"ECQ\">{{cite news |last1=Luna |first1=Franco |title=Duterte places entire Luzon under 'enhanced' community quarantine |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/16/2001320/duterte-places-entire-luzon-under-enhanced-community-quarantine |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|Calabarzon]]\n[[Category:History of Calabarzon]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Ongoing COVID-19 viral pandemic in Calabarzon of the Philippines}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use Philippine English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Calabarzon\n| map1            = COVID-19 pandemic cases in Calabarzon.svg\n| legend1         = {{center|Confirmed cases in Calabarzon by province (as of April 3){{refn|group=note|name=PHmapnote|Breakdown of confirmed cases is according to the [https://www.doh.gov.ph/covid19tracker COVID-19 Case Tracker] of the Department of Health.}}}}\n{{legend|#510000|100+ confirmed}}{{legend|#900000|71\u201399 confirmed}}{{legend|#c80200|51\u201370 confirmed}}{{legend|#ee7070|21\u201350 confirmed}}{{legend|#ffC0C0|1\u201320 confirmed}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Calabarzon]]\n| first_case      = [[Cainta, Rizal]]\n| arrival_date    = March 5, 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=03|day1=07|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], China (via Metro Manila)\n| recovery_cases  = 29\n| deaths          = 59\n| confirmed_cases = 747\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\n\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Calabarzon]], Philippines on March 7, 2020, when the first case of coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) was confirmed in [[Cainta, Rizal]]. All provinces in the region has confirmed cases. The region is second most affected region by COVID-19 with more than 700 confirmed cases and at least 50 deaths.\n\n== Background ==\nThe first confirmed COVID-19 case in [[Calabarzon]] is a 62-year old male, a resident of [[Cainta, Rizal]], who frequented a Muslim prayer hall in San Juan, Metro Manila. The patient was admitted at the Cardinal Santos Medical Center in San Juan, Metro Manila on March 1 and was diagnosed with severe pneumonia. The case was confirmed on March 5 and the man was referred to the [[Research Institute for Tropical Medicine]] in [[Muntinlupa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/cainta-rizal-coronavirus-philippines.html|title=Cainta, Rizal steps up coronavirus measures amid confirmed case|first=Elmor|last=Santos|work=CNN Philippines|date=March 7, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The individual's case is also the first confirmed local transmission of COVID-19 in the country having no travel history abroad.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/12/2000450/doh-first-local-transmission-wife-among-three-new-covid-19-deaths|title=First local COVID-19 transmission case, wife among 3 new deaths in Philippines|first=Ratziel|last=San Juan|work=The Philippine Star|date=March 12, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref> The patient's wife also contracted the disease.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://tribune.net.ph/index.php/2020/03/13/cainta-couple-die-from-covid-19/|title=Cainta couple dies from COVID-19|first=Neil|last=Alcober|work=Daily Tribune|date=March 13, 2020|accessdate=April 11, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMayor [[Kit Nieto]] of [[Cainta]], ordered the immediate provision of face masks and disinfectants in areas near the residence of the patient. The patient's family, as well as his neighbors, were placed under quarantine.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Santos |first1=Eimor |title=Cainta, Rizal steps up coronavirus measures amid confirmed case |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/7/cainta-rizal-coronavirus-philippines.html |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref> Nieto suspended classes in Cainta from March 7 to 10 and placed the city under community quarantine since March 15.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hallare |first1=Katrina |title=Cainta, Rizal suspends classes, distributes face masks over coronavirus threat |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1238217/cainta-rizal-suspends-classes-distributes-face-masks-over-coronavirus-threat |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Cainta mayor to place town under quarantine over 3 confirmed cases of COVID-19 |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/13/Cainta-mayor-to-place-town-under-quarantine-over-three-COVID-19-cases.html |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n\nAside from Rizal, all provinces have confirmed cases. The first case per province by date of confirmation as is as follows:\n*[[Cavite]] - March 10<ref>{{cite news |title=Cavite confirms first COVID-19 case |url=http://tempo.com.ph/2020/03/10/cavite-confirms-first-covid-19-case/ |accessdate=12 April 2020 |work=Tempo}}</ref>\n*[[Batangas]] - March 13 <ref>{{cite news |title=Batangas confirms 2 COVID-19 cases, suspends classes in all levels |url=https://www.gmanetwork.com/news/news/regions/729535/batangas-confirms-1st-covid-19-case-suspends-classes-in-all-levels/story/ |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=GMA News |date=March 13, 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Laguna (province)|Laguna]] and [[Quezon]] - March 15<ref name=\"Inquirer-CovidLaguna\">{{cite news |last1=Molina |first1=Carlo Jacob |title=Laguna confirms second coronavirus case |url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1246384/laguna-confirms-second-coronavirus-case |accessdate=March 31, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 22, 2020 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Quezon province confirms first COVID-19 patient |url=https://cnnphilippines.com/news/2020/3/15/quezon-province-first-case-coronavirus.html |accessdate=March 30, 2020 |work=CNN Philippines |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref>; the first two cases in Quezon is from [[Lucena, Philippines|Lucena]], which is geographically part of Quezon but is administered independently from the province. The first Quezon case outside Lucena is linked to the town of [[Sariaya]].<ref>{{cite news |title=2 new COVID-19 cases in Quezon traced to Lucena, Sariaya|url=https://newsinfo.inquirer.net/1247198/2-new-covid-19-cases-in-quezon-traced-to-lucena-sariaya |accessdate=April 12, 2020 |work=Philippine Daily Inquirer |date=March 23, 2020}}</ref>\n<!---\n== Timeline ==\n\n== Statistics ==\n--->\n\n== Response ==\nCalabarzon is under the scope of the [[Luzon enhanced community quarantine|enhanced community quarantine in Luzon]] imposed by the national government on March 16.<ref name=\"ECQ\">{{cite news |last1=Luna |first1=Franco |title=Duterte places entire Luzon under 'enhanced' community quarantine |url=https://www.philstar.com/headlines/2020/03/16/2001320/duterte-places-entire-luzon-under-enhanced-community-quarantine |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=The Philippine Star |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines}}\n{{Rodrigo Duterte}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the Philippines|Calabarzon]]\n[[Category:History of Calabarzon]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBackground:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 62-year old male \u2192 62-year-old male", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Calabarzon"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bermuda", "text_new": "{{one source|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Bermuda}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bermuda\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            =  \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Bermuda]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 18 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=18|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 25\n| deaths          = 4\n| confirmed_cases = 57<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6/|title=ArcGIS. Johns Hopkins CSSE}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the [[British Overseas Territory]] of [[Bermuda]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/> From 19 March, [[Public Health England]] no longer classified COVID-19 as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef />\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 18 March, the first two cases in Bermuda were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bernews.com/2020/03/first-cases-of-covid-19-in-bermuda-confirmed/ |title=First Cases Of Covid-19 In Bermuda Confirmed|website=bernews.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bernews.com/2020/03/live-updates-coronavirus/|title=Updates: Covid-19 On Thursday, March 26|date=2020-03-26|website=Bernews|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 12, there were a total of 50 cases on the island out of which 24 were imported, 18 were community spread, 8 were pending investigation, and 28 were recovered. On April 6, it was announced that there had been the first two COVID-19 deaths on the island. On April 8, there were a total of 4 deaths from Covid-19. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.bm/coronavirus/|title=Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) : Government of Bermuda}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\n\nThe government announced a 14-day 24-hour lockdown starting 4 April, where residents were only allowed to leave home for groceries or medical emergencies.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McWhirter |first1=Fiona |title=Under siege: island braces for 24-hour lockdown {{!}} The Royal Gazette:Bermuda News |url=http://www.royalgazette.com/health/article/20200402/under-siege-island-braces-for-24-hour-lockdown |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Royal Gazette}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Bermuda]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America|Bermuda]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in British Overseas Territories|Bermuda]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Bermuda]]\n\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{Bermuda-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{one source|date=March 2020}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Bermuda}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Bermuda\n| map1            = \n| legend1         = \n| map2            =  \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Bermuda]]\n| first_case      = \n| arrival_date    = 18 March 2020<br />({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=3|day1=18|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = \n| recovery_cases  = 25\n| deaths          = 4\n| confirmed_cases = 57<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.arcgis.com/apps/opsdashboard/index.html#/bda7594740fd40299423467b48e9ecf6/|title=ArcGIS. Johns Hopkins CSSE}}</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili       = \n| website         = \n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have reached the [[British Overseas Territory]] of [[Bermuda]] in March 2020.\n__TOC__\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/> From 19 March, [[Public Health England]] no longer classified COVID-19 as a \"High consequence infectious disease\".<ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef />\n\n==Timeline==\nOn 18 March, the first two cases in Bermuda were confirmed.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://bernews.com/2020/03/first-cases-of-covid-19-in-bermuda-confirmed/ |title=First Cases Of Covid-19 In Bermuda Confirmed|website=bernews.com}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://bernews.com/2020/03/live-updates-coronavirus/|title=Updates: Covid-19 On Thursday, March 26|date=2020-03-26|website=Bernews|access-date=2020-03-26}}</ref>\n\nAs of April 12, there were a total of 50 cases on the island out of which 24 were imported, 18 were community spread, 8 were pending investigation, and 28 were recovered. On April 6, it was announced that there had been the first two COVID-19 deaths on the island. On April 8, there were a total of 4 deaths from Covid-19. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gov.bm/coronavirus/|title=Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) : Government of Bermuda}}</ref>\n\n==Response==\n\nThe government announced a 14 day 24-hour lockdown starting 4 April, where residents were only allowed to leave home for groceries or medical emergencies.<ref>{{cite news |last1=McWhirter |first1=Fiona |title=Under siege: island braces for 24-hour lockdown {{!}} The Royal Gazette:Bermuda News |url=http://www.royalgazette.com/health/article/20200402/under-siege-island-braces-for-24-hour-lockdown |accessdate=6 April 2020 |work=The Royal Gazette}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Caribbean Public Health Agency]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{Coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Bermuda]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in North America|Bermuda]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in British Overseas Territories|Bermuda]]\n[[Category:Medical outbreaks in Bermuda]]\n\n\n{{COVID-19-stub}}\n{{Bermuda-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eResponse:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 14 day \u2192 14-day", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Bermuda"}
{"title_page": "Klokotnitsa", "text_new": "\n\n'''Klokotnitsa''' ({{lang-bg|\u041a\u043b\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430}}; also transliterated ''Klokotnica'') may refer to:\n\n*[[Klokotnitsa, Haskovo Province]], a village in Bulgaria\n**[[Battle of Klokotnitsa]], 1230\n*[[Klokotnitsa Ridge]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Klokotnica (disambiguation)]] (\u041a\u043b\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430)\n*[[Klokot (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Kloko\u010devac (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{geodis}}\n", "text_old": "\n\n'''Klokotnitsa''' ({{lang-bg|\u041a\u043b\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430}}; also transliterated ''Klokotnica'') may refer to:\n\n*[[Klokotnitsa (Haskovo)]], a village in Bulgaria\n**[[Battle of Klokotnitsa]], 1230\n*[[Klokotnitsa (ridge)]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Klokotnica (disambiguation)]] (\u041a\u043b\u043e\u043a\u043e\u0442\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0430)\n*[[Klokot (disambiguation)]]\n*[[Kloko\u010devac (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{geodis}}\n", "name_user": "SrpskiAnonimac", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Klokotnitsa"}
{"title_page": "LSE\u2013Gaddafi affair", "text_new": "The '''LSE\u2013Gaddafi affair''' was a scandal in the [[United Kingdom]] that occurred as a result of relationship that existed between the [[London School of Economics]] (LSE) and the [[Libya]]n government and its leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] and his son [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]]. The NGO Gaddafi Foundation pledged to donate \u00a31.5 million over five years to a research centre, LSE Global Governance, of which \u00a3300k were paid. In addition, LSE Enterprise established a contract worth \u00a32.2 million to train Libyan officials. In 2008, the LSE granted a PhD degree<ref>[http://www2.lse.ac.uk/newsAndMedia/news/archives/2011/03/director_steps_down.aspx LSE.ac.uk]</ref> to [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]], the son of the Libyan leader, for a dissertation. Currently, allegations circulate that Gaddafi's thesis was ghost-written and/or plagiarised. In December 2010, [[Muammar Gaddafi]] addressed members of the School in a video link-up where he was addressed as \"Brother Leader\" and received an LSE cap previously given to [[Nelson Mandela]].\nAt the time of the [[2011 Libyan Civil War]], the relationship between the LSE and the Gaddafi regime, and the conduct of individual members of LSE's staff was called into question.<ref>See, for example, {{cite news | first = Nick | last = Cohen | publisher = The Spectator|date = 3 March 2011| title = Why Howard Davies had to resign | url = http://www.spectator.co.uk/nickcohen/6751678/why-howard-davies-had-to-resign.thtml}}; ''Wall Street Journal,'' \"[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703362804576184773979915688?mod=googlenews_wsj Institutions Scramble to Check on Libya Ties],\" 6 March 2011.</ref> As a result of the scandal, the LSE's Director, Sir [[Howard Davies (economist)|Howard Davies]], resigned on 3 March 2011, citing \"errors of judgement\".<ref>{{cite news | first = Gregory |last = White |title = The Latest Qaddafi Casualty Is The Head Of The London School Of Economics |url = http://www.businessinsider.com/howard-davies-lse-qadaffi-2011-3 | publisher = Business Insider }}</ref> In a ''New York Times'' op-ed piece on 7 March 2011, [[Roger Cohen]] wrote, in reference to events that had transpired at the School, \"It may be possible to sink to greater depths but right now I can't think how. ...The [[Arab Spring]] is also a Western Winter. ...How did we back, use and encourage the brutality of Arab dictators over so many years? To what degree did that cynical encouragement of despots foster the very jihadist rage Western societies sought to curb?\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/08/opinion/08iht-edcohen08.html Libyan Closure],\" ''New York Times'', 7 March 2011.</ref>\n\n==LSE and the Monitor Group==\n{{Main|Monitor Group}}\n[[File:Muammar al-Gaddafi, 12th AU Summit, 090202-N-0506A-324.jpg|thumb|right|[[Muammar Gaddafi]] at the [[African Union]] meeting, February 2009.]]\n[[File:LondonSchoolofEconomics cford.jpg|thumb|The London School of Economics]]\nIn 2004 Libya's government engaged [[Monitor Group]], a Boston-based, Harvard-linked, consultancy firm founded by Harvard Business School professor Mark Fuller, as advisors on matters of public relations.<ref>Michael Richardson, \"Monitor Group Touted for Muammar Khadafy over Torture of Bulgarian Nurses,\" 11 March 2011.</ref> According to leaked documents, [[Monitor Group]] received \u00a32 million \"in order to enhance international understanding and appreciation of Libya and the contribution it has made and may continue to make to its region and to the world.\" In addition, \"the goal is to introduce [[Muammar Gaddafi]] as a thinker and intellectual, independent of his more widely known and very public persona as the Leader of the Revolution in Libya.\"<ref>Mother Jones</ref>\n\nA number of Harvard University academics were active within Monitor.{{who|date=January 2012}}\n\nOne way to achieve this aim was to recruit prominent journalists and intellectuals who were prepared to travel to Libya and write in positive terms about the country.<ref name=\"lse-libya-anthony-giddens-gaddafi\"/> One prime target was academics associated with the LSE, such as professor [[Anthony Giddens]] (Giddens is a Fellow of King's College Cambridge and is an Emeritus professor at LSE). In 2006 and 2007 the company organized two trips to Libya for Giddens, when the former LSE Director met with [[Muammar Gaddafi]]. Giddens has declined to comment on the financial compensation he received on these occasions.<ref name=\"lse-libya-anthony-giddens-gaddafi\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/education/2011/mar/04/lse-libya-anthony-giddens-gaddafi | title = Anthony Giddens' trip to see Gaddafi vetted by Libyan intelligence chief | publisher= The Guardian | location=London | first1=Rajeev | last1=Syal | first2=Jeevan | last2=Vasagar | date=5 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nGiddens' first visit to Libya resulted in articles in the ''[[New Statesman]]'', ''[[El Pa\u00eds]]'' and ''[[La Repubblica]]'', where he argued that Libya had been transformed. In the ''New Statesman'' he wrote: \"Gaddafi's 'conversion' may have been driven partly by the wish to escape sanctions, but I get the strong sense it is authentic and there is a lot of motive power behind it. [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi|Saif Gaddafi]] is a driving force behind the rehabilitation and potential modernisation of Libya. Gaddafi Sr, however, is authorising these processes.\"<ref>Anthony Giddens, \"[http://www.newstatesman.com/200608280032 The Colonel and His Third Way],\" ''New Statesman'', August 28, 2006.</ref>  During the second visit, [[Monitor Group]] organized a panel of \"three thinkers\" \u2014 Giddens, Gaddafi, and [[Benjamin Barber]], Emeritus professor of Rutgers University, author of the book ''Jihad vs. McWorld'' \u2014 chaired by the veteran journalist Sir [[David Frost]].<ref>Mother;s Jones</ref> Returning from Libya, Giddens wrote about his \"chat with the colonel,\" in the ''Guardian'', concluding that \"If Gadafy is sincere about reform, as I think he is, Libya could end up as the Norway of North Africa.\"<ref>Anthony Giddens, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/mar/09/comment.libya?CMP=twt_gu My Chat with the Colonel],\" ''The Guardian'', 9 March 2007.</ref>\n\n==LSE grants PhD degree to Saif Gaddafi==\n\nIn 2008, Muammar Gaddafi's son, [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]], received a PhD from the Department of Philosophy at the LSE with a dissertation entitled \"The Role of Civil Society in the Democratization of Global Governance Institutions: From 'Soft Power' to Collective Decision-Making?\"<ref name=\"Islam Gaddafi 2009\">Saif al-Islam Alqadhafi, \"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbODMwMmNhYmMtZTVjYS00ODZlLTk4NjItYmJkNjliODQ1MGI2&hl=en The Role of Civil Society in the Democratization of Global Governance Institutions: From 'Soft Power' to Collective Decision-Making?]\" PhD Thesis, London School of Economics, submitted in September 2007.</ref> His supervisor was [[Nancy Cartwright (philosopher)|Nancy Cartwright]], a distinguished philosopher of science, and [[Alex Voorhoeve]], a political philosopher, advised on chapter 4 and the first half of chapter 5.<ref name=\"volkskrant.nl\">Jonathan Witteman, \"[http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/4936/Buitenland/article/detail/1851463/2011/02/24/Zoon-Kadhafi-schreef-dissertatie-over-democratie-en-pleegde-plagiaat.dhtml Zoon Kadhafi schreef dissertatie over democratie 'en pleegde plagiaat'],\" ''de Volkskrant'', 24 February 2011.</ref> In the text [[David Held]] is acknowledged as having \"directly advised\" the work.<ref name=\"Islam Gaddafi 2009\"/> One of the two examiners, Lord Meghnad Desai, the founder of LSE Global Governance, had retired from LSE in 2003 and in 2007 was requested by the University of London to examine the thesis of Saif Gaddafi. The external examiner, Anthony McGrew, has collaborated with [[David Held]] on seven jointly written or co-edited books.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Dstripbooks&field-keywords=held+mcgrew&x=0&y=0 | title = Search results for \"held mcgrew\" | publisher = Amazon.com}}</ref> There is some confusion regarding when the degree itself was awarded. The preface of the dissertation says it was submitted in September, 2007; an LSE press office statement says that the PhD was \"awarded in 2008\"; but David Held is on record as saying Saif Gaddafi \"received his PhD from the LSE in 2009.\"<ref>Saif Al-Islam Alqadhafi, \"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbODMwMmNhYmMtZTVjYS00ODZlLTk4NjItYmJkNjliODQ1MGI2&hl=en The Role of Civil Society in the Democratization of Global Governance Institutions: From 'Soft Power' to Collective Decision-Making?]\" PhD Thesis, London School of Economics, 2008; [http://www2.lse.ac.uk/newsAndMedia/news/archives/2011/03/director_steps_down.aspx; YouTube] \"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ME5GGfU-iPE&feature=player_embedded Saif Gaddafi's Ralph Miliband Lecture],\" May 25, 2010.</ref> What is clear, however, is that the examiners raised concerns at the time of the viva which required revisions to be made and the dissertation to be resubmitted.<ref name=\"Sarkar\">Dipanakar De Sarkar, \"[http://www.hindustantimes.com/Acclaimed-NRIs-in-LSE-Libya-web/Article1-669581.aspx Acclaimed NRIs in LSE-Libya we] b,\" ''Hindustan Times'', 4 March 2011.</ref>\n\nIn the acknowledgements, Gaddafi thanks \"a number of individuals at [[Monitor Group]] with whom I worked to design and conduct the NGO Survey which provides empirical data for this thesis.\"<ref>Saif Al-Islam Alqadhafi, \"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbODMwMmNhYmMtZTVjYS00ODZlLTk4NjItYmJkNjliODQ1MGI2&hl=en The Role of Civil Society in the Democratization of Global Governance Institutions: From 'Soft Power' to Collective Decision-Making?]\" PhD Thesis, London School of Economics, 2008.</ref> This team consisted of Libyan and foreign academics, led by Professor Omran Bukhres, and included Bruce J. Allyn and Flora Rose, a Cambridge graduate who works for the leader of the [[House of Lords]].{{cn|date=April 2020}} When questioned, [[Monitor Group]] admitted to having contributed to the dissertation and acknowledged that such assistance had been a mistake. Our aim, they said, had been to \"help the Gaddafi regime bring about change.\"<ref>Farah Stockman, \"[http://www.boston.com/yourtown/cambridge/articles/2011/03/04/local_consultants_aided_khadafy/ Local consultancy aided Khadafy],\" ''Boston Globe'', 4 March 2011; {{cite news | title = IntellNews.org | date = September 16, 2009 | url = http://intelligencenews.wordpress.com/2009/09/16/01-244/}}</ref> The exact extent of the help provided by the team from [[Monitor Group]] is not established, and neither is it clear whether their contribution is in accordance with the rules of the University of London.<ref>See University of London, \"Regulations for the Degrees of MPhil and PhD,\" item 9.4.4, various years. Cf. Hannes Baumann, \"[http://www.jadaliyya.com/pages/index/916/more-than-a-personal-error-of-judgment_seif-gaddafi-and-the-london-school-of-economics More than a 'Personal Error of Judgment': Seif Gaddafi and the London School of Economics],\" ''Jadaliyya'', 15 March 2010.</ref> In addition, it has been claimed that parts of the dissertation have been plagiarized.<ref>See [http://saifalislamgaddafithesis.wikia.com/wiki/Saif_Al-Islam_Gaddafi_Thesis_Wiki Saif Al-Islam Gaddafi Thesis Wiki]; Dave Stone, \"[http://russian-front.com/2011/02/27/saif-gaddady-ph-d-and-the-london-school-of-economics/ Saif Gaddadi, Ph.D, and the London School of Economics],\" The Russian Front, Feb 27, 2011.</ref>\n\n\"We read the thesis and examined Mr Gaddafi orally for two-and-a-half hours,\" [[Meghnad Desai]] commented, \"at no stage did the supervisors or anyone else suggest to us that plagiarism was suspected and we found no reason to do so ourselves.\"<ref name=\"Sarkar\"/> \"I can hardly be confident that nobody else helped him,\" said [[Nancy Cartwright (philosopher)|Nancy Cartwright]], \"since there's evidence that he lifted bits, but I'm confident that it isn't in the sense done by anybody else start to finish.\"<ref name=\"Owen\">Jonathan Owen, \"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/lse-insider-claims-gaddafi-donation-was-lsquoopenly-joked-aboutrsquo-2240488.html LSE Insider Claims Gaddafi Donation Was \u2018Openly Joked About]\u2019\" ''Independent on Sunday'', 13 March 2011.</ref> \"We take these accusations seriously, of course,\" said Voorhoeve, \"like any accusations of plagiarism.\"<ref name=\"volkskrant.nl\"/>  The claims of plagiarism are to be investigated by the LSE.<ref>{{cite news | title = LSE investigates Gaddafi's son plagiarism claims | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-12608869 | first = Katherine | last = Sellgren | publisher = BBC | date = 1 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to John Christensen who independently tutored Gaddafi in economics, \"Saif lacked the intellectual depth to study at that level, and showed no willingness to read let alone do course work.\"<ref>John Christensen, [http://taxjustice.blogspot.com/2011_02_01_archive.html The Sneer of Cold Command: My Encounter with Saif al-Islam Qadafi], Tax Justice Network, 28 February 2011.</ref>\n\n==Gaddafi donates money to LSE's North Africa Programme==\nEven before Gaddafi had been examined for his PhD, according to a senior LSE source, the Pro-Directors of the School were \"anticipating the solicitation of a donation.\" However no factual evidence has been produced to support this allegation.<ref name=\"Owen\"/> The money eventually arrived in June 2009 when the LSE Council accepted a \u00a31.5 million donation from the [[Gaddafi International Charity and Development Foundation]], of which [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]] was the chairman.<ref name=DM_0303> Held became a trustee in June 2009 but was forced by the LSE Council to resign several months later due to \"potential conflicts of interest.\" Jonathan Owen, \"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/lse-insider-claims-gaddafi-donation-was-lsquoopenly-joked-aboutrsquo-2240488.html LSE Insider Claims Gaddafi Donation Was \u2018Openly Joked About]\u2019\" ''Independent on Sunday'', 13 March 2011.</ref>  This is, said an LSE press release, \"a generous donation from an NGO committed to the promotion of civil society and the development of democracy.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Petition On-line, [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1GnwedNTFtyQQNjTiS00GnCzIRxsnWqtu-WaWgeJDNuQ/edit?hl=sv \"For the LSE to revoke the alumni status of Saif al-Islam Gaddafi and to cease all cooperation with the Libyan regime].\"</ref>\n\nThe donation was used to create a \"North Africa Programme\" which would \"place Libya within the wider context of the region,\" and over time narrow its focus to \"the specific issues and challenges facing Libya.\".<ref name=\"LSEPS\">London School of Economics and Political Science, \"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbZDY4NGUwOTAtN2FkNC00MTUzLWIyZjgtNzdmMjZjYmZmY2Q3&hl=sv North Africa Research Programme, Progress Report 2009-2010],\"</ref> George Joffe, a Senior Fellow of the Centre of International Studies at Cambridge University<ref>[http://www.polis.cam.ac.uk/contacts/staff/joffe-george.html Polis.cam.ac.uk]</ref> was hired as academic advisor to the North Africa Programme.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/feb/28/lse-saif-gaddafi-africa-project Guardian.co.uk]</ref> Professor Joffe was Alia Brahimi's thesis examiner. According to a leaked internal memo, Gaddafi had a direct influence over the research activities of the North Africa Programme. In July 2010, Brahimi met with Gaddafi in Libya and in Greece to \"talk over objectives and expectations\" and to \"agree upon topics for workshops.\"<ref name=\"LSEPS\"/> The memo says that: \"\"The Programme will work with and consult the Gaddafi Foundation on all aspects of the Programme\".<ref>[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbZDY4NGUwOTAtN2FkNC00MTUzLWIyZjgtNzdmMjZjYmZmY2Q3&hl=sv North Africa Research Programme, Progress Report 2009-2010],\"</ref>\nIn addition, the programme commissioned scholars to write papers on various topics relating to North Africa, in return for fees from \u00a35,000 to \u00a310,000.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Nick|publisher=The Observer|date=3 April 2011|title=Lord Woolf's conflict of interest at the LSE|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/apr/03/nick-cohen-lse-libya-lord-woolf|location=London}}</ref>\n\n==LSE planned to train \"Libya's future elite\"==\n\n''[[The Times]]'' reported on 3 March 2011 that the LSE had secured a \u00a32.2 million deal to train hundreds of members of Libya's elite. The School agreed to bring 400 \"future leaders\" from Libya for training in leadership and management, with an additional 250 people due to be trained in Libya itself. The private commercial arrangement was made by Gaddafi.<ref>The Times, 3 March 2011, p. 1 LSE struck \u00a31m deal to train Libya's ruling elite: Embarrassed academics express regret at damage to reputation</ref>\nAccording to [[WikiLeaks]], American diplomats were told in September 2009 by Libya's National Economic Development Board that they were \u201cco-operating with the U.K. government and the London School of Economics, among other U.K. institutions, on an exchange program to send 400 people to London for leadership and management training.\"<ref name=GUTTENPLAN>{{cite news | first = D.D. |last = Guttenplan | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/05/world/europe/05degree.html?_r=1&emc=eta1 | title = London Economics School to Investigate Dealings With Libya | work = The New York Times|date = 5 March 2011}}</ref> Professor [[Francis Terry (cricket player)|Francis Terry]], Dept of Public Management, was academic director for the Libya programme and Julius Sen, LSE Enterprise, the co-director.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/3b69c024-a5f5-11de-8c92-00144feabdc0.html#ixzz1FtYYwHgg | title = Libya turns to LSE}}</ref> Professor Terry described his involvement as \"a very stimulating experience.\" According to press reports, references to the program on LSE's website have subsequently been removed.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23928919-cover-up-claims-after-editing-of-academics-biographies.do | title = Cover-up claims after editing of academics' biographies | date = 4 Mar 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Fred Halliday: \"A Dissenting Note\"==\n{{Main|Human rights in Libya}}\nOn 4 October 2009, [[Fred Halliday]], Emeritus Professor of International Relations at the LSE and the School's leading expert on the Middle East, wrote a memorandum to the LSE Council regarding the proposed cooperation with the Gaddafi Foundation.<ref name=Halliday>Fred Halliday, \"[https://docs.google.com/document/d/1myZyaOqtCqeW0fdvOSPry_55GIOKNVvvqFP0y6l2Ts4/edit?hl=sv# LSE and the Qaddafi Foundation: a Dissenting Note],\" 4 October 2009.</ref> \"I have repeatedly expressed reservations about formal educational and funding links with that country.\"\n\nWhile those in favour of accepting the donation argued that \"Libya is changing internally,\" most informed observers agree that while some of the worst excesses for the moment have ceased, the rights of its people are badly protected. Libya \"remains a country run by a secretive, erratic and corrupt elite.\"<ref>Cf.\"Government control and repression of civil society remain the norm in Libya, with little progress made on promised human rights reforms.\" Human Rights Watch, \"[https://www.scribd.com/doc/48022762/human-rights-watch-world-report-2011 World Report, 2011],\" New York, 2011, p. 562.</ref> Since 9/11 the Libyan government has reached compromises with the West on a number of issues, notably [[Pan Am Flight 103|the Lockerbie bombing]] and nuclear weapons. Yet tactical changes in foreign policy are not sufficient for the purposes of evaluating political and academic links. There are also ways in which Libyan foreign policy has ''not'' changed: the country continues to call for the destruction of Israel; Muammar Gaddafi recently called for the abolition of Switzerland, and he receives the leader of the [[Piracy in Somalia|Somali pirates]] operating off the Horn of Africa as honoured guests of state. Moreover, Libya's handling of the Lockerbie bombing \"has not been characterised by either consistency or clarity,\"\n\nI have in the past, Halliday noted, defended accepting grants from authoritarian regimes such as the Gulf states, \"but there should be clear limits on this, depending on the degree of political and human rights abuses perpetrated with them and on their ongoing foreign policy conduct.\" Whitehall and the City are now happy to do business with Libya, but it does not follow that the LSE should do the same. Responsible leaders throughout the Middle East continue to express reservations regarding Libya, including \"its more prominent 'liberal' representatives.\" We must remember, Halliday concluded, that the \"liberal\" wing within a regime such as Libya does not have the function of producing change but its role is instead \"to reach compromises with internal hard-liners that serve to lessen external pressure.\" A good case in point are the proposals LSE now is considering. It is, as LSE alumni in positions of responsibility in the region caution, \"far too early for the School to take this step.\"<ref name=\"Halliday\" />\n\n==Human Rights Watch criticism==\nIn 2009, [[Human Rights Watch]] was allowed entry to Libya, via [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]]'s non-profit organization in order to gather facts about the human rights situation there.<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/news/2009/12/12/libya-repressive-atmosphere-pockets-improvement Libya: In Repressive Atmosphere, Pockets of Improvement]</ref> While HRW reported that there were concerns about the \"repressive atmosphere,\" they felt there were signs of \"improvement\" and [[Sarah Leah Whitson]], director of HRW's Middle East division said that one should not \"underestimate the importance of the efforts made so far\" by Gaddafi in the realm of human rights in Libya. She also wrote of her official visit that \"the real impetus for the transformation rests squarely with a quasi-governmental organization, the Qaddafi Foundation for International Charities and Development\" chaired by Gaddafi. She praised Gaddafi for establishing the country's two semi-private newspapers, and said \"it is impossible to underestimate the importance of the efforts made so far. Let's hope this spring will last.\"<ref>[https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2009/05/26/tripoli_spring Tripoli Spring - How Libya's behind-the-scenes reformer is actually, well, reforming.]</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, HRW criticised other organisations as well as governments that had previously dealt with Gaddafi. HRW Business and Human Rights Director Arvind Ganesan condemned the London School of Economics (LSE) for allowing \"abusive and corrupt officials or their families to launder their images in exchange for money\". This was later followed by Ganesen saying that \"the London School of Economics did not act until Saif al-Islam's father literally began to kill his own people\". According to [[NGO Monitor]], this was despite the fact that David Held, Co-Director of LSE Global Governance, was partially influenced by Whitson's remarks regarding her Libyan visit, referring to Saif al-Islam Gaddafi as a reformer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.neurope.eu/article/human-rights-watch-slammed-over-anti-israeli-and-pro-gaddafi-reports |title=Human Rights Watch slammed over anti-Israeli and pro-Gaddafi reports |access-date=2013-04-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504104543/http://www.neurope.eu/article/human-rights-watch-slammed-over-anti-israeli-and-pro-gaddafi-reports |archive-date=2013-05-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.opendemocracy.net/david-held/dealing-with-saif-gaddafi-naivety-complicity-or-cautious-engagement Dealing with Saif Gaddafi: naivety, complicity or cautious engagement?]</ref><ref>[http://www.ngo-monitor.org/article.php?id=3605 HRW in 2011: More Balance, Less Credibility]</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, HRW's Whitson admitted that \"Seif Islam in fact abandoned his nascent reform agenda long before.\"<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2011/feb/24/opinion/la-oe-whitson-libya-20110224 Libya: To oust a tyrant]</ref>\n\n==LSE, Libya and BP==\n\n[[Peter Denis Sutherland]], formerly Attorney General of Ireland, European Commissioner, and Head of the World Trade Organisation, finished a 13-year stint as chairman of BP, Europe's largest oil company in early 2010. In Spring 2006 he was appointed Chair of London School of Economics Governors commencing in 2008.\n\nAt the LSE council meeting in 2009 Peter Sutherland declared a conflict of interest when the council decided to accept \u00a31.5 million from a charity headed by Muammar Gaddafi. Sutherland's conflict was that BP had signed an oil deal with Libya two years previously, at a time when Sutherland was chairman of the British oil giant. LSE records show Sutherland took no further role in that part of the June 2009 meeting.<ref>[http://journalist.ie/2011/03/sutherland-declared-libyan-conflict-of-interest-at-lse-meeting/ Journalist.ie]</ref>\n\n==Saif Gaddafi's Ralph Miliband Lecture==\nOn 25 May 2010, [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]] gave a \"Ralph Miliband lecture\" at the LSE, named after [[Ralph Miliband]], a Marxist scholar and former LSE lecturer. Gaddafi spoke on the topic of \"Libya: Past, Present, and Future.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www2.lse.ac.uk/publicEvents/miliband/200910LectureSeries.aspx | title = 2009-2010 lecture series: The Future of Global Capitalism }}</ref> In introducing the speaker, professor [[David Held]] told the audience that \"I have come to know him very well and I must say I have come to like him a great deal.\" He continued:\n\n<blockquote>Saif is committed to resolving contentious international and domestic issues through dialogue, debate and peaceful negotiations. ... Within his own country Saif has spearheaded efforts to open with Islamic militants about the nature and form of their struggle in order to find ways of bringing them back into the political process. ... His success was based on the use of the language of \"soft power,\" that is, the language of dialogue. ... Throughout this time I've come to know Saif as someone who looks to democracy, civil society and deep liberal values for the core of his inspiration.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ME5GGfU-iPE&feature=player_embedded | title = Held and Gadaffi}}</ref><ref>For the audio of the entire lecture, see [[Julia Belluz]], \"[http://www2.macleans.ca/tag/saif-al-islam-alqadhafi/ Gadhafi's Son: Then and Now],\" Macleans, 23 February 2001.</ref></blockquote>\n\nHeld went on to say that he had many tutorials with Saif and that throughout ongoing dialogue on a range of issues they came to agree on some, and to disagree on much.\n\nOn the evening of the lecture, a fight broke out between anti-Gaddafi protesters and pro-Gaddafi supporters. The police were eventually called in to break up the altercation.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23838481-brawl-at-lse-as-libyan-groups-clash-over-gaddafis-sons-speech.do | title = Brawl at LSE as Libyan groups clash over Gaddafi's son's speech | publisher = London Evening Standard | first = Terry | last = Kirby | date = 26 May 2010}}</ref><ref>Google Video, \"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fkd4QVQI47A Brawl at LSE as Libyan groups clash over Gaddafi's son's speech],\"</ref> In a comment on 6 March 2011, [[David Miliband]], Ralph Miliband's elder son and a former UK Foreign Secretary, was critical of the LSE's decision to invite Saif al-Islam Gaddafi:\n<blockquote>The Ralph Miliband Programme at the LSE was founded by a former student of my dad's ... The idea of Saif Gaddafi giving a lecture under his name is just horrific to him and horrific to the whole family obviously,<ref>Emily Ashton, \"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/miliband-anger-over-gaddafi-lecture-2233969.html Miliband Anger over Gadaffi Lecture],\" Independent, 6 March 2011.</ref></blockquote>  There were approximately 30-40 journalists at the event, however reports on the lecture were largely uncritical and did not raise the issues surrounding the LSE engagement with Libya. David Miliband continued his own association with LSE, giving a lecture at LSE on 8 March, two days after the above comments, where he made reference to the school's early history of economic liberalism combined with social justice.<ref>{{cite web|last=Miliband |first=David |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2011/03/centre-parties-social |title=Full Transcript &#124; David Miliband &#124; Speech on the European left &#124; LSE &#124; 8 March 2011 |publisher=Newstatesman.com |date=2011-03-08 |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\nAn open letter by Professor John Keane asks Professor David Held to explain further his links with Libya and to reconsider his reactions. Professor Keane raises several questions, such as: Has the LSE Libya affair not done damage to the scholarly credibility of research programs in the area of democracy? Click here <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://johnkeane.net/52/news/libya-intellectuals-and-democracy-an-open-letter-to-professor-david-held |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-03-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807163134/http://johnkeane.net/52/news/libya-intellectuals-and-democracy-an-open-letter-to-professor-david-held |archive-date=2011-08-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Keane's letter was heavily criticised by those who responded to it in the online magazine in which it was published <http://www.opendemocracy.net/john-keane/libya-intellectuals-and-democracy-open-letter-to-professor-david-held>. Many argued that it was vindictive and overblown. An overview of Halliday and Held - who were both contributors to openDemocracy - with respect to the affair and the larger implications for the independence of UK universities was published by its former editor [http://www.opendemocracy.net/ourkingdom/anthony-barnett/fred-halliday-david-held-lse-and-independence-of-universities Fred Halliday, David Held, the LSE and the independence of universities].\n\nIn October 2011 Held resigned from his post at the LSE in advance of the publication an independent report into the LSE's links with Libya.<ref name=\"Vasagar\"/>\n\nDavid Held issued a personal statement in reaction to the allegations, saying that \"in many discussions and meetings I encouraged the development of [Gaddafi's] reform agenda and subsequently sought to support it through research on the North Africa Programme funded by the Gaddafi International Charity and Development Foundation\" at the LSE.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://roarmagazine.wordpress.com/2011/02/21/david-held-gaddafi-libya-global-governanc/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110227142708/http://roarmagazine.wordpress.com/2011/02/21/david-held-gaddafi-libya-global-governanc/ |archive-date=2011-02-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In October 2011 Held resigned from his post at the LSE,.<ref name=\"Vasagar\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2011/oct/31/saif-gaddafi-lse-academic | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Jeevan | last=Vasagar | title=Academic linked to Gaddafi's fugitive son leaves LSE | date=31 October 2011}}</ref> The [[Harry Woolf, Baron Woolf|Woolf]] report examined links between the LSE and the Libyan regime. The inquiry report says it was Professor Held, who \"first approached Saif about the possibility of funding his centre for Global Governance in December 2008\". This was after the dictator's son had been awarded his PhD by the LSE but before the formal graduation ceremony. The gift offered was of \u00a31.5m in tranches of \u00a3300,000 over a five-year period. Periodic payments were to be made annually. The report says: \"This was not a one-off donation but the founding of a relationship between the school and the donor, which is not unusual. However, bearing in mind the volatility of the Gaddafi regime, the gift involved a substantial risk because of the length of the relationship.\" A decision was made that the gift would not come from Saif directly but from \"private sector sources\". This step \"became essential to Professor Held's presentation of the gift. Unless the money could be shown as coming to the foundation from private sources it could have been seen as unacceptable money from the Libyan state.\"Woolf writes: \"I come to no conclusions as to whether there was or would have been excessive influence by the donor over the use of the funds from Saif's foundation. However, what has been made plain is that proper structures of governance are needed to protect academic integrity against influence from the interests of private donors.\" The funding was accepted despite internal protest. Fred Halliday, a distinguished Middle East expert at the LSE before his death, criticised the donation in a letter that described the country's rulers as a \"secretive, erratic and corrupt elite\". Held was appointed to the board of the Gaddafi foundation on 28 June 2009, a few days after the gift was discussed and accepted by the university's governing body. Held subsequently resigned from the charity on the LSE council's advice.\n\nDespite institutional and procedural criticism the Woolf report, however, exonerated LSE staff (including David Held) stating that they acted in what they believed to be the best interests of the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=418293 |title=LSE's 'mistakes were legion' in Libyan dealings, Woolf finds &#124; Times Higher Education (THE) |publisher=Times Higher Education |date= |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\nQuestions remain, however, about the involvement of elite British academics at the LSE with the Gaddafi regime.\n\n==LSE's video link-up with Gaddafi==\nOn 2 December 2010, in a video-link conference hosted by the LSE, of LSE Global Governance, introduced [[Muammar Gaddafi]] as \"Brother Leader,\" and referred to him as \"the world's longest serving national leader.\"\n<blockquote>I will be chairing this on behalf of Howard Davies, the LSE's Director who unfortunately couldn't make it this evening, but who sends the following message, \u201cYou are most welcome here Colonel Gaddafi. We wish you had been able to deliver some Libyan weather at the same time\u201d -this is the message from Howard Davies -- \u201cWe are pleased to be asked to train Libya officials, and we hope the relationship will continue.\u201d</blockquote>\n\nGaddafi used the occasion to denounce the Lockerbie bombing as a \"fabrication and creation\" of Ronald Reagan and Margaret Thatcher, and revealed that the Libyan national, [[Abdelbaset al-Megrahi]], who was convicted of the bombing and imprisoned in Scotland in 2001, but returned to Libya in 2009 on health grounds, was preparing a multi-million pound compensation claim against Britain for false imprisonment and medical neglect.{{cn|date=April 2020}} At the end of the lecture, Muammar Gaddafi was given a black baseball cap bearing the bright red LSE logo. \"You're in good company,\" he was assured. \"Mandela, Kofi Annan, and Bill Clinton also have them.\"<ref>{{cite news | publisher = The Guardian |date = 1 March 2011 |title = He gave them wisdom. They gave him a baseball cap. Gaddafi's LSE love-in | url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/mar/01/hugh-muir-diary |location=London |first=Hugh |last=Muir}}</ref>\n\n==Saif Gaddafi's \"Rivers of Blood\" speech==\n\nOn 20 February 2011, Saif al-Islam Gaddafi delivered an address to the nation on Libyan state television stating that if no agreement could be found between protesters and the government \"thousands of deaths, and rivers of blood will run through Libya\". He also insisted that his father remained in charge with the army's backing and would \"fight until the last man, the last woman, the last bullet.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eL6I5hktEs0 | title = Al Jazeera English - Saif El Islam Gadaffi addresses the nation - Part 1 of 3 }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 2011, CBS News showed a clip of Gaddafi addressing a group of supporters in Tripoli. Holding a [[Heckler & Koch G36]] assault rifle in the air, he told the crowd that \"weapons are on the way.\"<ref>{{cite web | publisher = CBS News | date = 28 February 2011 | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gqR7zTkiSsg | title= Saif Qaddafi seen rallying supporters }}</ref> A day earlier, Gaddafi had told [[Christiane Amanpour]] in an exclusive interview for ABCNews that the Libyan government \"didn't use force to stay in power,\" and asked her to show him \"a single attack, a single bomb, a single casualty\".<ref>{{cite web | publisher = ABCNews | title = Exclusive Interview with Gadhafi's Sons |url = http://abcnews.go.com/ThisWeek/video/exclusive-interview-gadhafis-sons-13012336}}</ref> On 5 March 2011, he told CNN's [[Nic Robertson]] in [http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/world/2011/03/05/bts.robertson.saif.gadhafi.cnn?hpt=T2 an interview] that his family won't step down: \"I am the government. If we would hold tomorrow election my father would win with a big majority\".<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite news | publisher = CNN | date= 5 March 2011 | title = Moammar Gadhafi's son speaks with CNN | url = http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/world/2011/03/05/bts.robertson.saif.gadhafi.cnn?hpt=T2}}</ref> Saif further told CNN that the world should not worry about the \"200, 300 even 1000 militia...because now everybody is armed in Libya.\"<ref name=\"cnn.com\"/> In an interview with Benjamin Harvey from Bloomberg on 8 March, Gaddafi said that the crisis in Libya was \"a passing cloud. This is an historic opportunity for Libya to become a first-class democratic state.\u201d<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-09/davos-man-qaddafi-jr-fights-for-future-in-civil-rights-u-turn.html | title = Davos Man Qaddafi Jr. Fights for Future in Libya After Civil Rights U-Turn |first = Benjamin | last = Harvey | work=Bloomberg | date=9 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe contrast between his appearance in Tripoli in 2011 and his appearance as a guest speaker at LSE, said the BBC, \"could not have been more stark.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/newsnight/9407335.stm | title = Gaddafi's son Saif's ties to LSE and Britain | work=BBC News | first=Matt | last=Prodger | date=25 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Director Howard Davies resigns==\n[[File:Howard Davies at the World Economic Forum Summit on the Global Agenda 2008.jpg|left|thumb|[[Howard Davies (economist)|Howard Davies]] at the [[World Economic Forum|Davos Summit 2008]]]]\nLSE Director [[Howard Davies (economist)|Howard Davies]] resigned on 3 March over the scandal.<ref name=Davies>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/education/2011/mar/03/lse-director-resigns-gaddafi-scandal | title = LSE head quits over Gaddafi scandal | publisher = The Guardian | location=London | first1=Jeevan | last1=Vasagar | first2=Rajeev | last2=Syal | date=4 March 2011}}</ref> In a comment Davies said he had left the job because of \"two errors of judgment\": 1) his advice that a donation from Gaddafi's foundation was acceptable, and 2) his decision to act as a financial adviser to the Libyan government.<ref name=\"lse-libya-anthony-giddens-gaddafi\"/> Davies acknowledged in his resignation letter that it would \u201cbe right for me to step down, even though I know that this will cause difficulty for the institution I have come to love.\u201d He added, \u201cThe short point is that I am responsible for the school\u2019s reputation, and that has suffered.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | url = https://docs.google.com/document/d/115dQVYUdxoJRvRTsl8uYL9xe9WTp7QUbLBryMRzKqmI/edit?hl=sv# | title = Howard Davies' Letter of Resignation | publisher = The Guardian |date = 6 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn a statement the LSE's Board of Governors accepted Howard's resignation with \"great regret.\"<ref name=Davies/> [[Raheem Kassam]], from the 'Student Rights' group, called for the Libyan money to be donated to a charity to assist Gaddafi's victims.<ref>Jonny Paul [http://www.jpost.com/International/Article.aspx?id=209449 \"LSE suspends study program financed by Gaddafi\u2019s son\"], ''The Jerusalem Post'', 23 February 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=The Sunday Times |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/Politics/article565598.ece |title=Replay: Sunday politics Q&A with Robert Halfon MP |publisher=The Sunday Times |date=2011-02-27 |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\n[[Colin Talbot]], who holds a PhD degree from the LSE and is currently the Chair of Public Policy and Management at Manchester Business School, told UTv News on 4 March 2011 that Howard Davies should not be blamed for carrying out what amounted to \"British diplomatic strategy\".<ref name=\"u.tv\">{{cite news | publisher = UTvNews | title = British government encouraged LSE to forge Libya links, says academic | date = 4 March 2011 | url = http://www.u.tv/News/British-government-encouraged-LSE-to-forge-Libya-links-says-academic/6c296027-fffb-43e3-89c2-097dd9cc9188}}</ref> Talbot, who also taught on the LSE's Libya program further said that Davies was not the only person responsible for tarnishing the university's reputation, because the British government had encouraged Davies to establish close ties to the Gaddafi family.<ref name=\"u.tv\"/>\n\nThe LSE said in a statement on 21 February 2011, that its engagement with the Libyan authorities has already finished or has been stopped following recent events in the country. The School said no more of the \u00a31.5m donation would be accepted. About half of the \u00a3300,000 already accepted had been spent and the LSE Council would next consider what to do with the remaining funds, taking into account the views of LSE students.<ref name=Sellgren2>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-12550876 | title = Gaddafi funds prompt LSE students' protest | first = Katherine | last = Sellgren | date = 23 February 2011 | publisher = BBC }}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2011, Professor [[Judith Rees]] was appointed interim- director. Reese was pro director of the School from 1998 to 2004, and is currently director of the Grantham Research Institute on Climate Change and the Environment at LSE.\n\n==LSE reactions==\n\n===Students===\n\nSeveral protest actions were undertaken by LSE students in the response to the affair, including sit-ins and demonstrations. The students have insisted that LSE repay the donation from Gaddafi's foundation and revoke Gaddafi's status as LSE alumnus. The donation had originally been welcomed by the then-General Secretary of LSE Students Union, Aled Fisher, in June 2009, as \"exactly the kind of donation\" the School should be encouraging.\"<ref name=Sellgren2/> Fisher said he was \"taken out of context\" and LSE officials \"withheld pertinent facts about Saif Gaddafi\u2019s role in the state, which... would have made Council and I look differently on the issue,\" with Charlotte Gerada, General Secretary in 2011, stating it was \"unacceptable\" that LSE \"used\" Fisher \"as a scapegoat.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebeaveronline.co.uk/2011/03/08/former-gensec%E2%80%99s-email-%E2%80%9Ctaken-out-of-context%E2%80%9D/ |title=Germyx \u2013 Recenzii profesionale, la cele mai bune produse \u0219i servicii online |publisher=Thebeaveronline.co.uk |date=2019-06-26 |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\nIn an on-line petition, present and former LSE students urged the School to revoke Gaddafi's status as alumnus and to cease all cooperation with the Libyan regime. \"We were shocked to find out that the LSE has accepted a \u00a31.5 million donation from the Gaddafi International Charity and Development Foundation; an NGO headed by Gaddafi's son, Saif al-Islam Gaddafi.... We are astonished that the donation was accepted in the first place.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Faculty===\n[[File:Meghnad Desai 1980s.jpg|thumb|right|[[Meghnad Desai|Lord Desai]], co-founder, LSE Global Governance]]\n\nProfessor [[Meghnad Desai]], defended LSE's actions, arguing that \"Academic research needs money \u2014 Rockefeller was a robber baron once, but we take his money\".<ref>''New York Times'', \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/02/world/europe/02degree.html A London University Wrestles With a Qaddafi Gift],\" 1 March 2011.</ref> \"It was only after bullets started flying in Libya that Saif Gaddafi was found to have cheated. Nor had anyone until then objected that the LSE had received a donation from Saif Gaddafi's Foundation.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/mar/04/lse-heavy-price-saif-gaddafis-phd | title = LSE is paying a heavy price for Saif Gaddafi's PhD | first = Meghnad | last = Desai | location=London | work=The Guardian | date=4 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nProfessor [[David Held]] issued a statement saying that \"in many discussions and meetings I encouraged the development of Gaddafi's reform agenda and subsequently sought to support it through research on the North Africa Programme funded by the Gaddafi International Charity and Development Foundation.\"<ref>{{cite news| url = http://roarmagazine.wordpress.com/2011/02/21/david-held-gaddafi-libya-global-governanc/ | title = Personal Statement by David Held on Gaddafi\u2019s LSE Donation}}</ref>\n\nSaif Gaddafi, said [[Alex Voorhoeve]], \"seemed genuinely moved by the desire to study democratic ideals and practice and my colleagues had therefore hoped he would have a liberalizing influence on the Libyan regime. ... I had hoped that at such a crucial moment, he would defend the democratic ideals that he wrote about in his thesis.<ref name=\"volkskrant.nl\"/></blockquote>\n\nThese reactions were echoed by [[Alia Brahimi]], who claimed to be \"tremendously surprised\" by Saif Gaddafi's \"Rivers of Blood Speech.\"  Saif Gaddafi, she said, had been a reformer for many years but now \"seemed to be backpeddling\".<ref>{{cite news| publisher = Al-Jazeera | date = 24 February 2011 | title = Libya's power struggle: In a country divided by tribal alliances, who holds the future of the country in their hands? | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/programmes/insidestory/2011/02/2011224161551594815.html}}</ref> \"I\u2019ve got nothing to apologise for. Saif told me he was keen that democratic reform should happen soon in Libya.\"<ref name=DM_0303/>\n\n[[Henning Mayer]], a former employee of David Held, defended the decision to accept Gaddafi's money saying it was made based on information available at the time.<ref>Henning Mayer, 14 March 2011 The LSE Libya Crisis: A Statement in Support of David Held [http://www.social-europe.eu/2011/03/the-lse%E2%80%99s-libya-crisis-a-statement-in-support-of-david-held/ social-europe.eu]</ref>\n\nIn a statement [[Fred Halliday]]'s wife said she recalled that her late husband had been opposed to accepting Gaddafi as a student.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/feb/21/saif-al-islam-gaddafi | title = Saif al-Islam Gaddafi: LSE-educated man the west can no longer deal with | date = 21 February 2011 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first1=Ian | last1=Cobain | first2=Amelia | last2=Hill}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Financial Times'' reported on 3 March 2011, that the LSE had started to edit official university websites in an attempt to \"remove references to Libyan links from its academics\u2019 workplace biographies\".<ref>{{cite news | publisher = Financial Times | title = LSE websites edited to remove Libyan ties | date= 3 March 2011 | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/37dcc23e-45e1-11e0-acd8-00144feab49a.html#axzz1FgzZHpiu}}</ref>\n\n[[Shami Chakrabarti]], director of Liberty had also faced criticism over the affair, due to her position on the governing council of LSE. The \"Students Rights\" organisation accused her of hypocrisy \"for being \"the director of a human rights group while legitimizing murderous regimes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/International/LSE-head-resigns-over-Libya-link |title=LSE head resigns over Libya link - World News - Jerusalem Post |publisher=Jpost.com |date=2011-03-06 |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref> She later admitted her embarrassment and shame about the Gaddafi affair and finally in April 2013 Chakrabarti's spokesman confirmed that she had severed all links with The LSE.<ref>{{cite web|last=Walker |first=Tim |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/9995673/Shami-Chakrabarti-disowns-the-LSE.html |title=Shami Chakrabarti disowns the LSE |publisher=Telegraph |date=2013-04-16 |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\n==Lord Woolf Inquiry==\n\nOn 3 March 2011, LSE announced that they had set up an independent external inquiry into the School's relationship with the Libyan regime, to be conducted by the former lord chief justice [[Harry Woolf, Baron Woolf|Harry Woolf]].<ref name=Davies/> Lord Woolf is to conduct\n<blockquote>An independent inquiry to establish the full facts of the School\u2019s links with Libya, whether there have been errors made, and to establish clear guidelines for international donations to and links with the School. Lord Woolf is to make recommendations to the LSE Council as soon as possible. He is to have total discretion as to how he conducts the inquiry, and as to the matters on which he is to report.<ref>[http://woolflse.com/ Lord Woolf\u2019s Inquiry into the LSE and Libya] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318132926/http://www.woolflse.com/ |date=2012-03-18 }}.</ref></blockquote>\nThe Woolf report was published on 30 November 2011.  Woolf summarised his central conclusion as\n<blockquote>The School established, in an incremental and piecemeal fashion, a relationship with Libya. Before a global company embarks upon a relationship with a foreign partner, a due diligence assessment should be conducted. No similar exercise took place in this case. The links were allowed to grow, unchecked and to a degree unnoticed, until their effect was overwhelming. In October 2009, the LSE\u2019s Council resolved that the links should be monitored carefully in future. That monitoring came too late. By October 2009 the relationship with Libya had been well established. In addition, the history of the developing connection between the LSE and Libya has exposed a disconcerting number of failures in communication and governance within the School. The errors which I detail in the remaining chapters of this Report exceed those that should have occurred in an institution of the LSE\u2019s distinction. The pattern is such that I am driven to the central conclusion that there were shortcomings in the governance structure and management at the LSE.<ref>[http://woolflse.com/dl/woolf-lse-report.pdf Woolf Inquiry p22]</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Other universities with Libyan links==\n\nOn 19 May 2009, the French-language journal Jeune Afrique published an investigative report on the Gaddafi family's public relations campaign set up by Monitor. Titled 'Gaddafi: Mirror, Mirror, Tell Me Who is the Most Handsome'<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/Article/ARTJAJA2522p050-051.xml0/ Jeuneafrique.com]</ref> the article detailed how the Monitor group had been organizing visits to Libya by leading academics from US-and UK-based universities in order to meet Gaddafi the 'thinker and intellectual'.  In addition to Michael Porter from the Harvard Business School, [[Francis Fukuyama]], Professor of International Political Economy at Johns Hopkins University, lobbyist [[Richard Perle]], as well as [[Robert Putnam]] from Harvard University traveled to Tripoli to meet Gaddafi.<ref>[http://www.u.tv/News/British-government-encouraged-LSE-to-forge-Libya-links-says-academic/6c296027-fffb-43e3-89c2-097dd9cc9188 U.tv]</ref> All the meetings had been organized by the Monitor group.<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/Article/ARTJAJA2522p050-051.xml0/ Jeunafrique.com]</ref>\n\nIn the context of the scandal over LSE's Libya connections, it emerged that also [[Michigan State University]] had established a program to train future Libyan leaders. [[Moussa Koussa]], Libya's foreign minister and the second most powerful man in Libya after the Gaddafi family{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} received a master's degree in Sociology from Michigan State in 1978.<ref>[http://www.commentarymagazine.com/2011/03/04/london-school-of-economicss-ties-to-libya-the-tip-of-the-iceberg-for-academia/ Commentarymagazine.com]</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, the Guardian claimed that the [[University of St Andrews]] Centre for Syrian Studies received funding from businessman [[Ayman Asfari]] who was alleged to have links to the Syrian government led by [[Bashar al-Assad]].  However, it later transpired that Mr Asfari had no links to the Syrian government and the Guardian issued an apology to him in print in July; no such apology was issued to the University.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2011/apr/27/syrian-funding-st-andrews-university | location=London | work=The Guardian | first1=Peter | last1=Beaumont | first2=Jeevan | last2=Vasagar | title=St Andrews University,Higher education (Universities etc.),Education,Syria (News),Middle East (News),World news,UK news,Arab and Middle East unrest (News) | date=27 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lse.ac.uk London School of Economics and Political Science], official web site.\n* [http://www.monitor.com Monitor Group], official web site.\n* [http://www.gicdf.org/ Gaddafi International Foundation For Charity and Development], official web site.\n* Fred Halliday, [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1myZyaOqtCqeW0fdvOSPry_55GIOKNVvvqFP0y6l2Ts4/edit?hl=sv \"LSE: and the Qaddafi Foundation: A Dissenting Note\"], October 4, 2009.\n* Saif Al-Islam Alqadhafi, \"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbODMwMmNhYmMtZTVjYS00ODZlLTk4NjItYmJkNjliODQ1MGI2&hl=en The Role of Civil Society in the Democratization of Global Governance Institutions: From 'Soft Power' to Collective Decision-Making?]\" PhD Thesis, London School of Economics, 2008.\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1GnwedNTFtyQQNjTiS00GnCzIRxsnWqtu-WaWgeJDNuQ/edit?pli=1&hl=sv# \"For the LSE to Revoke the Alumni Status of Saif al-Islam Gaddafi and to Cease All Cooperation with the Libyan Regime,\"].\n* Human Rights Watch, \"[https://www.scribd.com/doc/48022762/human-rights-watch-world-report-2011 World Report, 2011], New York, 2011, pp.&nbsp;562\u2013567.\n* [http://woolflse.com/dl/woolf-lse-report.pdf The Woolf Inquiry: An inquiry into the LSE\u2019s links with Libya and lessons to be learned], October 2011.\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1guh8qHNi3uJswPurGqQksa2eTfIZc--GQAyw0V3sFwg/edit?hl=en# LSE Libya Links: A Short Bibliography]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lse Libya Links}}\n[[Category:London School of Economics|Gaddafi links]]\n[[Category:Gaddafi family]]\n[[Category:Academic scandals]]\n[[Category:Libya\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n", "text_old": "The '''LSE\u2013Gaddafi affair''' was a scandal in the [[United Kingdom]] that occurred as a result of relationship that existed between the [[London School of Economics]] (LSE) and the [[Libya]]n government and its leader [[Muammar Gaddafi]] and his son [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]]. The NGO Gaddafi Foundation pledged to donate \u00a31.5 million over five years to a research centre, LSE Global Governance, of which \u00a3300k were paid. In addition, LSE Enterprise established a contract worth \u00a32.2 million to train Libyan officials. In 2008, the LSE granted a PhD degree<ref>[http://www2.lse.ac.uk/newsAndMedia/news/archives/2011/03/director_steps_down.aspx LSE.ac.uk]</ref> to [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]], the son of the Libyan leader, for a dissertation. Currently, allegations circulate that Gaddafi's thesis was ghost-written and/or plagiarised. In December 2010, [[Muammar Gaddafi]] addressed members of the School in a video link-up where he was addressed as \"Brother Leader\" and received an LSE cap previously given to [[Nelson Mandela]].\nAt the time of the [[2011 Libyan Civil War]], the relationship between the LSE and the Gaddafi regime, and the conduct of individual members of LSE's staff was called into question.<ref>See, for example, {{cite news | first = Nick | last = Cohen | publisher = The Spectator|date = 3 March 2011| title = Why Howard Davies had to resign | url = http://www.spectator.co.uk/nickcohen/6751678/why-howard-davies-had-to-resign.thtml}}; ''Wall Street Journal,'' \"[https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB10001424052748703362804576184773979915688?mod=googlenews_wsj Institutions Scramble to Check on Libya Ties],\" 6 March 2011.</ref> As a result of the scandal, the LSE's Director, Sir [[Howard Davies (economist)|Howard Davies]], resigned on 3 March 2011, citing \"errors of judgement\".<ref>{{cite news | first = Gregory |last = White |title = The Latest Qaddafi Casualty Is The Head Of The London School Of Economics |url = http://www.businessinsider.com/howard-davies-lse-qadaffi-2011-3 | publisher = Business Insider }}</ref> In a ''New York Times'' op-ed piece on 7 March 2011, [[Roger Cohen]] wrote, in reference to events that had transpired at the School, \"It may be possible to sink to greater depths but right now I can't think how. ...The [[Arab Spring]] is also a Western Winter. ...How did we back, use and encourage the brutality of Arab dictators over so many years? To what degree did that cynical encouragement of despots foster the very jihadist rage Western societies sought to curb?\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/08/opinion/08iht-edcohen08.html Libyan Closure],\" ''New York Times'', 7 March 2011.</ref>\n\n==LSE and the Monitor Group==\n{{Main|Monitor Group}}\n[[File:Muammar al-Gaddafi, 12th AU Summit, 090202-N-0506A-324.jpg|thumb|right|[[Muammar Gaddafi]] at the [[African Union]] meeting, February 2009.]]\n[[File:LondonSchoolofEconomics cford.jpg|thumb|The London School of Economics]]\nIn 2004 Libya's government engaged [[Monitor Group]], a Boston-based, Harvard-linked, consultancy firm founded by Harvard Business School professor Mark Fuller, as advisors on matters of public relations.<ref>Michael Richardson, \"Monitor Group Touted for Muammar Khadafy over Torture of Bulgarian Nurses,\" 11 March 2011.</ref> According to leaked documents, [[Monitor Group]] received \u00a32 million \"in order to enhance international understanding and appreciation of Libya and the contribution it has made and may continue to make to its region and to the world.\" In addition, \"the goal is to introduce [[Muammar Gaddafi]] as a thinker and intellectual, independent of his more widely known and very public persona as the Leader of the Revolution in Libya.\"<ref>Mother Jones</ref>\n\nA number of Harvard University academics were active within Monitor.{{who|date=January 2012}}\n\nOne way to achieve this aim was to recruit prominent journalists and intellectuals who were prepared to travel to Libya and write in positive terms about the country.<ref name=\"lse-libya-anthony-giddens-gaddafi\"/> One prime target was academics associated with the LSE, such as professor [[Anthony Giddens]] (Giddens is a Fellow of King's College Cambridge and is an Emeritus professor at LSE). In 2006 and 2007 the company organized two trips to Libya for Giddens, when the former LSE Director met with [[Muammar Gaddafi]]. Giddens has declined to comment on the financial compensation he received on these occasions.<ref name=\"lse-libya-anthony-giddens-gaddafi\">{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/education/2011/mar/04/lse-libya-anthony-giddens-gaddafi | title = Anthony Giddens' trip to see Gaddafi vetted by Libyan intelligence chief | publisher= The Guardian | location=London | first1=Rajeev | last1=Syal | first2=Jeevan | last2=Vasagar | date=5 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nGiddens' first visit to Libya resulted in articles in the ''[[New Statesman]]'', ''[[El Pa\u00eds]]'' and ''[[La Repubblica]]'', where he argued that Libya had been transformed. In the ''New Statesman'' he wrote: \"Gaddafi's 'conversion' may have been driven partly by the wish to escape sanctions, but I get the strong sense it is authentic and there is a lot of motive power behind it. [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi|Saif Gaddafi]] is a driving force behind the rehabilitation and potential modernisation of Libya. Gaddafi Sr, however, is authorising these processes.\"<ref>Anthony Giddens, \"[http://www.newstatesman.com/200608280032 The Colonel and His Third Way],\" ''New Statesman'', August 28, 2006.</ref>  During the second visit, [[Monitor Group]] organized a panel of \"three thinkers\" \u2014 Giddens, Gaddafi, and [[Benjamin Barber]], Emeritus professor of Rutgers University, author of the book ''Jihad vs. McWorld'' \u2014 chaired by the veteran journalist Sir [[David Frost]].<ref>Mother;s Jones</ref> Returning from Libya, Giddens wrote about his \"chat with the colonel,\" in the ''Guardian'', concluding that \"If Gadafy is sincere about reform, as I think he is, Libya could end up as the Norway of North Africa.\"<ref>Anthony Giddens, \"[https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2007/mar/09/comment.libya?CMP=twt_gu My Chat with the Colonel],\" ''The Guardian'', 9 March 2007.</ref>\n\n==LSE grants PhD degree to Saif Gaddafi==\n\nIn 2008, Muammar Gaddafi's son, [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]], received a PhD from the Department of Philosophy at the LSE with a dissertation entitled \"The Role of Civil Society in the Democratization of Global Governance Institutions: From 'Soft Power' to Collective Decision-Making?\"<ref name=\"Islam Gaddafi 2009\">Saif al-Islam Alqadhafi, \"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbODMwMmNhYmMtZTVjYS00ODZlLTk4NjItYmJkNjliODQ1MGI2&hl=en The Role of Civil Society in the Democratization of Global Governance Institutions: From 'Soft Power' to Collective Decision-Making?]\" PhD Thesis, London School of Economics, submitted in September 2007.</ref> His supervisor was [[Nancy Cartwright (philosopher)|Nancy Cartwright]], a distinguished philosopher of science, and [[Alex Voorhoeve]], a political philosopher, advised on chapter 4 and the first half of chapter 5.<ref name=\"volkskrant.nl\">Jonathan Witteman, \"[http://www.volkskrant.nl/vk/nl/4936/Buitenland/article/detail/1851463/2011/02/24/Zoon-Kadhafi-schreef-dissertatie-over-democratie-en-pleegde-plagiaat.dhtml Zoon Kadhafi schreef dissertatie over democratie 'en pleegde plagiaat'],\" ''de Volkskrant'', 24 February 2011.</ref> In the text [[David Held]] is acknowledged as having \"directly advised\" the work.<ref name=\"Islam Gaddafi 2009\"/> One of the two examiners, Lord Meghnad Desai, the founder of LSE Global Governance, had retired from LSE in 2003 and in 2007 was requested by the University of London to examine the thesis of Saif Gaddafi. The external examiner, Anthony McGrew, has collaborated with [[David Held]] on seven jointly written or co-edited books.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.amazon.com/s/ref=nb_sb_noss?url=search-alias%3Dstripbooks&field-keywords=held+mcgrew&x=0&y=0 | title = Search results for \"held mcgrew\" | publisher = Amazon.com}}</ref> There is some confusion regarding when the degree itself was awarded. The preface of the dissertation says it was submitted in September, 2007; an LSE press office statement says that the PhD was \"awarded in 2008\"; but David Held is on record as saying Saif Gaddafi \"received his PhD from the LSE in 2009.\"<ref>Saif Al-Islam Alqadhafi, \"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbODMwMmNhYmMtZTVjYS00ODZlLTk4NjItYmJkNjliODQ1MGI2&hl=en The Role of Civil Society in the Democratization of Global Governance Institutions: From 'Soft Power' to Collective Decision-Making?]\" PhD Thesis, London School of Economics, 2008; [http://www2.lse.ac.uk/newsAndMedia/news/archives/2011/03/director_steps_down.aspx; YouTube] \"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ME5GGfU-iPE&feature=player_embedded Saif Gaddafi's Ralph Miliband Lecture],\" May 25, 2010.</ref> What is clear, however, is that the examiners raised concerns at the time of the viva which required revisions to be made and the dissertation to be resubmitted.<ref name=\"Sarkar\">Dipanakar De Sarkar, \"[http://www.hindustantimes.com/Acclaimed-NRIs-in-LSE-Libya-web/Article1-669581.aspx Acclaimed NRIs in LSE-Libya we] b,\" ''Hindustan Times'', 4 March 2011.</ref>\n\nIn the acknowledgements, Gaddafi thanks \"a number of individuals at [[Monitor Group]] with whom I worked to design and conduct the NGO Survey which provides empirical data for this thesis.\"<ref>Saif Al-Islam Alqadhafi, \"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbODMwMmNhYmMtZTVjYS00ODZlLTk4NjItYmJkNjliODQ1MGI2&hl=en The Role of Civil Society in the Democratization of Global Governance Institutions: From 'Soft Power' to Collective Decision-Making?]\" PhD Thesis, London School of Economics, 2008.</ref> This team consisted of Libyan and foreign academics, led by Professor Omran Bukhres, and included Bruce J. Allyn and Flora Rose, a Cambridge graduate who works for the leader of the [[House of Lords]].{{cn|date=April 2020}} When questioned, [[Monitor Group]] admitted to having contributed to the dissertation and acknowledged that such assistance had been a mistake. Our aim, they said, had been to \"help the Gaddafi regime bring about change.\"<ref>Farah Stockman, \"[http://www.boston.com/yourtown/cambridge/articles/2011/03/04/local_consultants_aided_khadafy/ Local consultancy aided Khadafy],\" ''Boston Globe'', 4 March 2011; {{cite news | title = IntellNews.org | date = September 16, 2009 | url = http://intelligencenews.wordpress.com/2009/09/16/01-244/}}</ref> The exact extent of the help provided by the team from [[Monitor Group]] is not established, and neither is it clear whether their contribution is in accordance with the rules of the University of London.<ref>See University of London, \"Regulations for the Degrees of MPhil and PhD,\" item 9.4.4, various years. Cf. Hannes Baumann, \"[http://www.jadaliyya.com/pages/index/916/more-than-a-personal-error-of-judgment_seif-gaddafi-and-the-london-school-of-economics More than a 'Personal Error of Judgment': Seif Gaddafi and the London School of Economics],\" ''Jadaliyya'', 15 March 2010.</ref> In addition, it has been claimed that parts of the dissertation have been plagiarized.<ref>See [http://saifalislamgaddafithesis.wikia.com/wiki/Saif_Al-Islam_Gaddafi_Thesis_Wiki Saif Al-Islam Gaddafi Thesis Wiki]; Dave Stone, \"[http://russian-front.com/2011/02/27/saif-gaddady-ph-d-and-the-london-school-of-economics/ Saif Gaddadi, Ph.D, and the London School of Economics],\" The Russian Front, Feb 27, 2011.</ref>\n\n\"We read the thesis and examined Mr Gaddafi orally for two-and-a-half hours,\" [[Meghnad Desai]] commented, \"at no stage did the supervisors or anyone else suggest to us that plagiarism was suspected and we found no reason to do so ourselves.\"<ref name=\"Sarkar\"/> \"I can hardly be confident that nobody else helped him,\" said [[Nancy Cartwright (philosopher)|Nancy Cartwright]], \"since there's evidence that he lifted bits, but I'm confident that it isn't in the sense done by anybody else start to finish.\"<ref name=\"Owen\">Jonathan Owen, \"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/lse-insider-claims-gaddafi-donation-was-lsquoopenly-joked-aboutrsquo-2240488.html LSE Insider Claims Gaddafi Donation Was \u2018Openly Joked About]\u2019\" ''Independent on Sunday'', 13 March 2011.</ref> \"We take these accusations seriously, of course,\" said Voorhoeve, \"like any accusations of plagiarism.\"<ref name=\"volkskrant.nl\"/>  The claims of plagiarism are to be investigated by the LSE.<ref>{{cite news | title = LSE investigates Gaddafi's son plagiarism claims | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-12608869 | first = Katherine | last = Sellgren | publisher = BBC | date = 1 March 2011 }}</ref>\n\nAccording to John Christensen who independently tutored Gaddafi in economics, \"Saif lacked the intellectual depth to study at that level, and showed no willingness to read let alone do course work.\"<ref>John Christensen, [http://taxjustice.blogspot.com/2011_02_01_archive.html The Sneer of Cold Command: My Encounter with Saif al-Islam Qadafi], Tax Justice Network, 28 February 2011.</ref>\n\n==Gaddafi donates money to LSE's North Africa Programme==\nEven before Gaddafi had been examined for his PhD, according to a senior LSE source, the Pro-Directors of the School were \"anticipating the solicitation of a donation.\" However no factual evidence has been produced to support this allegation.<ref name=\"Owen\"/> The money eventually arrived in June 2009 when the LSE Council accepted a \u00a31.5 million donation from the [[Gaddafi International Charity and Development Foundation]], of which [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]] was the chairman.<ref name=DM_0303> Held became a trustee in June 2009 but was forced by the LSE Council to resign several months later due to \"potential conflicts of interest.\" Jonathan Owen, \"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/lse-insider-claims-gaddafi-donation-was-lsquoopenly-joked-aboutrsquo-2240488.html LSE Insider Claims Gaddafi Donation Was \u2018Openly Joked About]\u2019\" ''Independent on Sunday'', 13 March 2011.</ref>  This is, said an LSE press release, \"a generous donation from an NGO committed to the promotion of civil society and the development of democracy.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Petition On-line, [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1GnwedNTFtyQQNjTiS00GnCzIRxsnWqtu-WaWgeJDNuQ/edit?hl=sv \"For the LSE to revoke the alumni status of Saif al-Islam Gaddafi and to cease all cooperation with the Libyan regime].\"</ref>\n\nThe donation was used to create a \"North Africa Programme\" which would \"place Libya within the wider context of the region,\" and over time narrow its focus to \"the specific issues and challenges facing Libya.\".<ref name=\"LSEPS\">London School of Economics and Political Science, \"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbZDY4NGUwOTAtN2FkNC00MTUzLWIyZjgtNzdmMjZjYmZmY2Q3&hl=sv North Africa Research Programme, Progress Report 2009-2010],\"</ref> George Joffe, a Senior Fellow of the Centre of International Studies at Cambridge University<ref>[http://www.polis.cam.ac.uk/contacts/staff/joffe-george.html Polis.cam.ac.uk]</ref> was hired as academic advisor to the North Africa Programme.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/feb/28/lse-saif-gaddafi-africa-project Guardian.co.uk]</ref> Professor Joffe was Alia Brahimi's thesis examiner. According to a leaked internal memo, Gaddafi had a direct influence over the research activities of the North Africa Programme. In July 2010, Brahimi met with Gaddafi in Libya and in Greece to \"talk over objectives and expectations\" and to \"agree upon topics for workshops.\"<ref name=\"LSEPS\"/> The memo says that: \"\"The Programme will work with and consult the Gaddafi Foundation on all aspects of the Programme\".<ref>[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbZDY4NGUwOTAtN2FkNC00MTUzLWIyZjgtNzdmMjZjYmZmY2Q3&hl=sv North Africa Research Programme, Progress Report 2009-2010],\"</ref>\nIn addition, the programme commissioned scholars to write papers on various topics relating to North Africa, in return for fees from \u00a35,000 to \u00a310,000.<ref>{{cite news|last=Cohen|first=Nick|publisher=The Observer|date=3 April 2011|title=Lord Woolf's conflict of interest at the LSE|url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/apr/03/nick-cohen-lse-libya-lord-woolf|location=London}}</ref>\n\n==LSE planned to train \"Libya's future elite\"==\n\n''[[The Times]]'' reported on 3 March 2011 that the LSE had secured a \u00a32.2 million deal to train hundreds of members of Libya's elite. The School agreed to bring 400 \"future leaders\" from Libya for training in leadership and management, with an additional 250 people due to be trained in Libya itself. The private commercial arrangement was made by Gaddafi.<ref>The Times, 3 March 2011, p. 1 LSE struck \u00a31m deal to train Libya's ruling elite: Embarrassed academics express regret at damage to reputation</ref>\nAccording to [[WikiLeaks]], American diplomats were told in September 2009 by Libya's National Economic Development Board that they were \u201cco-operating with the U.K. government and the London School of Economics, among other U.K. institutions, on an exchange program to send 400 people to London for leadership and management training.\"<ref name=GUTTENPLAN>{{cite news | first = D.D. |last = Guttenplan | url = https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/05/world/europe/05degree.html?_r=1&emc=eta1 | title = London Economics School to Investigate Dealings With Libya | work = The New York Times|date = 5 March 2011}}</ref> Professor [[Francis Terry (cricket player)|Francis Terry]], Dept of Public Management, was academic director for the Libya programme and Julius Sen, LSE Enterprise, the co-director.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/3b69c024-a5f5-11de-8c92-00144feabdc0.html#ixzz1FtYYwHgg | title = Libya turns to LSE}}</ref> Professor Terry described his involvement as \"a very stimulating experience.\" According to press reports, references to the program on LSE's website have subsequently been removed.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23928919-cover-up-claims-after-editing-of-academics-biographies.do | title = Cover-up claims after editing of academics' biographies | date = 4 Mar 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Fred Halliday: \"A Dissenting Note\"==\n{{Main|Human rights in Libya}}\nOn 4 October 2009, [[Fred Halliday]], Emeritus Professor of International Relations at the LSE and the School's leading expert on the Middle East, wrote a memorandum to the LSE Council regarding the proposed cooperation with the Gaddafi Foundation.<ref name=Halliday>Fred Halliday, \"[https://docs.google.com/document/d/1myZyaOqtCqeW0fdvOSPry_55GIOKNVvvqFP0y6l2Ts4/edit?hl=sv# LSE and the Qaddafi Foundation: a Dissenting Note],\" 4 October 2009.</ref> \"I have repeatedly expressed reservations about formal educational and funding links with that country.\"\n\nWhile those in favour of accepting the donation argued that \"Libya is changing internally,\" most informed observers agree that while some of the worst excesses for the moment have ceased, the rights of its people are badly protected. Libya \"remains a country run by a secretive, erratic and corrupt elite.\"<ref>Cf.\"Government control and repression of civil society remain the norm in Libya, with little progress made on promised human rights reforms.\" Human Rights Watch, \"[https://www.scribd.com/doc/48022762/human-rights-watch-world-report-2011 World Report, 2011],\" New York, 2011, p. 562.</ref> Since 9/11 the Libyan government has reached compromises with the West on a number of issues, notably [[Pan Am Flight 103|the Lockerbie bombing]] and nuclear weapons. Yet tactical changes in foreign policy are not sufficient for the purposes of evaluating political and academic links. There are also ways in which Libyan foreign policy has ''not'' changed: the country continues to call for the destruction of Israel; Muammar Gaddafi recently called for the abolition of Switzerland, and he receives the leader of the [[Piracy in Somalia|Somali pirates]] operating off the Horn of Africa as honoured guests of state. Moreover, Libya's handling of the Lockerbie bombing \"has not been characterised by either consistency or clarity,\"\n\nI have in the past, Halliday noted, defended accepting grants from authoritarian regimes such as the Gulf states, \"but there should be clear limits on this, depending on the degree of political and human rights abuses perpetrated with them and on their ongoing foreign policy conduct.\" Whitehall and the City are now happy to do business with Libya, but it does not follow that the LSE should do the same. Responsible leaders throughout the Middle East continue to express reservations regarding Libya, including \"its more prominent 'liberal' representatives.\" We must remember, Halliday concluded, that the \"liberal\" wing within a regime such as Libya does not have the function of producing change but its role is instead \"to reach compromises with internal hard-liners that serve to lessen external pressure.\" A good case in point are the proposals LSE now is considering. It is, as LSE alumni in positions of responsibility in the region caution, \"far too early for the School to take this step.\"<ref name=\"Halliday\" />\n\n==Human Rights Watch criticism==\nIn 2009, [[Human Rights Watch]] was allowed entry to Libya, via [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]]'s non-profit organization in order to gather facts about the human rights situation there.<ref>[https://www.hrw.org/news/2009/12/12/libya-repressive-atmosphere-pockets-improvement Libya: In Repressive Atmosphere, Pockets of Improvement]</ref> While HRW reported that there were concerns about the \"repressive atmosphere,\" they felt there were signs of \"improvement\" and [[Sarah Leah Whitson]], director of HRW's Middle East division said that one should not \"underestimate the importance of the efforts made so far\" by Gaddafi in the realm of human rights in Libya. She also wrote of her official visit that \"the real impetus for the transformation rests squarely with a quasi-governmental organization, the Qaddafi Foundation for International Charities and Development\" chaired by Gaddafi. She praised Gaddafi for establishing the country's two semi-private newspapers, and said \"it is impossible to underestimate the importance of the efforts made so far. Let's hope this spring will last.\"<ref>[https://foreignpolicy.com/articles/2009/05/26/tripoli_spring Tripoli Spring - How Libya's behind-the-scenes reformer is actually, well, reforming.]</ref>\n\nIn January 2011, HRW criticised other organisations as well as governments that had previously dealt with Gaddafi. HRW Business and Human Rights Director Arvind Ganesan condemned the London School of Economics (LSE) for allowing \"abusive and corrupt officials or their families to launder their images in exchange for money\". This was later followed by Ganesen saying that \"the London School of Economics did not act until Saif al-Islam's father literally began to kill his own people\". According to [[NGO Monitor]], this was despite the fact that David Held, Co-Director of LSE Global Governance, was partially influenced by Whitson's remarks regarding her Libyan visit, referring to Saif al-Islam Gaddafi as a reformer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.neurope.eu/article/human-rights-watch-slammed-over-anti-israeli-and-pro-gaddafi-reports |title=Human Rights Watch slammed over anti-Israeli and pro-Gaddafi reports |access-date=2013-04-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504104543/http://www.neurope.eu/article/human-rights-watch-slammed-over-anti-israeli-and-pro-gaddafi-reports |archive-date=2013-05-04 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>[http://www.opendemocracy.net/david-held/dealing-with-saif-gaddafi-naivety-complicity-or-cautious-engagement Dealing with Saif Gaddafi: naivety, complicity or cautious engagement?]</ref><ref>[http://www.ngo-monitor.org/article.php?id=3605 HRW in 2011: More Balance, Less Credibility]</ref>\n\nIn February 2011, HRW's Whitson admitted that \"Seif Islam in fact abandoned his nascent reform agenda long before.\"<ref>[http://articles.latimes.com/2011/feb/24/opinion/la-oe-whitson-libya-20110224 Libya: To oust a tyrant]</ref>\n\n==LSE, Libya and BP==\n\n[[Peter Denis Sutherland]], formerly Attorney General of Ireland, European Commissioner, and Head of the World Trade Organisation, finished a 13-year stint as chairman of BP, Europe's largest oil company in early 2010. In Spring 2006 he was appointed Chair of London School of Economics Governors commencing in 2008.\n\nAt the LSE council meeting in 2009 Peter Sutherland declared a conflict of interest when the council decided to accept \u00a31.5 million from a charity headed by Muammar Gaddafi. Sutherland's conflict was that BP had signed an oil deal with Libya two years previously, at a time when Sutherland was chairman of the British oil giant. LSE records show Sutherland took no further role in that part of the June 2009 meeting.<ref>[http://journalist.ie/2011/03/sutherland-declared-libyan-conflict-of-interest-at-lse-meeting/ Journalist.ie]</ref>\n\n==Saif Gaddafi's Ralph Miliband Lecture==\nOn 25 May 2010, [[Saif al-Islam Gaddafi]] gave a \"Ralph Miliband lecture\" at the LSE, named after [[Ralph Miliband]], a Marxist scholar and former LSE lecturer. Gaddafi spoke on the topic of \"Libya: Past, Present, and Future.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www2.lse.ac.uk/publicEvents/miliband/200910LectureSeries.aspx | title = 2009-2010 lecture series: The Future of Global Capitalism }}</ref> In introducing the speaker, professor [[David Held]] told the audience that \"I have come to know him very well and I must say I have come to like him a great deal.\" He continued:\n\n<blockquote>Saif is committed to resolving contentious international and domestic issues through dialogue, debate and peaceful negotiations. ... Within his own country Saif has spearheaded efforts to open with Islamic militants about the nature and form of their struggle in order to find ways of bringing them back into the political process. ... His success was based on the use of the language of \"soft power,\" that is, the language of dialogue. ... Throughout this time I've come to know Saif as someone who looks to democracy, civil society and deep liberal values for the core of his inspiration.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=ME5GGfU-iPE&feature=player_embedded | title = Held and Gadaffi}}</ref><ref>For the audio of the entire lecture, see [[Julia Belluz]], \"[http://www2.macleans.ca/tag/saif-al-islam-alqadhafi/ Gadhafi's Son: Then and Now],\" Macleans, 23 February 2001.</ref></blockquote>\n\nHeld went on to say that he had many tutorials with Saif and that throughout ongoing dialogue on a range of issues they came to agree on some, and to disagree on much.\n\nOn the evening of the lecture, a fight broke out between anti-Gaddafi protesters and pro-Gaddafi supporters. The police were eventually called in to break up the altercation.<ref>{{cite news | url = http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/standard/article-23838481-brawl-at-lse-as-libyan-groups-clash-over-gaddafis-sons-speech.do | title = Brawl at LSE as Libyan groups clash over Gaddafi's son's speech | publisher = London Evening Standard | first = Terry | last = Kirby | date = 26 May 2010}}</ref><ref>Google Video, \"[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Fkd4QVQI47A Brawl at LSE as Libyan groups clash over Gaddafi's son's speech],\"</ref> In a comment on 6 March 2011, [[David Miliband]], Ralph Miliband's elder son and a former UK Foreign Secretary, was critical of the LSE's decision to invite Saif al-Islam Gaddafi:\n<blockquote>The Ralph Miliband Programme at the LSE was founded by a former student of my dad's ... The idea of Saif Gaddafi giving a lecture under his name is just horrific to him and horrific to the whole family obviously,<ref>Emily Ashton, \"[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/education/education-news/miliband-anger-over-gaddafi-lecture-2233969.html Miliband Anger over Gadaffi Lecture],\" Independent, 6 March 2011.</ref></blockquote>  There were approximately 30-40 journalists at the event, however reports on the lecture were largely uncritical and did not raise the issues surrounding the LSE engagement with Libya. David Miliband continued his own association with LSE, giving a lecture at LSE on 8 March, two days after the above comments, where he made reference to the school's early history of economic liberalism combined with social justice.<ref>{{cite web|last=Miliband |first=David |url=http://www.newstatesman.com/uk-politics/2011/03/centre-parties-social |title=Full Transcript &#124; David Miliband &#124; Speech on the European left &#124; LSE &#124; 8 March 2011 |publisher=Newstatesman.com |date=2011-03-08 |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\nAn open letter by Professor John Keane asks Professor David Held to explain further his links with Libya and to reconsider his reactions. Professor Keane raises several questions, such as: Has the LSE Libya affair not done damage to the scholarly credibility of research programs in the area of democracy? Click here <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://johnkeane.net/52/news/libya-intellectuals-and-democracy-an-open-letter-to-professor-david-held |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-03-22 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110807163134/http://johnkeane.net/52/news/libya-intellectuals-and-democracy-an-open-letter-to-professor-david-held |archive-date=2011-08-07 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Keane's letter was heavily criticised by those who responded to it in the online magazine in which it was published <http://www.opendemocracy.net/john-keane/libya-intellectuals-and-democracy-open-letter-to-professor-david-held>. Many argued that it was vindictive and overblown. An overview of Halliday and Held - who were both contributors to openDemocracy - with respect to the affair and the larger implications for the independence of UK universities was published by its former editor [http://www.opendemocracy.net/ourkingdom/anthony-barnett/fred-halliday-david-held-lse-and-independence-of-universities Fred Halliday, David Held, the LSE and the independence of universities].\n\nIn October 2011 Held resigned from his post at the LSE in advance of the publication an independent report into the LSE's links with Libya.<ref name=\"Vasagar\"/>\n\nDavid Held issued a personal statement in reaction to the allegations, saying that \"in many discussions and meetings I encouraged the development of [Gaddafi's] reform agenda and subsequently sought to support it through research on the North Africa Programme funded by the Gaddafi International Charity and Development Foundation\" at the LSE.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://roarmagazine.wordpress.com/2011/02/21/david-held-gaddafi-libya-global-governanc/ |title=Archived copy |access-date=2011-03-04 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110227142708/http://roarmagazine.wordpress.com/2011/02/21/david-held-gaddafi-libya-global-governanc/ |archive-date=2011-02-27 |url-status=dead }}</ref> In October 2011 Held resigned from his post at the LSE,.<ref name=\"Vasagar\">{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2011/oct/31/saif-gaddafi-lse-academic | location=London | work=The Guardian | first=Jeevan | last=Vasagar | title=Academic linked to Gaddafi's fugitive son leaves LSE | date=31 October 2011}}</ref> The [[Harry Woolf, Baron Woolf|Woolf]] report examined links between the LSE and the Libyan regime. The inquiry report says it was Professor Held, who \"first approached Saif about the possibility of funding his centre for Global Governance in December 2008\". This was after the dictator's son had been awarded his PhD by the LSE but before the formal graduation ceremony. The gift offered was of \u00a31.5m in tranches of \u00a3300,000 over a five-year period. Periodic payments were to be made annually. The report says: \"This was not a one-off donation but the founding of a relationship between the school and the donor, which is not unusual. However, bearing in mind the volatility of the Gaddafi regime, the gift involved a substantial risk because of the length of the relationship.\" A decision was made that the gift would not come from Saif directly but from \"private sector sources\". This step \"became essential to Professor Held's presentation of the gift. Unless the money could be shown as coming to the foundation from private sources it could have been seen as unacceptable money from the Libyan state.\"Woolf writes: \"I come to no conclusions as to whether there was or would have been excessive influence by the donor over the use of the funds from Saif's foundation. However, what has been made plain is that proper structures of governance are needed to protect academic integrity against influence from the interests of private donors.\" The funding was accepted despite internal protest. Fred Halliday, a distinguished Middle East expert at the LSE before his death, criticised the donation in a letter that described the country's rulers as a \"secretive, erratic and corrupt elite\". Held was appointed to the board of the Gaddafi foundation on 28 June 2009, a few days after the gift was discussed and accepted by the university's governing body. Held subsequently resigned from the charity on the LSE council's advice.\n\nDespite institutional and procedural criticism the Woolf report, however, exonerated LSE staff (including David Held) stating that they acted in what they believed to be the best interests of the school.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=418293 |title=LSE's 'mistakes were legion' in Libyan dealings, Woolf finds &#124; Times Higher Education (THE) |publisher=Times Higher Education |date= |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\nQuestions remain, however, about the involvement of elite British academics at the LSE with the Gaddafi regime.\n\n==LSE's video link-up with Gaddafi==\nOn 2 December 2010, in a video-link conference hosted by the LSE, of LSE Global Governance, introduced [[Muammar Gaddafi]] as \"Brother Leader,\" and referred to him as \"the world's longest serving national leader.\"\n<blockquote>I will be chairing this on behalf of Howard Davis, the LSE's Director who unfortunately couldn't make it this evening, but who sends the following message, \u201cYou are most welcome here Colonel Gaddafi. We wish you had been able to deliver some Libyan weather at the same time\u201d -this is the message from Howard Davis -- \u201cWe are pleased to be asked to train Libya officials, and we hope the relationship will continue.\u201d</blockquote>\n\nGaddafi used the occasion to denounce the Lockerbie bombing as a \"fabrication and creation\" of Ronald Reagan and Margaret Thatcher, and revealed that the Libyan national, [[Abdelbaset al-Megrahi]], who was convicted of the bombing and imprisoned in Scotland in 2001, but returned to Libya in 2009 on health grounds, was preparing a multi-million pound compensation claim against Britain for false imprisonment and medical neglect.{{cn|date=April 2020}} At the end of the lecture, Muammar Gaddafi was given a black baseball cap bearing the bright red LSE logo. \"You're in good company,\" he was assured. \"Mandela, Kofi Annan, and Bill Clinton also have them.\"<ref>{{cite news | publisher = The Guardian |date = 1 March 2011 |title = He gave them wisdom. They gave him a baseball cap. Gaddafi's LSE love-in | url = https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2011/mar/01/hugh-muir-diary |location=London |first=Hugh |last=Muir}}</ref>\n\n==Saif Gaddafi's \"Rivers of Blood\" speech==\n\nOn 20 February 2011, Saif al-Islam Gaddafi delivered an address to the nation on Libyan state television stating that if no agreement could be found between protesters and the government \"thousands of deaths, and rivers of blood will run through Libya\". He also insisted that his father remained in charge with the army's backing and would \"fight until the last man, the last woman, the last bullet.\"<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eL6I5hktEs0 | title = Al Jazeera English - Saif El Islam Gadaffi addresses the nation - Part 1 of 3 }}</ref>\n\nOn 28 February 2011, CBS News showed a clip of Gaddafi addressing a group of supporters in Tripoli. Holding a [[Heckler & Koch G36]] assault rifle in the air, he told the crowd that \"weapons are on the way.\"<ref>{{cite web | publisher = CBS News | date = 28 February 2011 | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gqR7zTkiSsg | title= Saif Qaddafi seen rallying supporters }}</ref> A day earlier, Gaddafi had told [[Christiane Amanpour]] in an exclusive interview for ABCNews that the Libyan government \"didn't use force to stay in power,\" and asked her to show him \"a single attack, a single bomb, a single casualty\".<ref>{{cite web | publisher = ABCNews | title = Exclusive Interview with Gadhafi's Sons |url = http://abcnews.go.com/ThisWeek/video/exclusive-interview-gadhafis-sons-13012336}}</ref> On 5 March 2011, he told CNN's [[Nic Robertson]] in [http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/world/2011/03/05/bts.robertson.saif.gadhafi.cnn?hpt=T2 an interview] that his family won't step down: \"I am the government. If we would hold tomorrow election my father would win with a big majority\".<ref name=\"cnn.com\">{{cite news | publisher = CNN | date= 5 March 2011 | title = Moammar Gadhafi's son speaks with CNN | url = http://www.cnn.com/video/#/video/world/2011/03/05/bts.robertson.saif.gadhafi.cnn?hpt=T2}}</ref> Saif further told CNN that the world should not worry about the \"200, 300 even 1000 militia...because now everybody is armed in Libya.\"<ref name=\"cnn.com\"/> In an interview with Benjamin Harvey from Bloomberg on 8 March, Gaddafi said that the crisis in Libya was \"a passing cloud. This is an historic opportunity for Libya to become a first-class democratic state.\u201d<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-09/davos-man-qaddafi-jr-fights-for-future-in-civil-rights-u-turn.html | title = Davos Man Qaddafi Jr. Fights for Future in Libya After Civil Rights U-Turn |first = Benjamin | last = Harvey | work=Bloomberg | date=9 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe contrast between his appearance in Tripoli in 2011 and his appearance as a guest speaker at LSE, said the BBC, \"could not have been more stark.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/programmes/newsnight/9407335.stm | title = Gaddafi's son Saif's ties to LSE and Britain | work=BBC News | first=Matt | last=Prodger | date=25 February 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Director Howard Davies resigns==\n[[File:Howard Davies at the World Economic Forum Summit on the Global Agenda 2008.jpg|left|thumb|[[Howard Davies (economist)|Howard Davies]] at the [[World Economic Forum|Davos Summit 2008]]]]\nLSE Director [[Howard Davies (economist)|Howard Davies]] resigned on 3 March over the scandal.<ref name=Davies>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/education/2011/mar/03/lse-director-resigns-gaddafi-scandal | title = LSE head quits over Gaddafi scandal | publisher = The Guardian | location=London | first1=Jeevan | last1=Vasagar | first2=Rajeev | last2=Syal | date=4 March 2011}}</ref> In a comment Davies said he had left the job because of \"two errors of judgment\": 1) his advice that a donation from Gaddafi's foundation was acceptable, and 2) his decision to act as a financial adviser to the Libyan government.<ref name=\"lse-libya-anthony-giddens-gaddafi\"/> Davies acknowledged in his resignation letter that it would \u201cbe right for me to step down, even though I know that this will cause difficulty for the institution I have come to love.\u201d He added, \u201cThe short point is that I am responsible for the school\u2019s reputation, and that has suffered.\u201d<ref>{{cite web | url = https://docs.google.com/document/d/115dQVYUdxoJRvRTsl8uYL9xe9WTp7QUbLBryMRzKqmI/edit?hl=sv# | title = Howard Davies' Letter of Resignation | publisher = The Guardian |date = 6 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn a statement the LSE's Board of Governors accepted Howard's resignation with \"great regret.\"<ref name=Davies/> [[Raheem Kassam]], from the 'Student Rights' group, called for the Libyan money to be donated to a charity to assist Gaddafi's victims.<ref>Jonny Paul [http://www.jpost.com/International/Article.aspx?id=209449 \"LSE suspends study program financed by Gaddafi\u2019s son\"], ''The Jerusalem Post'', 23 February 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=The Sunday Times |url=http://www.thesundaytimes.co.uk/sto/news/Politics/article565598.ece |title=Replay: Sunday politics Q&A with Robert Halfon MP |publisher=The Sunday Times |date=2011-02-27 |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\n[[Colin Talbot]], who holds a PhD degree from the LSE and is currently the Chair of Public Policy and Management at Manchester Business School, told UTv News on 4 March 2011 that Howard Davies should not be blamed for carrying out what amounted to \"British diplomatic strategy\".<ref name=\"u.tv\">{{cite news | publisher = UTvNews | title = British government encouraged LSE to forge Libya links, says academic | date = 4 March 2011 | url = http://www.u.tv/News/British-government-encouraged-LSE-to-forge-Libya-links-says-academic/6c296027-fffb-43e3-89c2-097dd9cc9188}}</ref> Talbot, who also taught on the LSE's Libya program further said that Davies was not the only person responsible for tarnishing the university's reputation, because the British government had encouraged Davies to establish close ties to the Gaddafi family.<ref name=\"u.tv\"/>\n\nThe LSE said in a statement on 21 February 2011, that its engagement with the Libyan authorities has already finished or has been stopped following recent events in the country. The School said no more of the \u00a31.5m donation would be accepted. About half of the \u00a3300,000 already accepted had been spent and the LSE Council would next consider what to do with the remaining funds, taking into account the views of LSE students.<ref name=Sellgren2>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/education-12550876 | title = Gaddafi funds prompt LSE students' protest | first = Katherine | last = Sellgren | date = 23 February 2011 | publisher = BBC }}</ref>\n\nOn 17 March 2011, Professor [[Judith Rees]] was appointed interim- director. Reese was pro director of the School from 1998 to 2004, and is currently director of the Grantham Research Institute on Climate Change and the Environment at LSE.\n\n==LSE reactions==\n\n===Students===\n\nSeveral protest actions were undertaken by LSE students in the response to the affair, including sit-ins and demonstrations. The students have insisted that LSE repay the donation from Gaddafi's foundation and revoke Gaddafi's status as LSE alumnus. The donation had originally been welcomed by the then-General Secretary of LSE Students Union, Aled Fisher, in June 2009, as \"exactly the kind of donation\" the School should be encouraging.\"<ref name=Sellgren2/> Fisher said he was \"taken out of context\" and LSE officials \"withheld pertinent facts about Saif Gaddafi\u2019s role in the state, which... would have made Council and I look differently on the issue,\" with Charlotte Gerada, General Secretary in 2011, stating it was \"unacceptable\" that LSE \"used\" Fisher \"as a scapegoat.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thebeaveronline.co.uk/2011/03/08/former-gensec%E2%80%99s-email-%E2%80%9Ctaken-out-of-context%E2%80%9D/ |title=Germyx \u2013 Recenzii profesionale, la cele mai bune produse \u0219i servicii online |publisher=Thebeaveronline.co.uk |date=2019-06-26 |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\nIn an on-line petition, present and former LSE students urged the School to revoke Gaddafi's status as alumnus and to cease all cooperation with the Libyan regime. \"We were shocked to find out that the LSE has accepted a \u00a31.5 million donation from the Gaddafi International Charity and Development Foundation; an NGO headed by Gaddafi's son, Saif al-Islam Gaddafi.... We are astonished that the donation was accepted in the first place.\"<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n\n===Faculty===\n[[File:Meghnad Desai 1980s.jpg|thumb|right|[[Meghnad Desai|Lord Desai]], co-founder, LSE Global Governance]]\n\nProfessor [[Meghnad Desai]], defended LSE's actions, arguing that \"Academic research needs money \u2014 Rockefeller was a robber baron once, but we take his money\".<ref>''New York Times'', \"[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/03/02/world/europe/02degree.html A London University Wrestles With a Qaddafi Gift],\" 1 March 2011.</ref> \"It was only after bullets started flying in Libya that Saif Gaddafi was found to have cheated. Nor had anyone until then objected that the LSE had received a donation from Saif Gaddafi's Foundation.\"<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/mar/04/lse-heavy-price-saif-gaddafis-phd | title = LSE is paying a heavy price for Saif Gaddafi's PhD | first = Meghnad | last = Desai | location=London | work=The Guardian | date=4 March 2011}}</ref>\n\nProfessor [[David Held]] issued a statement saying that \"in many discussions and meetings I encouraged the development of Gaddafi's reform agenda and subsequently sought to support it through research on the North Africa Programme funded by the Gaddafi International Charity and Development Foundation.\"<ref>{{cite news| url = http://roarmagazine.wordpress.com/2011/02/21/david-held-gaddafi-libya-global-governanc/ | title = Personal Statement by David Held on Gaddafi\u2019s LSE Donation}}</ref>\n\nSaif Gaddafi, said [[Alex Voorhoeve]], \"seemed genuinely moved by the desire to study democratic ideals and practice and my colleagues had therefore hoped he would have a liberalizing influence on the Libyan regime. ... I had hoped that at such a crucial moment, he would defend the democratic ideals that he wrote about in his thesis.<ref name=\"volkskrant.nl\"/></blockquote>\n\nThese reactions were echoed by [[Alia Brahimi]], who claimed to be \"tremendously surprised\" by Saif Gaddafi's \"Rivers of Blood Speech.\"  Saif Gaddafi, she said, had been a reformer for many years but now \"seemed to be backpeddling\".<ref>{{cite news| publisher = Al-Jazeera | date = 24 February 2011 | title = Libya's power struggle: In a country divided by tribal alliances, who holds the future of the country in their hands? | url = http://english.aljazeera.net/programmes/insidestory/2011/02/2011224161551594815.html}}</ref> \"I\u2019ve got nothing to apologise for. Saif told me he was keen that democratic reform should happen soon in Libya.\"<ref name=DM_0303/>\n\n[[Henning Mayer]], a former employee of David Held, defended the decision to accept Gaddafi's money saying it was made based on information available at the time.<ref>Henning Mayer, 14 March 2011 The LSE Libya Crisis: A Statement in Support of David Held [http://www.social-europe.eu/2011/03/the-lse%E2%80%99s-libya-crisis-a-statement-in-support-of-david-held/ social-europe.eu]</ref>\n\nIn a statement [[Fred Halliday]]'s wife said she recalled that her late husband had been opposed to accepting Gaddafi as a student.<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/feb/21/saif-al-islam-gaddafi | title = Saif al-Islam Gaddafi: LSE-educated man the west can no longer deal with | date = 21 February 2011 | location=London | work=The Guardian | first1=Ian | last1=Cobain | first2=Amelia | last2=Hill}}</ref>\n\nThe ''Financial Times'' reported on 3 March 2011, that the LSE had started to edit official university websites in an attempt to \"remove references to Libyan links from its academics\u2019 workplace biographies\".<ref>{{cite news | publisher = Financial Times | title = LSE websites edited to remove Libyan ties | date= 3 March 2011 | url = http://www.ft.com/cms/s/0/37dcc23e-45e1-11e0-acd8-00144feab49a.html#axzz1FgzZHpiu}}</ref>\n\n[[Shami Chakrabarti]], director of Liberty had also faced criticism over the affair, due to her position on the governing council of LSE. The \"Students Rights\" organisation accused her of hypocrisy \"for being \"the director of a human rights group while legitimizing murderous regimes\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jpost.com/International/LSE-head-resigns-over-Libya-link |title=LSE head resigns over Libya link - World News - Jerusalem Post |publisher=Jpost.com |date=2011-03-06 |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref> She later admitted her embarrassment and shame about the Gaddafi affair and finally in April 2013 Chakrabarti's spokesman confirmed that she had severed all links with The LSE.<ref>{{cite web|last=Walker |first=Tim |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/education/educationnews/9995673/Shami-Chakrabarti-disowns-the-LSE.html |title=Shami Chakrabarti disowns the LSE |publisher=Telegraph |date=2013-04-16 |accessdate=2019-09-15}}</ref>\n\n==Lord Woolf Inquiry==\n\nOn 3 March 2011, LSE announced that they had set up an independent external inquiry into the School's relationship with the Libyan regime, to be conducted by the former lord chief justice [[Harry Woolf, Baron Woolf|Harry Woolf]].<ref name=Davies/> Lord Woolf is to conduct\n<blockquote>An independent inquiry to establish the full facts of the School\u2019s links with Libya, whether there have been errors made, and to establish clear guidelines for international donations to and links with the School. Lord Woolf is to make recommendations to the LSE Council as soon as possible. He is to have total discretion as to how he conducts the inquiry, and as to the matters on which he is to report.<ref>[http://woolflse.com/ Lord Woolf\u2019s Inquiry into the LSE and Libya] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120318132926/http://www.woolflse.com/ |date=2012-03-18 }}.</ref></blockquote>\nThe Woolf report was published on 30 November 2011.  Woolf summarised his central conclusion as\n<blockquote>The School established, in an incremental and piecemeal fashion, a relationship with Libya. Before a global company embarks upon a relationship with a foreign partner, a due diligence assessment should be conducted. No similar exercise took place in this case. The links were allowed to grow, unchecked and to a degree unnoticed, until their effect was overwhelming. In October 2009, the LSE\u2019s Council resolved that the links should be monitored carefully in future. That monitoring came too late. By October 2009 the relationship with Libya had been well established. In addition, the history of the developing connection between the LSE and Libya has exposed a disconcerting number of failures in communication and governance within the School. The errors which I detail in the remaining chapters of this Report exceed those that should have occurred in an institution of the LSE\u2019s distinction. The pattern is such that I am driven to the central conclusion that there were shortcomings in the governance structure and management at the LSE.<ref>[http://woolflse.com/dl/woolf-lse-report.pdf Woolf Inquiry p22]</ref></blockquote>\n\n==Other universities with Libyan links==\n\nOn 19 May 2009, the French-language journal Jeune Afrique published an investigative report on the Gaddafi family's public relations campaign set up by Monitor. Titled 'Gaddafi: Mirror, Mirror, Tell Me Who is the Most Handsome'<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/Article/ARTJAJA2522p050-051.xml0/ Jeuneafrique.com]</ref> the article detailed how the Monitor group had been organizing visits to Libya by leading academics from US-and UK-based universities in order to meet Gaddafi the 'thinker and intellectual'.  In addition to Michael Porter from the Harvard Business School, [[Francis Fukuyama]], Professor of International Political Economy at Johns Hopkins University, lobbyist [[Richard Perle]], as well as [[Robert Putnam]] from Harvard University traveled to Tripoli to meet Gaddafi.<ref>[http://www.u.tv/News/British-government-encouraged-LSE-to-forge-Libya-links-says-academic/6c296027-fffb-43e3-89c2-097dd9cc9188 U.tv]</ref> All the meetings had been organized by the Monitor group.<ref>[http://www.jeuneafrique.com/Article/ARTJAJA2522p050-051.xml0/ Jeunafrique.com]</ref>\n\nIn the context of the scandal over LSE's Libya connections, it emerged that also [[Michigan State University]] had established a program to train future Libyan leaders. [[Moussa Koussa]], Libya's foreign minister and the second most powerful man in Libya after the Gaddafi family{{Citation needed|date=August 2012}} received a master's degree in Sociology from Michigan State in 1978.<ref>[http://www.commentarymagazine.com/2011/03/04/london-school-of-economicss-ties-to-libya-the-tip-of-the-iceberg-for-academia/ Commentarymagazine.com]</ref>\n\nIn April 2011, the Guardian claimed that the [[University of St Andrews]] Centre for Syrian Studies received funding from businessman [[Ayman Asfari]] who was alleged to have links to the Syrian government led by [[Bashar al-Assad]].  However, it later transpired that Mr Asfari had no links to the Syrian government and the Guardian issued an apology to him in print in July; no such apology was issued to the University.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/education/2011/apr/27/syrian-funding-st-andrews-university | location=London | work=The Guardian | first1=Peter | last1=Beaumont | first2=Jeevan | last2=Vasagar | title=St Andrews University,Higher education (Universities etc.),Education,Syria (News),Middle East (News),World news,UK news,Arab and Middle East unrest (News) | date=27 April 2011}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lse.ac.uk London School of Economics and Political Science], official web site.\n* [http://www.monitor.com Monitor Group], official web site.\n* [http://www.gicdf.org/ Gaddafi International Foundation For Charity and Development], official web site.\n* Fred Halliday, [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1myZyaOqtCqeW0fdvOSPry_55GIOKNVvvqFP0y6l2Ts4/edit?hl=sv \"LSE: and the Qaddafi Foundation: A Dissenting Note\"], October 4, 2009.\n* Saif Al-Islam Alqadhafi, \"[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&pid=explorer&chrome=true&srcid=0B1oqqxmEgcXbODMwMmNhYmMtZTVjYS00ODZlLTk4NjItYmJkNjliODQ1MGI2&hl=en The Role of Civil Society in the Democratization of Global Governance Institutions: From 'Soft Power' to Collective Decision-Making?]\" PhD Thesis, London School of Economics, 2008.\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1GnwedNTFtyQQNjTiS00GnCzIRxsnWqtu-WaWgeJDNuQ/edit?pli=1&hl=sv# \"For the LSE to Revoke the Alumni Status of Saif al-Islam Gaddafi and to Cease All Cooperation with the Libyan Regime,\"].\n* Human Rights Watch, \"[https://www.scribd.com/doc/48022762/human-rights-watch-world-report-2011 World Report, 2011], New York, 2011, pp.&nbsp;562\u2013567.\n* [http://woolflse.com/dl/woolf-lse-report.pdf The Woolf Inquiry: An inquiry into the LSE\u2019s links with Libya and lessons to be learned], October 2011.\n* [https://docs.google.com/document/d/1guh8qHNi3uJswPurGqQksa2eTfIZc--GQAyw0V3sFwg/edit?hl=en# LSE Libya Links: A Short Bibliography]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Lse Libya Links}}\n[[Category:London School of Economics|Gaddafi links]]\n[[Category:Gaddafi family]]\n[[Category:Academic scandals]]\n[[Category:Libya\u2013United Kingdom relations]]\n", "name_user": "Lee Bunce", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLSE's video link-up with Gaddafi", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/LSE%E2%80%93Gaddafi_affair"}
{"title_page": "Green Revolution in India", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2014}}\n[[File:Punjab Monsoon.jpg|thumbnail|250px|The state of [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]] led India's [[Green Revolution]] and earned the distinction of being the country's wheat basket.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/stateplan/sdr_pdf/shdr_pun04.pdf |title=Human Development Report 2004, Punjab |date=2004 |author=[[Government of Punjab, India|The Government of Punjab]] |accessdate=9 August 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110708073911/http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/stateplan/sdr_pdf/shdr_pun04.pdf| archivedate= 8 July 2011 | url-status= live}} Section: \"The Green Revolution\", pp. 17\u201320.</ref>]]\n\nThe '''Green Revolution in India''' refers to a period when Indian [[agriculture in India|agriculture]] was converted into an industrial system due to the adoption of modern methods and technology such as the use of '''[[High-yielding variety|high yielding variety (HYV) seeds]],''' '''tractors, irrigation facilities, pesticides, and fertilizers'''. It was mainly found by [[M.S. Swaminathan]]. This was part of the larger [[Green revolution]] endeavor initiated by [[Norman Borlaug]], which leveraged agricultural research and technology to increase agricultural productivity in the developing world.<ref>Hardin, Lowell S. \"Meetings That Changed the World: Bellagio 1969: The Green Revolution.\" Nature 25 Sep 2008: 470-471. Retrieved 16 November 2018 from https://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1027&context=envstudtheses</ref>\n\nUnder '''Congress''' (INC) led government, the Green Revolution within [[India]] commenced in 1965 that led to an increase in food grain production, especially in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[Haryana]], and [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Major milestones in this undertaking were the development of high-yielding varieties of [[wheat]],<ref name=\"about IARI\">{{cite web|title=About IARI|url=http://www.iari.res.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=161&Itemid=1730|website=IARI|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref> and [[rust (fungus)|rust]] resistant strains of wheat.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web | title = Rust-resistant Wheat Varieties. Work at Pusa Institute|work=The Indian Express| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Jcc-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=lUwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3228,3861741&dq=pusa+institute&hl=en|date=7 February 1950| accessdate = 13 September 2013}}</ref><ref>Newman, Bryan. \"A Bitter Harvest: Farmer Suicide and the Unforeseen Social, Environmental and Economic Impacts of the Green Revolution in Punjab, India .\" Development Report No. 15. Jan 2007. Food First: Institute for Food and Development Policy. Retrieved 16 November 2018 from https://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1027&context=envstudtheses</ref> However, agricultural scientists like [[M.S. Swaminathan]] and social activists like [[Vandana Shiva]] are of the opinion that it caused greater long term sociological and financial problems for the people of Punjab and Haryana.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shiva |first1=Vandana |title=Green revolution in India |url=http://livingheritage.org/green-revolution.htm |website=Living heritage |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> However it proved to be a useful measure and was pioneer in helping the then Indian Government  to independently produce necessary crops in her own country instead of depending on foreign exports whose policies were often misused by the foreign nations to blackmail India to serve their own political purpose and get dominated by those nations.\n\n== Practices ==\n\n=== Wheat production ===\nThe main development was higher-yielding varieties of [[wheat]],<ref name=\"about IARI\" /> for developing [[rust (fungus)|rust]] resistant strains of wheat.<ref name=\":0\" /> The introduction of high-yielding varieties(HYV) of seeds and the increased quality of [[fertilizers]] and [[irrigation]] technique led to the increase in production to make the country self-sufficient in food grains, thus improving [[agriculture in India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://countrystudies.us/india/104.htm|title=The Green Revolution in India|work=U.S. Library of Congress (released in [[public domain]])|series=Library of Congress is Country Studies|accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref> The methods adopted included the use of [[high-yielding varieties]] (HYVs) of seeds<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-38156350|title=IR8: The miracle rice which saved millions of lives|last=Rowlatt|first=Justin|date=2016-12-01|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-12-05}}</ref> with modern farming methods.\n\nThe production of wheat has produced the best results in fueling self-sufficiency of India. Along with high-yielding seeds and irrigation facilities, the enthusiasm of farmers mobilized the idea of agricultural revolution. Due to the rise in use of chemical pesticides and fertilizers, there was a negative effect on the [[soil]] and the land (e.g., [[land degradation]]).\n\n=== Other practices ===\n{{Prose|section|date=January 2018}}\n* [[Irrigation]] infrastructure\n* Use of [[pesticides]]\n** Use of [[insecticides]]\n** Use of [[herbicide]]s\n* Consolidation of [[Possession (law)|holdings]]\n* [[Land reforms]]\n* Improved [[rural infrastructure]]\n* Supply of agricultural [[credit (finance)|credit]]\n* Use of chemical or [[synthetic fertilizers]]\n* Use of [[irrigation sprinkler|sprinklers]] or [[drip irrigation]] systems\n* Use of advanced [[machinery]]\n* Use of [[vector quantity]]\n\n== Rationale for the Green Revolution ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2019}}\nThe Green Revolution in India was first introduced in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] in the late 1960s as part of a development program issued by international donor agencies and the Government of India.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Dutta|first=Swarup|date=June 2012|title=Green Revolution Revisited: The Contemporary Agrarian Situation in Punjab, India|journal=Social Change|volume=42|issue=2|pages=229\u2013247|doi=10.1177/004908571204200205|issn=0049-0857}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[British Raj]], India's grain economy hinged on a unilateral relation of exploitation.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|title=Late Victorian holocausts : El Ni\u00f1o famines and the making of the Third World|last=Davis, Mike, 1946- author.|isbn=978-1-78168-360-6|oclc=1051845720|year = 2017}}</ref> Consequently, when India gained independence, the weakened country quickly became vulnerable to frequent famines, financial instabilities, and low productivity. These factors formed a rationale for the implementation of the Green Revolution as a development strategy in India.\n\n=== Frequent famines ===\nIn 1964-65 and 1965\u201366, India experienced two severe droughts which led to food shortages and famines among the country's growing population.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sangha|first=Kamaljit Kaur|date=2014|title=Modern agricultural practices and analysis of socio-economic and ecological impacts of development in agriculture sector, Punjab, India - A review|journal=Indian Journal of Agricultural Research|volume=48|issue=5|pages=331|doi=10.5958/0976-058x.2014.01312.2|issn=0367-8245|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/2c0365b5e0f885da15f5c52ff2f6c858a7db564e}}</ref> Modern agricultural technologies appeared to offer strategies to counter the frequency of famines.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=Green revolution : history, impact and future|last=Jain, H. K.|date=2012|publisher=Studium Press LLC|isbn=978-1-4416-7448-7|oclc=967650924}}</ref> There is debate regarding India's famines prior to independence, with some arguing they were intensified by British taxation and agrarian policies in the 19th and 20th centuries,<ref name=\":42\"/> and others downplaying such impact of colonial rule.\n\n=== Lack of finance ===\nMarginal farmers found it very difficult to get [[Financing|finance]] and [[credit]] at economical rates from the government and banks and hence, fell as easy prey to the [[Moneylender|money lenders]]. They took loans from [[landlords]], who charged high rates of [[interest]]s and also exploited the farmers later on to work in their fields to repay the loans ([[farm labourer]]s).{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} Proper financing was not given during the Green Revolution period, which created a lot of problems and sufferings to the farmers of India. Government also helped those under loans.\n\n=== Low Productivity ===\nIn the context of India's rapidly growing population, the country's traditional agricultural practices yielded insufficient food production. By the 1960s, this low productivity led India to experience food grain shortages that were more severe than those of other developing countries. Agricultural technological advancements offered opportunities to increase productivity.<ref name=\":22\"/>\n\n== Criticisms of the Green Revolution ==\nThe Green Revolution yielded great economic prosperity during its early years. In Punjab, where it was first introduced, the Green Revolution led to significant increases in the state's agricultural output, supporting India\u2019s overall economy. By 1970, Punjab was producing 70 percent of the country's total food grains,<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Sandhu|first=Jashandeep Singh|date=2014|title=Green Revolution: A Case Study of Punjab|url=|journal=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress|volume=75|pages=1192\u20131199|via=JSTOR}}</ref> and farmers' incomes were increasing by over 70 percent.<ref name=\":02\" /> Punjab's prosperity following the Green Revolution became a model to which other states aspired to reach.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/violenceofgreen00shiv|title=The Violence of the green revolution : ecological degredation and political conflict|last=Shiva, Vandana.|date=1991|publisher=Zed|isbn=0-86232-964-7|oclc=24740968|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nHowever, despite the initial prosperity experienced in Punjab, the Green Revolution was met with much controversy throughout India.\n\n=== Indian Economic Sovereignty ===\nCriticism of the effects of the green revolution include the cost for many small farmers using HYV seeds, with their associated demands of increased irrigation systems and pesticides. A case study is found in India, where farmers are buying [[Monsanto]] BT cotton seeds\u2014sold on the idea that these seeds produced 'natural insecticides'. In reality, they need to still pay for expensive pesticides and irrigation systems, which might lead to increased borrowing to finance the change from traditional seed varieties. Many farmers have difficulty in paying for the expensive technologies, especially if they have a bad harvest. These high costs of cultivation push rural farmers to take out loans\u2014typically at high interest rates.<ref name=\":12\"/> Over-borrowing commonly entraps farmers into a cycle of debt.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nOn top of this, India's liberalized economy further exacerbates the farmers's economic conditions. Indian environmentalist [[Vandana Shiva]] writes that this is the \"second Green Revolution\". The first Green Revolution, she suggests, was mostly publicly funded (by the Indian Government). This new Green Revolution, she says, is driven by private (and foreign) interest \u2013 notably MNCs like Monsanto\u2014as encourage by the [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal]] context. Ultimately, this is leading to foreign ownership over most of India's farmland, undermining farmers' interests.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nFarmer's financial issues have become especially apparent in Punjab, where its rural areas have witnessed an alarming rise in suicide rates.<ref name=\":12\" /> Excluding the countless unreported cases, there has been estimated to be a 51.97 per cent increase in the number of suicides in Punjab in 1992-93, compared to the recorded 5.11 per cent increase in the country as a whole.<ref name=\":12\" /> According to a 2019 Indian newspaper, indebtedness continues to be a grave issue affecting Punjabi people today, demonstrated by the more than 900 recorded farmer suicided in Punjab in the last two years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/punjab/farm-suicides-unabated-in-punjab-over-900-in-2-years/727671.html|title=Farm suicides unabated in Punjab, over 900 in 2 years|last=Bharti|first=Vishav|date=Feb 12, 2019|work=The Tribune|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Environmental Damage ===\nExcessive and inappropriate use of fertilizers and pesticides polluted waterways and killed beneficial insects and wild life. It has caused [[overexploitation|over-use]] of soil and rapidly depleted its nutrients. The rampant irrigation practices led to eventual [[soil degradation]]. Groundwater practices have fallen dramatically. Further, heavy dependence on few major crops has led to [[Biodiversity loss|loss of biodiversity]] of farmers. These problems were aggravated due to absence of training to use modern technology and vast illiteracy leading to excessive use of chemicals.[https://sol.du.ac.in/mod/book/view.php?id=1735&chapterid=1695]\n\n=== Increased Regional disparities ===\nThe green revolution spread only in irrigated and high-potential rainfed areas. The villages or regions without the access of sufficient water were left out that widened the regional disparities between adopters and non-adopters. Since, the HYV seeds technically can be applied only in a land with assured water supply and availability of other inputs like chemicals, fertilizers etc. The application of the new technology in the dry-land areas is simply ruled out.\n\nThe states like Punjab, Haryana, Western UP etc. having good irrigation and other infrastructure facilities were able to derive the benefits of the green revolution and achieve faster economic development while other states have recorded slow growth in agriculture production.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{India topics}}\n{{Agriculture in India}}\n\n[[Category:Agricultural revolutions]]\n[[Category:History of agriculture in India]]\n[[Category:Intensive farming]]\n[[Category:History of the Republic of India]]\n[[Category:Economic history of India]]\n[[Category:Indira Gandhi administration]]\n[[Category:History of Punjab, India (1947\u2013present)]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2018}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2018}}\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2014}}\n[[File:Punjab Monsoon.jpg|thumbnail|250px|The state of [[Punjab (India)|Punjab]] led India's [[Green Revolution]] and earned the distinction of being the country's wheat basket.<ref>{{cite report |url=http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/stateplan/sdr_pdf/shdr_pun04.pdf |title=Human Development Report 2004, Punjab |date=2004 |author=[[Government of Punjab, India|The Government of Punjab]] |accessdate=9 August 2011| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110708073911/http://planningcommission.nic.in/plans/stateplan/sdr_pdf/shdr_pun04.pdf| archivedate= 8 July 2011 | url-status= live}} Section: \"The Green Revolution\", pp. 17\u201320.</ref>]]\n\nThe '''Green Revolution in India''' refers to a period when Indian [[agriculture in India|agriculture]] was converted into an industrial system due to the adoption of modern methods and technology such as the use of '''[[High-yielding variety|high yielding variety (HYV) seeds]],''' '''tractors, irrigation facilities, pesticides, and fertilizers'''. It was mainly found by [[M.S. Swaminathan]]. This was part of the larger [[Green revolution]] endeavor initiated by [[Norman Borlaug]], which leveraged agricultural research and technology to increase agricultural productivity in the developing world.<ref>Hardin, Lowell S. \"Meetings That Changed the World: Bellagio 1969: The Green Revolution.\" Nature 25 Sep 2008: 470-471. Retrieved 16 November 2018 from https://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1027&context=envstudtheses</ref>\n\nUnder '''Congress''' (INC) led government, the Green Revolution within [[India]] commenced in 1965 that led to an increase in food grain production, especially in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]], [[Haryana]], and [[Uttar Pradesh]]. Major milestones in this undertaking were the development of high-yielding varieties of [[wheat]],<ref name=\"about IARI\">{{cite web|title=About IARI|url=http://www.iari.res.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=161&Itemid=1730|website=IARI|accessdate=11 June 2015}}</ref> and [[rust (fungus)|rust]] resistant strains of wheat.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web | title = Rust-resistant Wheat Varieties. Work at Pusa Institute|work=The Indian Express| url = https://news.google.com/newspapers?id=Jcc-AAAAIBAJ&sjid=lUwMAAAAIBAJ&pg=3228,3861741&dq=pusa+institute&hl=en|date=7 February 1950| accessdate = 13 September 2013}}</ref><ref>Newman, Bryan. \"A Bitter Harvest: Farmer Suicide and the Unforeseen Social, Environmental and Economic Impacts of the Green Revolution in Punjab, India .\" Development Report No. 15. Jan 2007. Food First: Institute for Food and Development Policy. Retrieved 16 November 2018 from https://digitalcommons.unl.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1027&context=envstudtheses</ref> However, agricultural scientists like [[M.S. Swaminathan]] and social activists like [[Vandana Shiva]] are of the opinion that it caused greater long term sociological and financial problems for the people of Punjab and Haryana.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Shiva |first1=Vandana |title=Green revolution in India |url=http://livingheritage.org/green-revolution.htm |website=Living heritage |accessdate=5 March 2019}}</ref> However it proved to be a useful measure and was pioneer in helping the then Indian Government  to independently produce necessary crops in her own country instead of depending on foreign exports and whose policies were often misused by the foreign nations to blackmail India to serve their own political purpose and get dominated by those nations.\n\n== Practices ==\n\n=== Wheat production ===\nThe main development was higher-yielding varieties of [[wheat]],<ref name=\"about IARI\" /> for developing [[rust (fungus)|rust]] resistant strains of wheat.<ref name=\":0\" /> The introduction of high-yielding varieties(HYV) of seeds and the increased quality of [[fertilizers]] and [[irrigation]] technique led to the increase in production to make the country self-sufficient in food grains, thus improving [[agriculture in India]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://countrystudies.us/india/104.htm|title=The Green Revolution in India|work=U.S. Library of Congress (released in [[public domain]])|series=Library of Congress is Country Studies|accessdate=2007-10-06}}</ref> The methods adopted included the use of [[high-yielding varieties]] (HYVs) of seeds<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-india-38156350|title=IR8: The miracle rice which saved millions of lives|last=Rowlatt|first=Justin|date=2016-12-01|newspaper=BBC News|language=en-GB|access-date=2016-12-05}}</ref> with modern farming methods.\n\nThe production of wheat has produced the best results in fueling self-sufficiency of India. Along with high-yielding seeds and irrigation facilities, the enthusiasm of farmers mobilized the idea of agricultural revolution. Due to the rise in use of chemical pesticides and fertilizers, there was a negative effect on the [[soil]] and the land (e.g., [[land degradation]]).\n\n=== Other practices ===\n{{Prose|section|date=January 2018}}\n* [[Irrigation]] infrastructure\n* Use of [[pesticides]]\n** Use of [[insecticides]]\n** Use of [[herbicide]]s\n* Consolidation of [[Possession (law)|holdings]]\n* [[Land reforms]]\n* Improved [[rural infrastructure]]\n* Supply of agricultural [[credit (finance)|credit]]\n* Use of chemical or [[synthetic fertilizers]]\n* Use of [[irrigation sprinkler|sprinklers]] or [[drip irrigation]] systems\n* Use of advanced [[machinery]]\n* Use of [[vector quantity]]\n\n== Rationale for the Green Revolution ==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=November 2019}}\nThe Green Revolution in India was first introduced in [[Punjab, India|Punjab]] in the late 1960s as part of a development program issued by international donor agencies and the Government of India.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Dutta|first=Swarup|date=June 2012|title=Green Revolution Revisited: The Contemporary Agrarian Situation in Punjab, India|journal=Social Change|volume=42|issue=2|pages=229\u2013247|doi=10.1177/004908571204200205|issn=0049-0857}}</ref>\n\nDuring the [[British Raj]], India's grain economy hinged on a unilateral relation of exploitation.<ref name=\":42\">{{Cite book|title=Late Victorian holocausts : El Ni\u00f1o famines and the making of the Third World|last=Davis, Mike, 1946- author.|isbn=978-1-78168-360-6|oclc=1051845720|year = 2017}}</ref> Consequently, when India gained independence, the weakened country quickly became vulnerable to frequent famines, financial instabilities, and low productivity. These factors formed a rationale for the implementation of the Green Revolution as a development strategy in India.\n\n=== Frequent famines ===\nIn 1964-65 and 1965\u201366, India experienced two severe droughts which led to food shortages and famines among the country's growing population.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Sangha|first=Kamaljit Kaur|date=2014|title=Modern agricultural practices and analysis of socio-economic and ecological impacts of development in agriculture sector, Punjab, India - A review|journal=Indian Journal of Agricultural Research|volume=48|issue=5|pages=331|doi=10.5958/0976-058x.2014.01312.2|issn=0367-8245|url=https://semanticscholar.org/paper/2c0365b5e0f885da15f5c52ff2f6c858a7db564e}}</ref> Modern agricultural technologies appeared to offer strategies to counter the frequency of famines.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite book|title=Green revolution : history, impact and future|last=Jain, H. K.|date=2012|publisher=Studium Press LLC|isbn=978-1-4416-7448-7|oclc=967650924}}</ref> There is debate regarding India's famines prior to independence, with some arguing they were intensified by British taxation and agrarian policies in the 19th and 20th centuries,<ref name=\":42\"/> and others downplaying such impact of colonial rule.\n\n=== Lack of finance ===\nMarginal farmers found it very difficult to get [[Financing|finance]] and [[credit]] at economical rates from the government and banks and hence, fell as easy prey to the [[Moneylender|money lenders]]. They took loans from [[landlords]], who charged high rates of [[interest]]s and also exploited the farmers later on to work in their fields to repay the loans ([[farm labourer]]s).{{citation needed|date=November 2016}} Proper financing was not given during the Green Revolution period, which created a lot of problems and sufferings to the farmers of India. Government also helped those under loans.\n\n=== Low Productivity ===\nIn the context of India's rapidly growing population, the country's traditional agricultural practices yielded insufficient food production. By the 1960s, this low productivity led India to experience food grain shortages that were more severe than those of other developing countries. Agricultural technological advancements offered opportunities to increase productivity.<ref name=\":22\"/>\n\n== Criticisms of the Green Revolution ==\nThe Green Revolution yielded great economic prosperity during its early years. In Punjab, where it was first introduced, the Green Revolution led to significant increases in the state's agricultural output, supporting India\u2019s overall economy. By 1970, Punjab was producing 70 percent of the country's total food grains,<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite journal|last=Sandhu|first=Jashandeep Singh|date=2014|title=Green Revolution: A Case Study of Punjab|url=|journal=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress|volume=75|pages=1192\u20131199|via=JSTOR}}</ref> and farmers' incomes were increasing by over 70 percent.<ref name=\":02\" /> Punjab's prosperity following the Green Revolution became a model to which other states aspired to reach.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/violenceofgreen00shiv|title=The Violence of the green revolution : ecological degredation and political conflict|last=Shiva, Vandana.|date=1991|publisher=Zed|isbn=0-86232-964-7|oclc=24740968|url-access=registration}}</ref>\n\nHowever, despite the initial prosperity experienced in Punjab, the Green Revolution was met with much controversy throughout India.\n\n=== Indian Economic Sovereignty ===\nCriticism of the effects of the green revolution include the cost for many small farmers using HYV seeds, with their associated demands of increased irrigation systems and pesticides. A case study is found in India, where farmers are buying [[Monsanto]] BT cotton seeds\u2014sold on the idea that these seeds produced 'natural insecticides'. In reality, they need to still pay for expensive pesticides and irrigation systems, which might lead to increased borrowing to finance the change from traditional seed varieties. Many farmers have difficulty in paying for the expensive technologies, especially if they have a bad harvest. These high costs of cultivation push rural farmers to take out loans\u2014typically at high interest rates.<ref name=\":12\"/> Over-borrowing commonly entraps farmers into a cycle of debt.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nOn top of this, India's liberalized economy further exacerbates the farmers's economic conditions. Indian environmentalist [[Vandana Shiva]] writes that this is the \"second Green Revolution\". The first Green Revolution, she suggests, was mostly publicly funded (by the Indian Government). This new Green Revolution, she says, is driven by private (and foreign) interest \u2013 notably MNCs like Monsanto\u2014as encourage by the [[Neoliberalism|neoliberal]] context. Ultimately, this is leading to foreign ownership over most of India's farmland, undermining farmers' interests.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nFarmer's financial issues have become especially apparent in Punjab, where its rural areas have witnessed an alarming rise in suicide rates.<ref name=\":12\" /> Excluding the countless unreported cases, there has been estimated to be a 51.97 per cent increase in the number of suicides in Punjab in 1992-93, compared to the recorded 5.11 per cent increase in the country as a whole.<ref name=\":12\" /> According to a 2019 Indian newspaper, indebtedness continues to be a grave issue affecting Punjabi people today, demonstrated by the more than 900 recorded farmer suicided in Punjab in the last two years.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tribuneindia.com/news/punjab/farm-suicides-unabated-in-punjab-over-900-in-2-years/727671.html|title=Farm suicides unabated in Punjab, over 900 in 2 years|last=Bharti|first=Vishav|date=Feb 12, 2019|work=The Tribune|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n=== Environmental Damage ===\nExcessive and inappropriate use of fertilizers and pesticides polluted waterways and killed beneficial insects and wild life. It has caused [[overexploitation|over-use]] of soil and rapidly depleted its nutrients. The rampant irrigation practices led to eventual [[soil degradation]]. Groundwater practices have fallen dramatically. Further, heavy dependence on few major crops has led to [[Biodiversity loss|loss of biodiversity]] of farmers. These problems were aggravated due to absence of training to use modern technology and vast illiteracy leading to excessive use of chemicals.[https://sol.du.ac.in/mod/book/view.php?id=1735&chapterid=1695]\n\n=== Increased Regional disparities ===\nThe green revolution spread only in irrigated and high-potential rainfed areas. The villages or regions without the access of sufficient water were left out that widened the regional disparities between adopters and non-adopters. Since, the HYV seeds technically can be applied only in a land with assured water supply and availability of other inputs like chemicals, fertilizers etc. The application of the new technology in the dry-land areas is simply ruled out.\n\nThe states like Punjab, Haryana, Western UP etc. having good irrigation and other infrastructure facilities were able to derive the benefits of the green revolution and achieve faster economic development while other states have recorded slow growth in agriculture production.{{citation needed|date=April 2019}}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{India topics}}\n{{Agriculture in India}}\n\n[[Category:Agricultural revolutions]]\n[[Category:History of agriculture in India]]\n[[Category:Intensive farming]]\n[[Category:History of the Republic of India]]\n[[Category:Economic history of India]]\n[[Category:Indira Gandhi administration]]\n[[Category:History of Punjab, India (1947\u2013present)]]\n", "name_user": "Priyadarshi Mukhopadhyay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Green_Revolution_in_India"}
{"title_page": "Alessandro Del Piero", "text_new": "{{redirect|Del Piero|the Italian Brazilian footballer|Yago Del Piero}}\n{{short description|Italian footballer}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name = Alessandro Del Piero\n| image = Alessandro Del Piero in 2014.jpg\n| image_size = \n| caption = Del Piero with [[Sydney FC]] in 2014\n| fullname = Alessandro Del Piero\n| birth_date = {{birth date and age|1974|11|09|df=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Conegliano]], Italy\n| height = <!-- PLEASE DO NOT CHANGE THIS TO 1.75M or 1.73M; THE SOURCE SAYS 1.74M! !-->{{height|m=1.74}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alessandrodelpiero.com/profilo/passaporto.html |title=Alessandro Del Piero, passaporto |publisher=Alessandrodelpiero.com |date=}}</ref>\n| position = [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n| youthyears1 = 1982\u20131988\n| youthclubs1 = San Vendemiano\n| youthyears2 = 1988\u20131991\n| youthclubs2 = [[Calcio Padova|Padova]]\n| years1 = 1991\u20131993\n| clubs1 = [[Calcio Padova|Padova]]\n| caps1 = 14\n| goals1 = 1\n| years2 = 1993\u20132012\n| clubs2 = [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]\n| caps2 = <!-- DO NOT CHANGE THIS TO 705 !-->513<!-- IT IS FOR LEAGUE APPEARANCES AND GOALS ONLY !-->\n| goals2 = 208<!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES AND GOALS ONLY !-->\n| years3 = 2012\u20132014\n| clubs3 = [[Sydney FC]]\n| caps3 = 48\n| goals3 = 24<!-- LEAGUE APPEARANCES AND GOALS ONLY !-->\n| years4 = 2014\n| clubs4 = [[Delhi Dynamos FC|Delhi Dynamos]]\n| caps4 = 10\n| goals4 = 1\n| totalcaps = 585\n| totalgoals = 234\n| medaltemplates = {{Medal|Sport|Men's [[Association football|football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|ITA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|Winner|[[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 Germany]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Football Championship|UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[UEFA Euro 2000|2000 Belgium-Netherlands]]|}}\n| nationalyears1 = 1991\n| nationalteam1 = [[Italy national under-17 football team|Italy U17]]\n| nationalcaps1 = 3\n| nationalgoals1 = 1\n| nationalyears2 = 1992\u20131993\n| nationalteam2 = [[Italy national under-18 football team|Italy U18]]\n| nationalcaps2 = 14\n| nationalgoals2 = 12\n| nationalyears3 = 1993\u20131996\n| nationalteam3 = [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italy U21]]\n| nationalcaps3 = 12\n| nationalgoals3 = 3\n| nationalyears4 = 1995\u20132008\n| nationalteam4 = [[Italy national football team|Italy]]\n| nationalcaps4 = 91\n| nationalgoals4 = 27\n}}\n\n'''Alessandro Del Piero''' {{postnominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit of the Italian Republic|Ufficiale OMRI]]}}<ref name=\"5th class\"/><ref name=\"4th class\"/> ({{IPA-it|ales\u02c8sandro del \u02c8pje\u02d0ro}}; born 9 November 1974) is an Italian former professional [[Association football|footballer]] who mainly played as a [[Forward (association football)#Second-striker|deep-lying forward]], although he was capable of playing in several offensive positions.<ref name=\"Alessandro Del Piero and Roberto Carlos touted for A-League coaching roles\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/oct/12/alessandro-del-piero-and-roberto-carlos-touted-for-a-league-coaching-roles|title=Alessandro Del Piero and Roberto Carlos touted for A-League coaching roles|newspaper=The Guardian|author1=Mike Hytner|date=12 October 2015|accessdate=15 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/65304/agent-%E2%80%99del-piero-could-retire%E2%80%99|title=Agent: \u2019Del Piero could retire\u2019|publisher=Football Italia|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com.au/story/2284516/juventus-should-not-sell-paul-pogba-says-alessandro-del-piero|title=Juventus shouldn't sell Paul Pogba, says Alessandro Del Piero|publisher=ESPN FC|author=Ben Gladwell|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2015/02/06/8673782/del-piero-berlusconi-wanted-me-at-ac-milan-and-now-im-a-free|title=Del Piero: Berlusconi wanted me at AC Milan and now I'm a free agent...|website=goal.com|publisher=Goal.com|author=Mark Doyle|accessdate=4 May 2015}}</ref> Since 2015, he has worked as a [[pundit]] for [[Sky Sport (Italy)|Sky Sport Italia]].<ref name=\"Del Piero wants coaching career\">{{cite news|url=http://gazzettaworld.gazzetta.it/news/del-piero-coaching-career/?refresh_ce-cp|title=Del Piero wants coaching career|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|author1=David Schiavone|date=10 October 2015|accessdate=15 October 2015}}</ref>\n\nA technically gifted<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archivio.panorama.it/archivio/Totti-e-Del-Piero-sulla-via-del-Portogallo|title=Totti e Del Piero sulla via del Portogallo|publisher=Panorama.it|language=Italian|accessdate=4 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104201326/http://archivio.panorama.it/archivio/Totti-e-Del-Piero-sulla-via-del-Portogallo|archive-date=4 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and creative supporting forward<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ilsole24ore.com/art/notizie/2014-04-13/a-league-piero-assist-man-sydney-playoff-120107.shtml?uuid=AB1nHdAB|title=A-League: Del Piero assist-man, Sydney ai playoff|newspaper=Il Sole 24 Ore|language=Italian|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio/fantasisti/fantasisti/fantasisti.html|title=Del Piero, Totti e Baggio la fantasia al potere|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=6 October 2001|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> who was also a [[Direct free kick|free-kick specialist]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/news-and-comment/the-ten-best-freekick-specialists-1785081.html?action=gallery&ino=6|title=The Ten Best Free-Kick Specialists: Alessandro Del Piero|newspaper=The Independent|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/newscentre/features/news/newsid=1551015/index.html|title=Kings of the free-kick|publisher=FIFA.com|accessdate=4 January 2015}}</ref> Del Piero is widely regarded by players, pundits, and managers as one of the greatest players of his generation<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sydneyfc.com/about/hall-of-fame/80mnrsphkdzl11ubdivxz99ov|title=Hall Of Fame \u2013 Sydney FC|publisher=Sydney FC|accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/blog/2014/jan/31/alessandro-del-piero-sydney-fc-australia|title=Alessandro Del Piero walks the line in Sydney but is still sensational|newspaper=The Guardian|author1=Barney Ronay|date=31 January 2014|accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref> and as one of the best Italian players of all time,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilpost.it/2014/11/09/alessandro-del-piero-trofei/|title=Tutti i trofei vinti da Alessandro Del Piero|publisher=[[Il Post]]|language=Italian|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"AFS Top-100 Players of All-Time\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/afstop100.html|title=AFS Top-100 Players of All-Time|website=RSSSF|author1=Marcelo Leme de Arruda|date=14 December 2007|accessdate=19 August 2015}}</ref> winning the [[Serie A Italian Footballer of the Year]] award in 1998 and 2008. A prolific goal-scorer, he is currently the [[Football records in Italy#Highest-scoring Italian players in all competitions|second highest all-time Italian top-scorer in all competitions]], with 346 goals, behind only [[Silvio Piola]], with 390 goals; he is also the joint ninth highest goalscorer in [[Football records in Italy#Goalscoring|Serie A history]], with 188 goals, alongside [[Giuseppe Signori]] and [[Alberto Gilardino]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.calcionews360.net/2012/07/ciao-alex-del-piero-buona-nuova-avventura.html|title=Ciao Alex Del Piero, buona nuova avventura|publisher=Calcionews360.net|accessdate=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131012064944/http://www.calcionews360.net/2012/07/ciao-alex-del-piero-buona-nuova-avventura.html|archivedate=12 October 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/nazionali/?action=read&idnet=dHV0dG9uYXppb25hbGkuY29tLTIzOTA|title=Capitani Azzurri: Alessandro Del Piero (2004\u20132008) \u2013 Nazionali \u2013 TMW |publisher=Tuttomercatoweb.com |date=20 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2012/gennaio/26/Festa_Del_Piero_Questa_maglia_ga_10_120126051.shtml|title=Festa Del Piero \"Questa maglia mi rende speciale\"|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=26 January 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Milan/16-09-2009/7-vite-inzaghi-501316594152.shtml|title=Le 7 vite di Inzaghi I numeri magici di SuperPippo|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|date=16 September 2009|accessdate=13 October 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportmediaset.mediaset.it/mercato/mercato/articoli/70877/inzaghi-riflessioni-sul-futuro.shtml|title=Inzaghi, riflessioni sul futuro. Via dal Milan, Italia o Stati Uniti|publisher=Mediaset.it|language=Italian|date=28 October 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/serie_a/juventus/2010/03/15-60075/Del+Piero+a+quota+301+gol+in+carriera%3A+nel+mirino+c%27%C3%A8+Inzaghi|title=Del Piero a quota 301 gol in carriera: nel mirino c'\u00e8 Inzaghi|newspaper=Tuttosport|language=Italian|date=15 March 2010|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141006100558/http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/serie_a/juventus/2010/03/15-60075/Del+Piero+a+quota+301+gol+in+carriera%3A+nel+mirino+c%27%C3%A8+Inzaghi|archivedate=6 October 2014}}</ref> After beginning his career with Italian club [[Padova Calcio|Padova]] in [[Serie B]] in 1991, he moved to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] in 1993, where he played for 19 seasons (11 as [[Captain (association football)|captain]]), and holds the club records for most [[List of Juventus F.C. records and statistics#Goalscorers|goals]] (290) and [[List of Juventus F.C. records and statistics#Appearances|appearances]] (705). During his time at the club, he won six [[Serie A]] titles, the [[Coppa Italia]], four [[Supercoppa Italiana]] titles, the [[UEFA Champions League]], the [[UEFA Super Cup]], the [[UEFA Intertoto Cup]], and the [[Intercontinental Cup (football)|Intercontinental Cup]]. After leaving the club in 2012, he also spent two seasons with Australian side [[Sydney FC]]; he retired after a season with [[Delhi Dynamos FC]] in the [[Indian Super League]], in 2014.\n\nDel Piero has scored in every competition in which he has participated.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/serie_a/juventus/2008/12/29-13455/Juve%2C+come+Del+Piero+nessuno+mai|title=Juve, come Del Piero nessuno mai|newspaper=Tuttosport|language=Italian|date=29 December 2008|access-date=22 October 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202120917/http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/serie_a/juventus/2008/12/29-13455/Juve%2C+come+Del+Piero+nessuno+mai|archive-date=2 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> In 2004, he was named in the [[FIFA 100]], a list of the 125 greatest living footballers selected by [[Pel\u00e9]] as a part of [[FIFA]]'s centenary celebrations.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/3533833.stm|title=Fifa names greatest list|work=[[BBC Sport]]|date=4 March 2004|accessdate =12 April 2010}}</ref> In the same year, he was also voted into the [[UEFA Golden Jubilee Poll]], a list of the 50 best European players of the past 50 years.<ref>[http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/uefa-awards.html \"UEFA Awards\"]. ''RSSSF''.</ref> Along with six awards in Italy for gentlemanly conduct,<ref name=Alex>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/uk/news/detail.aspx?lml_language_id=0&trs_id=1370000&ID=7782|title=Two awards for Alex|publisher=Juventus|date=10 May 2006|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071014055024/http://juventus.com/uk/news/detail.aspx?lml_language_id=0&trs_id=1370000&ID=7782 |archivedate=14 October 2007 |url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20051031145935/http://www.juventus.com/fmknet/View.aspx?da_id=4871 \"Comunicato Stampa\"] (in Italian). Retrieved 26 May 2012.</ref> he has also won the [[Golden Foot]] award, which pertains to personality as well as playing ability.\n\nAt international level, Del Piero has also represented the [[Italy national football team|Italian national team]] at three [[FIFA World Cup]]s and four [[UEFA European Football Championship]]s, most notably winning the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]], and reaching the final of [[UEFA Euro 2000]] with Italy. He is the joint [[Italy national football team#Top goalscorers|fourth highest scorer for the Italian national team]], with 27 goals, alongside [[Roberto Baggio]], and behind only Silvio Piola with 30 goals, [[Giuseppe Meazza]] with 33 goals, and [[Luigi Riva]] with 35 goals; with 91 appearances for Italy between 1995 and 2008, he is also his nation's [[Italy national football team records#Appearances|eleventh-most capped player of all-time]].\n\n== Early life ==\nAlessandro Del Piero was born in [[Conegliano]], Veneto. Del Piero is the son of Gino, an electrician, and Bruna, a housekeeper.<ref name=\"Sportstar\"/> He regularly played football in the backyard with two friends, Nelso and Pierpaolo, as a child. All three dreamed of becoming footballers, but only Alessandro would eventually manage to do so.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200106/28/3b3b488301d3a/ |title=Le luci di Del Piero |work=Raisport.rai.it |language=Italian |date=28 June 2001 |accessdate=26 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120513201816/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/200106/28/3b3b488301d3a/ |archive-date=13 May 2012 |url-status=dead  }}</ref> Alessandro's older brother, Stefano, briefly played professional football for [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] before an injury curtailed his career; he later worked as Alessandro's agent.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Juventus/18-07-2009/stefano-piero-juve-scelta-cuore-50796353526.shtml|title=Stefano Del Piero: \"Juve scelta di cuore\"|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=18 July 2009|accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref> The family lived in the hamlet of Saccon, a rural home in [[San Vendemiano]].<ref name=itbiografie.com>{{cite web|url=http://itbiografie.com/biografie/Alessandro%20Del%20Piero-1399.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060715145522/http://itbiografie.com/biografie/Alessandro%20Del%20Piero-1399.html|archivedate=15 July 2006|title=Del Piero biografie |publisher=ItBiografie.com|language=Italian|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> While growing up, Del Piero's family did not have much money for travelling abroad, so he considered being a lorry driver in order to see the world.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Alessandro Del Piero: \"Se avessi saputo dire: \"Pap\u00e0, ti voglio bene\"\"|url=http://www.vanityfair.it/people/italia/2012/04/17/alessandro-del-piero-intervista-vanity-fair|magazine=Vanity Fair|language=Italian|author1=Giovanni Audiffredi|date=17 April 2012|accessdate=3 June 2014}}</ref>\n\nWhile playing for the local youth team of San Vendemiano,<ref name=\"kicker\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kicker.de/news/fussball/wm/spielplan/spielersteckbrief/object/22317/saison/2006 |title=Del Piero profile|publisher=Kicker.de|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> Del Piero used to feature as a [[Goalkeeper (association football)|goalkeeper]], in order to gain more playing time. His mother thought it would be better for him to play in this role as he would not sweat, and the possibility of him getting injured was less likely. His brother Stefano commented to their mother that, due to his skill, Alessandro was more suited to playing in a more offensive position, and Del Piero switched to a [[Forward (association football)|forward]] role.<ref name=itbiografie.com/>\n\n== Club career ==\n\n=== 1991\u20131993: Early career and debut with Padova ===\nDel Piero began his rise to professional football in 1981, in the ranks of San Vendemiano. In 1988, Del Piero was first spotted by scouts, and he left home at the young age of 13 to play with the youth side of [[Padova Calcio|Padova]].<ref name=\"iht\"/> He joined the senior side during the [[1991\u201392 Serie B|1991\u201392 season]], at the age of 16, and at the age of 17, he made his d\u00e9but in [[Serie B]] against [[Messina F.C.|Messina]], under manager Mauro Sandreani, on 15 March 1992, coming on as a substitute for Roberto Putelli.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.padovaoggi.it/sport/alessandro-del-piero-compleanno-40-anni-esordio.html|title=Auguri Del Piero, dal Padova alla Juve: come si divente leggenda|trans-title=Happy birthday Del Piero, from Padova to Juve: how one becomes a legend|website=padovaoggi.it|publisher=Padova Oggi|language=it|author=Gloria Callarelli|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> The [[1992\u201393 Serie B|following season]], on 22 November 1992, he scored his first professional goal in a 5\u20130 victory over [[Ternana Calcio|Ternana]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.padova24ore.it/eventi-e-mondanita/2161-alessandro-del-piero-racconta-i-primi-anni-nel-calcio-che-conta-a-padova.html|title=Alessandro Del Piero racconta i primi anni nel calcio che conta a Padova|publisher=Padova 24 Ore|language=Italian|accessdate=16 March 2010}}</ref> In 1993, thanks to [[Giampiero Boniperti]], Del Piero was bought by [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] for five [[billion (short scale)|billion]] [[Italian lire|lire]], with an overlap of 150&nbsp;million lire per season.<ref name=TrePassiNelFuturoJuve>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1994/marzo/21/Del_Piero_tre_passi_nel_co_0_94032115764.shtml|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616134806/http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1994/marzo/21/Del_Piero_tre_passi_nel_co_0_94032115764.shtml|archivedate=16 June 2013|title=Del Piero, tre passi nel futuro Juve|periodical=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=21 March 1994|accessdate=17 August 2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Juventus ===\n\n==== 1993\u20131998: Early domestic and European success ====\nIn 1993, Del Piero transferred to [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] and played for the Torinese club for 19 seasons until being released in the summer of 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Festa per il capitano Del Piero|url=http://www3.lastampa.it/sport/sezioni/quijuve/articolo/lstp/322452/|work=[[La Stampa]]|date=12 September 2010|language=Italian}}</ref> Although manager [[Giovanni Trapattoni]] insisted that he trained with the senior team, he initially played with the [[Juventus F.C. Youth Sector|Primavera squad]], which was coached by [[Antonello Cuccureddu]], helping the Juventus Youth team to win both the [[1994 Torneo di Viareggio]], and the 1994 [[Campionato Nazionale Primavera|U-20 Scudetto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/juve/it/news/accadde%20oggi%20primavera%2025giugno2011%20news|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150602010434/http://www.juventus.com/juve/it/news/accadde%20oggi%20primavera%2025giugno2011%20news|url-status=dead|archive-date=2 June 2015|title=25 giugno 1994, Primavera tricolore|publisher=Juventus.com|accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref> Del Piero made his [[Serie A]] debut against [[Foggia Calcio|Foggia]] on 12 September 1993 under Trapattoni, as a substitute, and he scored his first goal in his next game against [[A.C. Reggiana 1919|Reggiana]] on 19 September, after coming off the bench once again. On his full debut for Juventus, he netted a [[hat-trick]] against [[Parma F.C.|Parma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehardtackle.com/2012/juventus-corner-what-del-piero-means-to-fans/|title=Juventus Corner : What Del Piero Means To Fans|publisher=The Hard Tackle|date=21 May 2012}}</ref> After his promising performances, Del Piero began to be deployed with more continuity, and he managed 14 appearances for Juventus that season between [[Juventus F.C. Youth Sector|youth matches]], league matches, the [[1993\u201394 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]], and the [[1993\u201394 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]], scoring 5 goals, which all came in [[1993\u201394 Serie A|Serie A]], as Juventus finished the season in second place in the league.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1994/marzo/21/Del_Piero_tre_passi_nel_co_0_94032115764.shtml|title=Del Piero, tre passi nel futuro Juve Del Piero, tre passi nel futuro Juve|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=21 March 1994|accessdate=7 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe next season saw [[Marcello Lippi]] take over as Juventus manager, as well as the introduction of a new team of directors, made up of Giraudo, [[Roberto Bettega]], and [[Luciano Moggi]]; Del Piero played a more prominent role for the club that season following [[Roberto Baggio]]'s injury in November against [[Padova Calcio|Padova]]. Del Piero temporarily took his place in the first team alongside [[Gianluca Vialli]] and [[Fabrizio Ravanelli]], flourishing at the opportunity given to him, and Juventus went on to claim their first ''[[1994\u201395 Serie A|Scudetto]]'' in nine years. Del Piero scored 8 goals in Serie A that season, including a match-winning chipped volley against [[ACF Fiorentina|Fiorentina]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportmediaset.mediaset.it/calcio/fiorentina/2014/articoli/1052877/fiorentina-juventus-20-anni-fa-il-super-gol-di-del-piero.shtml|title=Fiorentina-Juventus, 20 anni fa il super gol di Del Piero|publisher=Mediaset.it|language=Italian|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> Del Piero was also able to achieve a rare double, and he captured the [[1994\u201395 Coppa Italia]] with Juventus, defeating their season rivals [[Parma F.C.|Parma]] in the final, although they were defeated by Parma in the [[1995 UEFA Cup Final]].<ref name=\"Euro 2008: Alex Del Piero\">{{cite news|url=http://temi.repubblica.it/nuovavenezia-europei2008/2008/05/23/alex-del-piero/?h=1|title=Euro 2008: Alex Del Piero|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=23 May 2008|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> During this time, Del Piero earned the nickname ''\"[[Pinturicchio]]\"'', due to the similarity between his own technical and tactical characteristics, and Baggio's creative style of play.<ref name=\"DEL PIERO, FESTA TRADITA\">{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1994/03/14/del-piero-festa-tradita.html|title=DEL PIERO, FESTA TRADITA|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=14 March 1994|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> This nickname arose when former president [[Gianni Agnelli]] compared the emerging talent Del Piero to the renaissance artist Pinturicchio, who was the student of the great Italian renaissance artist ''\"[[Raphael|Rafaello]]\"'', a nickname he had used to describe Baggio, to emphasise his elegance on the ball.<ref name=\"Sportstar\"/> Del Piero placed fourth in the [[1995 Ballon d'Or]] for his performances throughout the season.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy95.html|title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 1995|website=RSSSF|author1=Jos\u00e9 Luis Pierrend|date=26 March 2005|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref> With the Turin club, Del Piero won the Serie A eight times, although the 2005 and 2006 titles were revoked due to Juventus's involvement in the [[2006 Italian football scandal]].<ref name=\"Punishments cut for Italian clubs\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/5215178.stm|title=Punishments cut for Italian clubs|work=BBC Sport|date=26 July 2006}}</ref>\n\nFor the [[1995\u201396 Serie A|1995\u201396 season]], Del Piero was awarded Baggio's [[Squad number (association football)|number 10 shirt]] (which had also previously belonged to [[Michel Platini]]), following his departure to [[A.C. Milan]]. Del Piero scored 6 goals and provided 10 assists in Serie A, although Juventus finished the season in second place behind Milan. Del Piero did manage to capture the [[1995 Supercoppa Italiana|Supercoppa Italiana in 1995]], over Parma, setting up Vialli's only goal of the match.<ref name=\"Euro 2008: Alex Del Piero\"/> He also played a key role in helping Juventus to win the [[1995\u201396 UEFA Champions League]], scoring 6 goals in the competition, and finishing as the second highest scorer of the tournament.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://temi.repubblica.it/ilpiccolo-europei2008/2008/05/23/alex-del-piero/?printpage=undefined|title=Alex Del Piero|website=repubblica.it|publisher=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=23 May 2008|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe following season, Del Piero followed these victories up with the [[1996 UEFA Super Cup]] and the [[1996 Intercontinental Cup]], scoring goals in both finals, and being named Man of the Match in the latter final; he also won the [[Bravo Award]] (as the best u-23 player in European Competitions), and placed 4th in the [[1996 Ballon d'Or]] for the second consecutive year.<ref name=\"Euro 2008: Alex Del Piero\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy96.html|title=European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 1996|website=RSSSF|author1=Jos\u00e9 Luis Pierrend|date=26 March 2005|accessdate=25 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"IC-MotM\">{{cite web |url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablest/toyotamvp.html |title=Toyota Cup \u2013 Most Valuable Player of the Match Award |website=RSSSF |author1=Marcelo Leme de Arruda |date=29 December 2008 |accessdate=5 May 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090414090937/http://rsssf.com/tablest/toyotamvp.html |archivedate=14 April 2009 |url-status=dead}}</ref> Del Piero also captured his second [[1996\u201397 Serie A|Serie A]] title with Juventus that season, and helped lead Juventus to their second consecutive [[1996\u201397 UEFA Champions League|Champions League final]], although he was unable to start the match due to injury.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1997/maggio/29/Peccato_resta_anno_eccezionale_co_0_9705299999.shtml|title=Peccato, ma resta un anno eccezionale|trans-title=It's a shame, but it's still been an exceptional year|website=corriere.it|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|author=Roberto Perrone|date=29 May 1997|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> During the group stage, en route to the final, he helped Juventus to qualify for the quarter-finals a match early, scoring a goal in Juventus's 1\u20130 win over [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] at [[Old Trafford]], on 20 November 1996; this was the first time that an Italian team had defeated Manchester United at their home ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/1997/ottobre/01/Del_Piero_forza_del_passato_ga_0_9710013139.shtml|title=Del Piero la forza del passato|trans-title=Del Piero the strength of the past|website=gazzetta.it|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=it|author1=Salvatore Lo Presti|author2=Lodovico Maradei|date=1 October 1997|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> In the [[1997 UEFA Champions League Final]], he came off the bench to score a goal with a back-heel, which was, however, unable to prevent Juventus from losing 3\u20131 to [[Borussia Dortmund]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1996/overview/index.html#199697+riedle+makes+dortmunds|title=Riedle makes Dortmund's day|publisher=UEFA|date=28 May 1997|accessdate=10 October 2015}}</ref> Del Piero received nominations for both the [[1997 FIFA World Player of the Year]], finishing sixth<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-awards.html#player10 |title=FIFA Awards \u2013 World Player of the Year \u2013 Top 10 |website=RSSSF |accessdate=31 March 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112042845/http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/fifa-awards.html |archivedate=12 January 2016 }}</ref> and the [[1997 Ballon d'Or]],<ref>{{Cite web| url  = http://www.rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy97.html| title = European Footballer of the Year (\"Ballon d'Or\") 1997| first = Jos\u00e9 Luis| last       = Pierrend| publisher  = [[Rec.Sport.Soccer Statistics Foundation|RSSSF]]| date = 26 March 2005| accessdate = 5 November 2013| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20130314042148/http://rsssf.com/miscellaneous/europa-poy97.html| archivedate=14 March 2013}}</ref> due to his performances throughout the calendar year.\n\nDel Piero began the following campaign strongly by winning the [[1997 Supercoppa Italiana|Supercoppa Italiana once again in 1997]], forming a strong offensive unit with Juventus teammates [[Zinedine Zidane]] in midfield, and newcomer [[Filippo Inzaghi]] upfront. The [[1997\u201398 Serie A|1997\u201398]] campaign was his best season yet, as he scored a joint career best of 21 goals in Serie A, and finished top scorer in the [[1997\u201398 UEFA Champions League]] with 10 goals,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2011/04/25/2457361/alessandro-del-pieros-283-goals-for-juventus-make-him-the|title=Alessandro Del Piero's 283 goals for Juventus make him the greatest one-club marksman in Italy|publisher=Goal.com|date=25 April 2011}}</ref> one of which included a freekick and [[List of UEFA Champions League hat-tricks|a hat-trick]] against [[AS Monaco FC|Monaco]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/1717/editorial/2009/01/06/1044602/calcio-flashback-juventus-4-1-monaco-champions-league-semi-final#|title=Calcio Flashback: Juventus 4\u20131 Monaco (Champions League Semi Final 1998)|publisher=Goal.com|date=6 January 2009}}</ref> With these goals, he helped Juventus to reach their third consecutive [[1998 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League final]], although Del Piero was not fully fit for the match,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/1998/maggio/22/ansia_per_Del_Piero_ga_0_9805227687.shtml|title=in ansia per Del Piero|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=22 May 1998|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> and Juventus were once again defeated, falling 1\u20130 to [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] from a strike by [[Predrag Mijatovi\u0107]] on 20 May.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=1997/overview/index.html#199798+seventh+heaven+madrid|title=1997/98: Seventh heaven for Madrid|publisher=UEFA|date=20 May 1998}}</ref> Domestic success, however, was achieved that season, after a tight battle with [[Inter Milan|Inter]], as Juventus celebrated its 25th Serie A title over their Italian rivals, with Del Piero scoring a memorable and decisive individual match-winning goal during the controversial [[Derby d'Italia]] match.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2009/04/20/1219294/scudetto-of-1998-belongs-to-inter-not-juventus-gigi-simoni|title=Scudetto of 1998 Belongs To Inter, Not Juventus \u2013 Gigi Simoni|publisher=Goal.com|date=20 April 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1998/aprile/27/Juve_scudetto_dei_veleni_vicino_co_0_9804271357.shtml|title=Juve, lo scudetto dei veleni e' vicino|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=27 April 1998|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> Del Piero also managed a goal in the [[1997\u201398 Coppa Italia]] that season, helping Juventus to the semi-finals, and finishing the season with a career best of 32 goals in all competitions. Del Piero was awarded the [[Serie A Italian Footballer of the Year]] award for his performances,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/199809/22/3607ef0f06e63/|title=La notte degli Oscar|trans-title=Oscar night|website=rai.it|publisher=Rai Sport|language=it|date=22 September 1998|accessdate=28 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151208154017/http://www2.raisport.rai.it/news/sport/calcio/199809/22/3607ef0f06e63/|archive-date=8 December 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and he was also nominated for the [[1998 Ballon d'Or]]. During this time, he was nicknamed by the fans as \"Il Fenomeno Vero\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kom.it/eurocalcio/dbase/200.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160314012056/http://www.kom.it/eurocalcio/dbase/200.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=14 March 2016|title=Alex Del Piero Fenomeno Vero |work=Eurocalcio News|language=Italian|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> meaning \"The Real Phenomenon\", in comparison with the Brazilian striker [[Ronaldo (Brazilian footballer)|Ronaldo]], who was nicknamed ''\"Il Fenomeno\"'' by supporters of rivals [[Inter Milan|Internazionale]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2008/02_Febbraio/13/ronaldoinfortuni_1302.shtml|title=Un Fenomeno di sfortuna Tutti gli infortuni di Ronaldo|trans-title=An unfortunate Phenomenon: All of Ronaldo's injuries|website=gazzetta.it|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=it|date=13 February 2008|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== 1998\u20132001: Injury struggles ====\nJuventus began the [[1998\u201399 Serie A|1998\u201399 season]] with a 2\u20131 defeat in the [[1998 Supercoppa Italiana]] at the hands of [[S.S. Lazio|Lazio]], although Del Piero was able to score from a penalty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1998/agosto/30/Lazio_una_Supercoppa_aspettando_Vieri_co_0_9808305771.shtml|title=Lazio, una Supercoppa aspettando Vieri|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|author1=Giancarlo Padovan|author2=Stefano Agresti|date=30 August 1998|accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref> On 8 November 1998, Del Piero picked up a serious knee injury in the final minutes of a 2\u20132 draw with [[Udinese Calcio|Udinese]];<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1998/novembre/10/Campionato_gia_finito_per_Del_co_0_9811107957.shtml|title=Campionato gia' finito per Del Piero infortunato|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=10 November 1998|accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref><ref name=footballspeak.com>{{cite web|url=http://footballspeak.com/post/2012/03/25/Flashback-Juventus-2-3-Man-Utd.aspx|title=Flashback \u2013 Juventus 2\u20133 Man Utd. 1999 CL semi final|publisher=Football Speak|date=25 March 2012|access-date=11 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120625162145/http://footballspeak.com/post/2012/03/25/Flashback-Juventus-2-3-Man-Utd.aspx|archive-date=25 June 2012|url-status=dead}}</ref> this kept him out of action for the remainder of the season, as he managed only 2 goals. The club struggled without him, finishing the league season in a disappointing sixth place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital99.html|title=Italy 1998/99|website=RSSSF|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> Juventus did manage to reach the semi-finals of the [[1998\u201399 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] that season, however, losing out to eventual Champions Manchester United.<ref name=footballspeak.com/> Following his serious injury, Del Piero underwent a muscle strengthening regime in order to adapt to the increasingly more physical and athletic demands of twenty-first century football, which allowed him to compensate for the loss of some of his pace and agility.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football-drugs-in-serie-a---italy-sinking-deeper-into-scandal-1178042.html|title=Football: Drugs in Serie A \u2013 Italy sinking deeper into scandal|website=independent.co.uk|publisher=The Independent|author=Andrew Warshaw|date=13 October 1998|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref> Due to his dramatic weight gain and physical development during this period, as well as the club's success during the mid to late 90s,<ref name=UEFA>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=262717.html|title=Juve doctor convicted of doping|publisher=[[Union of European Football Associations]] (UEFA)|accessdate=26 November 2004}}</ref> Del Piero, along with several other Juventus players and staff members, was claimed of being involved in illegal performance-enhancing drug abuse;<ref name=UEFA/> after a lengthy investigation, the club's staff members incriminated were eventually cleared of all doping allegations in 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/11/01/sports/soccer/01iht-SOCCER.html|title=A Reminder of the Beautiful Game|website=nytimes.com|publisher=The New York Times|author=Bob Hughes|date=31 October 2010|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/352199/juventus-team-doctor-acquitted-in-doping-case|title=Juventus team doctor acquitted in doping case|website=espnfc.com|publisher=ESPN FC|date=14 December 2005|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nDuring the next season under new manager [[Carlo Ancelotti]], Del Piero primarily served as an assist-man, providing 14 assists in Serie A, the most in the league that season, and 20 in all competitions.<ref name=\"Serie A 1999/2000\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-lineups.com/tourn/Serie_A_1999-2000/stats/top_goal_scorers/|title=Serie A 1999/2000|publisher=football-lineups.com|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> He faced criticism, however, for his inability to score in open play following his injury the previous season, as only one of his 9 Serie A goals that season was in open play (a header against Parma), with the rest coming from penalties.<ref name=\"Serie A 1999/2000\"/> Furthermore, towards the end of the season, his once excellent attacking partnership with Inzaghi became less effective, due to Inzaghi's individualism, as well as the pair's lack of understanding and strained relationship both on and off the pitch.<ref name=\"tale\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/apr/09/sport.comment1|title=The wonderful tale of Mamma Inzaghi and her boys|newspaper=The Guardian|author1=Simon Kuper|date=9 April 2000|accessdate=27 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"blob\">{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/15-09-2016/blob-trapattoni-strunz-era-tutto-programmato-piero-sfotte-17063198270.shtml|title=Il blob: Trapattoni-Strunz, era tutto programmato. E Del Piero sfotte...|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Ivan Palumbo|date=16 September 2016|accessdate=18 March 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"feeling\">{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2000/aprile/05/Del_Piero_Inzaghi_poco_feeling_ga_0_00040512322.shtml|title=Del Piero Inzaghi, poco feeling|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Silvano Stella|author2=Paolo Forcolin|date=5 April 2000|accessdate=19 March 2017}}</ref> Del Piero helped Juventus to capture the [[1999 UEFA Intertoto Cup]] that season, which allowed Juventus to qualify for the [[1999\u20132000 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]; overall, he scored 12 goals in all competitions, as Juventus narrowly missed out on the [[1999\u20132000 Serie A|Serie A]] title. In 2000, Del Piero was the world's best-paid football player from salaries, bonuses, and advertising revenue.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/jun/24/euro2000.sport8|title=Del Piero fuels passionate debate|newspaper=The Guardian|author1=Paddy Agnew|date=24 June 2000|accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe following season saw Juventus suffer another disappointing defeat losing out on the [[2000\u201301 Serie A|Serie A title]] once again, to [[A.S. Roma|Roma]]. Juventus and Del Piero began the season strongly, and Del Piero scored the winner on his season debut against [[S.S.C. Napoli|Napoli]] on 30 September,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://azzurrissimo.it/2011/11/29/napoli-juventus-i-precedenti-e-le-curiosita/|title=NAPOLI-JUVENTUS. I precedenti e le curiosit\u00e0|publisher=azzurrissimo.it|language=Italian|date=29 November 2011|accessdate=20 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020190358/http://azzurrissimo.it/2011/11/29/napoli-juventus-i-precedenti-e-le-curiosita/|archive-date=20 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> although he later suffered another injury and fell out of form, failing to score. On 18 February 2001, Del Piero broke his goal drought, scoring in an away win over [[F.C. Bari 1908|Bari]]. Del Piero celebrated the goal by dedicating it to his father, who had recently died.<ref name=\"\u00e8 tornato Del Piero\">{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2001/febbraio/19/Esulta_Juve_tornato_Del_Piero_co_0_0102198415.shtml|title=Esulta la Juve, \u00e8 tornato Del Piero|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=19 February 2001|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> Del Piero refound his form towards the end of the season, although he was unable to help Juventus capture the Serie A title, despite scoring a goal in a 2\u20132 draw against Roma.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2001/03/17/del-piero-torna-leader-restero-alla-juventus.html|title=Del Piero torna leader Rester\u00f2 alla Juventus|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=17 March 2001|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n==== 2001\u20132004: New successes ====\nDel Piero was named Juventus captain upon Lippi's return to Juventus, and he formed a formidable offensive partnership with French striker [[David Trezeguet]], who joined in 2000, and Czech playmaker [[Pavel Nedv\u011bd]], who arrived in 2001. Del Piero scored 16 goals and provided several assists, as Juventus were crowned [[2001\u201302 Serie A|Serie A champions]] for a 26th time on 5 May 2002, the last match day of the season; Juventus won the title over Roma and Inter by a single point, after a 2\u20130 away victory over Udinese, with goals from [[Capocannoniere|top-scorer]] Trezeguet and Del Piero.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thesefootballtimes.co/2016/07/16/the-great-serie-a-title-race-of-2001-02/|title=The great Serie A title race of 2001\u201302|publisher=thesefootballtimes.co|date=16 July 2016|accessdate=20 November 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161121172143/http://thesefootballtimes.co/2016/07/16/the-great-serie-a-title-race-of-2001-02/|archive-date=21 November 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Del Piero managed 21 goals in all competitions, also scoring his 100th and 101st goals for Juventus that season, against [[A.C. Venezia|Venezia]], on 26 August 2001.<ref name=\"Del Piero bussa alla storia\">{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2006/ottobre/16/Del_Piero_bussa_alla_storia_ga_10_061016067.shtml|title=Del Piero bussa alla storia|website=gazzetta.it|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Forcolin Paolo|date=16 October 2006|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> Del Piero also helped Juventus reach the [[2002 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia final]] that season, although Juventus were defeated by Parma.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldfootball.net/schedule/ita-coppa-italia-2001-2002-finale/2/|title=Coppa Italia 2001/2002 \u00bb Final|publisher=worldfootball.net|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nJuventus's title success in 2002 enabled the club to automatically qualify for the [[2002\u201303 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] the following season. Juventus began the 2002\u201303 season by winning the [[2002 Supercoppa Italiana]] over Parma, with Del Piero scoring two goals,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/serie_a/juventus/2013/08/16-270094/Supercoppa+Italiana,+la+Juve+cerca+l%27aggancio+al+Milan|title=Supercoppa Italiana, la Juve cerca l'aggancio al Milan|website=tuttosport.com/|publisher=Tuttosport|language=Italian|date=16 August 2013|accessdate=13 April 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150414015025/http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/serie_a/juventus/2013/08/16-270094/Supercoppa+Italiana,+la+Juve+cerca+l%27aggancio+al+Milan|archive-date=14 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and Juventus were also able to successfully defend their [[2002-03 Serie A|Serie A title]].<ref name=\"Tutti i trofei vinti da Alessandro Del Piero\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ilpost.it/2014/11/09/alessandro-del-piero-trofei/|title=Tutti i trofei vinti da Alessandro Del Piero|website=ilpost.it|publisher=Il Post|language=Italian|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> Del Piero scored his 100th goal in Serie A in a 2\u20131 win over [[Brescia Calcio|Brescia]] on 27 April 2003.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio2002_partite_a/juventusbrescia/juventusbrescia/juventusbrescia.html|title=La Juve batte il Brescia 2\u20131 scudetto sempre pi\u00f9 vicino|website=repubblica.it|publisher=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=27 April 2003|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> In the UEFA Champions League, Juventus were placed in Group E alongside [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]], [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]], and [[Feyenoord]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2002/clubs/index.html|title=2002/03 clubs|publisher=UEFA.com|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> Del Piero opened up his account in European competitions that season when he scored his side's second goal in a 5\u20130 victory over Dynamo Kyiv on 24 September, after combining with Nedv\u011bd and [[Mauro Camoranesi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2002/round=1636/match=1036456/index.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130105073421/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2002/round=1636/match=1036456/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 January 2013|title=Electric Juventus power past Dynamo|publisher=UEFA.com|date=24 September 2002}}</ref>\n\nOn the next matchday, Juventus played host to Newcastle on 1 October and Del Piero hit a brace to help his club maintain the top spot in their group.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2002/round=1636/match=1036471/index.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130105133730/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2002/round=1636/match=1036471/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 January 2013|title=Newcastle stung by Del Piero double|publisher=UEFA.com|date=1 October 2002}}</ref> Juventus advanced to the second group stage where the club managed to progress, along with [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]], on goal differential over [[FC Basel]] and [[Deportivo de La Coru\u00f1a]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2002/round=1637/match=1038272/index.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130105152537/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2002/round=1637/match=1038272/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 January 2013|title=Dramatic win not enough for Basel|publisher=UEFA.com|date=18 March 2003}}</ref> Juventus then saw off [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]] in the quarter-finals through an extra time goal by [[Marcelo Zalayeta]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2002/round=1638/match=1041696/index.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130105054705/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2002/round=1638/match=1041696/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 January 2013|title=Zalayeta sends Juventus through|publisher=UEFA.com|date=22 April 2003}}</ref> and faced Spanish opposition again in the likes of defending champions [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] in the semi-finals. The triumvirate attacking partnership proved wonders for Juventus, as the team overturned a 2\u20131 first leg deficit to record a 4\u20133 aggregate win as all three attacking stars netted in a 3\u20131 home win in the second leg.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2002/round=1639/match=1044119/index.html|archive-url=https://archive.today/20130105082259/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/ucl/history/season=2002/round=1639/match=1044119/index.html|url-status=dead|archive-date=5 January 2013|title=Madrid fall to brilliant Nedved|publisher=UEFA.com|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref> Juventus faced Italian rivals [[A.C. Milan|Milan]] in the [[2003 UEFA Champions League Final|Final]] in Manchester on 28 May 2003. After a goalless 120 minutes, the tie went to a penalty shoot-out, where Del Piero finished his spot-kick, but it wasn't enough, as Juventus fell 3\u20132 in the shoot-out.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2002/overview/index.html#200203+shevchenko+spot+milan|title=2002/03: Shevchenko spot on for Milan|publisher=UEFA.com|date=28 May 2003}}</ref>\n\nThe following season saw Juventus start strongly, winning the [[2003 Supercoppa Italiana]] over Milan on penalties, although Juventus were knocked out in the round of 16 in the [[2003\u201304 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]], and finished the [[2003\u201304 Serie A|Serie A]] season in a disappointing third place. The club did manage to reach the final of the [[2004 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia]], however, only to be defeated by Lazio. Lippi left Juventus at the end of the season to take charge of the Italian national team.<ref name=\"Tutti i trofei vinti da Alessandro Del Piero\"/>\n\n==== 2004\u20132006: Calciopoli and relegation ====\nAfter Euro 2004, Juventus manager Marcello Lippi was replaced by [[Fabio Capello]]. Capello was not convinced of Del Piero's fitness levels, and frequently benched him in favour of the younger, new offensive signing [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2008/11/22/Ale.shtml|title=Quando Del Piero era riserva di Ibrahimovic|trans-title=When Del Piero was a reserve for Ibrahimovic|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Luca Curino|date=22 November 2008|accessdate=26 August 2015}}</ref> Despite his limited playing time, Del Piero still managed to score 14 goals as Juventus won their [[2004\u201305 Serie A|28th league title]], due to his overhead assist to teammate David Trezeguet, which proved decisive in a match against Milan at the [[San Siro]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acmilan.com/en/news/show/139248|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055959/http://www.acmilan.com/en/news/show/139248|url-status=dead|archive-date=4 March 2016|title=A match that needs no introduction.|publisher=AC Milan|date=22 February 2012}}</ref> Del Piero also helped Juventus to reach the quarter finals of the [[2004\u201305 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] that season, only losing out to eventual champions [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2004/clubs/club=50139/matches/index.html|title=UEFA Champions League 2004/05 \u2013 History \u2013 Juventus|publisher=uefa.com|accessdate=20 November 2016}}</ref>\n\nSeveral journalists and coaches believed that Del Piero was back to his best form in the [[2005\u201306 Serie A|2005\u201306 season]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2006/febbraio/14/Del_Piero_ringrazia_Capello_Rinato_co_9_060214147.shtml|title=Del Piero ringrazia Capello: \"Rinato grazie al turn over\"|website=corriere.it|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|author1=Arianna Ravelli|date=14 February 2006|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> as he managed 12 goals in Serie A, and 20 goals in all competitions, helping Juventus to defend the Serie A title. His role at Juventus, however, changed during his second season under coach Fabio Capello, who preferred to use him as an \"immediate impact\" substitute.<ref name=\"iht\">{{cite news|url=http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/02/14/sports/soccer.php |title=Del Piero an ace at icing Juventus cake |newspaper=The International Herald Tribune |date=14 February 2006 |accessdate=10 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081014002229/http://www.iht.com/articles/2006/02/14/sports/soccer.php |archivedate=14 October 2008 }}</ref> Due to his lack of playing time, Del Piero's relationship with Fabio Capello was often strained.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttocalciatori.net/notizie-225-del-pierocapello-e-rottura|title=DEL PIERO-CAPELLO: E' ROTTURA|website=tuttocalciatori.net|language=Italian|date=10 May 2006|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 January 2006, Del Piero became the all-time leading goalscorer for Juventus when he scored three times in a Coppa Italia match against Fiorentina, taking his total goal tally for the club to 185. The previous record holder was [[Giampiero Boniperti]], with 182 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/juve/it/news/2011/1/news_newseventi_862c36cf3c834af8ba5faa3f43964364.asp|title=Del Piero supera Boniperti|trans-title=Del Piero overtakes Boniperti|website=juventus.com|language=Italian|date=10 January 2006|accessdate=8 April 2015}}</ref> Del Piero also finished the season as the top scorer of the [[2005\u201306 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]], with 5 goals. Del Piero equalled [[Jos\u00e9 Altafini]]'s Serie A record of six goals as a substitute after scoring in the final minute of Juventus' final game of the 2005\u201306 season,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2005/e/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/38giornata/juventuscagliari1/juventuscagliari1.html|title=La Juve festeggia lo scudetto Poker al Cagliari di Zola|website=repubblica.it|publisher=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=29 May 2005|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref> before Juventus were forcibly relegated due to the ''[[2006 Italian football scandal|Calciopoli]]'' scandal, also having their two most recent Serie A titles revoked.<ref name=\"Punishments cut for Italian clubs\"/>\n\n==== 2006\u20132007: Serie B champions ====\nAfter Juventus were demoted to [[Serie B]] and their two most recent ''Scudetti'' were revoked, Del Piero pledged that he would stay to captain the team. He underlined that players should remain with the team, explaining that \"The [[Agnelli family]] deserve this, as do the fans and the new directors.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/1182539-alex-the-great-a-look-back-at-del-pieros-time-in-turin|title=Alex Del Piero: A Look Back at Alex the Great's Time in Turin|publisher=bleacherreport.com|date=14 May 2012|accessdate=27 July 2016}}</ref> While many key players such as [[Fabio Cannavaro]], [[Emerson Ferreira da Rosa|Emerson]], [[Gianluca Zambrotta]], [[Patrick Vieira]], [[Zlatan Ibrahimovi\u0107]], and [[Lilian Thuram]] left, Del Piero chose to stay and help the club gain promotion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2006/07/sezioni/sport/calcio/calciomercato-2006/buffon-resta/buffon-resta.html|title=Real Madrid, accordo con la Juve per Cannavaro ed Emerson|website=repubblica.it|publisher=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=19 July 2006|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n{{Quote box\n |quote=A true gentleman never leaves his lady.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2005/settembre/01/sfida_piu_difficile_Alex_Del_co_8_050901011.shtml|title=La sfida pi\u00f9 difficile di Alex Del Piero|website=corriere.it|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=1 September 2005|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref>\n |source=Alessandro Del Piero (about the \"Old Lady\", Juventus, during [[2006 Italian football scandal|Calciopoli]])|align=centre\n |quoted=1\n |width=21%\n}}\n[[File:Rimini-juve3.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Del Piero playing for Juventus in September 2006 against [[A.C. Rimini 1912|Rimini]] during the 2006\u201307 Serie B season.]]\nDel Piero's first appearance after the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] triumph was in a [[2006\u201307 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]] match against [[A.C. Cesena|Cesena]] on 23 August 2006. As Juventus played in the Serie B for the 2006\u201307 season, the Coppa Italia campaign became increasingly important for the club in order to achieve a [[2007\u201308 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] spot. Having been on vacation beforehand, Del Piero started on the bench. Juventus and Cesena were locked on 1\u20131 when Del Piero entered in the 74th minute and after nine seconds, he scored the winning goal for Juventus.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071106035544/http://www.juventus.com/it/news/detail.aspx?lml_language_id=0&trs_id=1201000&ID=8488 \"Juventus 2\u20131 al Cesena\" (in Italian)] Juventus.com. 23 August 2006</ref>\n\nDel Piero then came on as a substitute in the 61st minute during Juventus's next Coppa Italia match on 27 August, against Napoli. Once again Juventus came from behind, as Del Piero scored twice to give his team the lead. The match eventually went to penalties; although Del Piero scored his spot-kick, Napoli won 5\u20134 in the [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|penalty shoot-out]].<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071013184836/http://juventus.com/uk/news/detail.aspx?lml_language_id=0&trs_id=1368000&ID=8531 \"Napoli \u2013 Juventus, 3\u20133 a.e.t. (Napoli win 5\u20134 on penalties)\"] Juventus.com. 28 August 2006</ref> Despite starting the season with a nine-point penalty from the match-fixing scandal,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story?id=388100&cc=5901|title=Arbitration board reduces Juventus' points penalty|publisher=ESPN|date=27 October 2006}}</ref> Juventus gained promotion to Serie A as Serie B champions;<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/6673133.stm|title=Juventus win Serie B at a canter|work=BBC Sport|date=19 May 2007}}</ref> Del Piero finished the league campaign as the top scorer of the [[2006\u201307 Serie B]] season, with 20 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital2tops.html |title=Italy \u2013 Serie B Top Scorers |website=RSSSF |accessdate=22 July 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150318052943/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/ital2tops.html |archivedate=18 March 2015  }}</ref> During the season, Del Piero also managed his 200th goal with Juventus on 21 October 2006, in a 1\u20130 league victory over [[Frosinone Calcio|Frosinone]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Squadre/Juventus/Primo_Piano/2006/10_Ottobre/28/ale200.shtml|title=Adesso Del Piero \u00e8 mister 200|website=gazzetta.it|publisher=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=21 October 2006|accessdate=13 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== 2007\u20132011: Return to Serie A and post-Calciopoli struggles ====\n{{Quote box\n |quote=Del Piero never really grows old.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/champions_league/2008/11/06-8686/Del+Piero+%C3%A8+meglio+%27e+Maradona|title=Del Piero \u00e8 meglio 'e Maradona|newspaper=Tuttosport|language=Italian|date=6 November 2008|accessdate=20 October 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222151701/http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/champions_league/2008/11/06-8686/Del+Piero+%C3%A8+meglio+%27e+Maradona|archivedate=22 December 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref>|source=[[Diego Maradona]]|align=centre\n |quoted=1\n |width=20%\n}}\n[[File:Del Piero - Juventus.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Del Piero during the 2007\u201308 season against Fiorentina.]]\nFollowing Juventus's return to Serie A, Del Piero was locked in months of fractious negotiations over the signing of a new contract with Juventus' new management. After successfully negotiating a new contract till 30 June 2010,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2007/10_Ottobre/16/aledelpiero.shtml|title=Del Piero-Juve fino al 2010 Ale: \"Giorni entusiasmanti\"|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Alberto Mauro|date=16 October 2007|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> he was greeted with news of the birth of his first child, Tobias Del Piero.<ref name=\"Del Piero, giorni d'oro E' nato il figlio Tobias\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2007/10_Ottobre/22/del_piero_figlio_2210.shtml|title=Del Piero, giorni d'oro E' nato il figlio Tobias|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=22 October 2007|accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref> This was quite a staggering turnaround in his fortunes, as only two weeks earlier, he was dropped by [[Claudio Ranieri]] for the Serie A match with Fiorentina,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2007/10/sezioni/sport/calcio/serie_a/giornata-7a/fiorentina-juventus/fiorentina-juventus.html|title=Pari con polemiche tra Fiorentina e Juventus|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=7 October 2007|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> and was then axed from [[Roberto Donadoni]]'s [[Italy national football team|Italy squad]] for the games with [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]] and [[South Africa national football team|South Africa]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Nazionale/Primo_Piano/2007/10_Ottobre/07/convocazioni.shtml|title=Nazionale, novit\u00e0 Montolivo A casa Del Piero e Inzaghi|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Gaetano De Stefano|date=7 October 2007|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 December 2007, Del Piero scored two goals away at Lazio and was named to two consecutive Serie A teams of the week.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/serie-a/2007-2008/juventus-edge-lazio_sto1414042/story.shtml|title=Juventus edge Lazio|publisher=Eurosport|date=15 December 2007|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> In February 2008, he scored the winning goal for Juventus from a free-kick in a 1\u20130 Serie A home victory over Roma.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2008/02_Febbraio/16/juv-rom.shtml|title=Del Piero \u00e8 l'anima Juve Roma battuta e avvicinata|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=16 February 2008|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> On 6 April 2008, he set a new appearance record for Juventus, overtaking [[Gaetano Scirea]]'s previous tally of 552 matches in all competitions.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Juventus/Primo_Piano/2008/03_Marzo/24/delpiero.shtml|title=Del Piero, 552 senza tempo|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=24 March 2008|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Palermo/Primo_Piano/2008/04_Aprile/06/palermojuve.shtml|title=Juve, che doccia fredda nel momento pi\u00f9 caldo|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Pier Luigi Todisco|date=6 April 2008|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> In April, he registered seven goals in five Serie A matches, including a hat-trick in a 0\u20134 away win over [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.com/sports/2008/04/20/del_piero_and_kaka_score_hat_tricks.html|title=Del Piero and Kaka score hat tricks|publisher=thestar.com|date=20 April 2008}}</ref>\n\nOn the final weekend of the [[2007\u201308 Serie A|2007\u201308 season]], Del Piero scored a brace against [[U.C. Sampdoria|Sampdoria]] in a 3\u20133 draw.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/224500?cc=5901|title=Del Piero at the double|publisher=ESPN|date=17 May 2008}}</ref> These two goals were crucial, as it took him to 21 goals for the season, thus winning him the ''[[Capocannonieri]]'' prize in Serie A for the first time in his illustrious career, beating the likes of teammate David Trezeguet (20 goals) and [[Marco Borriello]] (19 goals), also matching his highest seasonal tally in Serie A since the 1997\u201398 season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2008/maggio/18/Samp_Juve_show_Super_Del_ga_10_080518073.shtml|title=Samp-Juve show Super Del Piero \u00e8 il re del gol|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=18 May 2008|accessdate=8 January 2009}}</ref> He became only the second Italian ever to win consecutive ''Capocannoniere'' titles in two different leagues \u2013 former Juventus and [[1982 FIFA World Cup|1982 World Cup]] hero [[Paolo Rossi]] being the other. (Coincidentally, Rossi also won the ''Capocannoniere'' titles like Del Piero \u2013 first in Serie B and then in Serie A). On 26 July, Del Piero was awarded the Scirea Award.<ref name=\"Premio Nazionale Carriera Esemplare Gaetano Scirea: Alba d'Oro\">{{cite web|url=http://www.comune.cinisello-balsamo.mi.it/spip.php?article3932|title=Premio Nazionale Carriera Esemplare \"Gaetano Scirea\": Alba d'Oro|publisher=Comune Cinisello|language=Italian|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> Juventus finished the 2007\u201308 Serie A season in third place, which allowed them to qualify for the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|UEFA Champions League]] the following season.\n\nBefore the season, Juventus manager [[Claudio Ranieri]] remarked that Del Piero would have as good a season, or an even better one, than the previous term. In August 2008, Del Piero announced that he would try to keep playing professional football with Juventus until he turned 40.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/node/12852|title=Del Piero: 'I'll play until I'm 40'|publisher=Football Italia|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> Juventus were drawn into the same Champions League group as [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]], and [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]] winners [[FC Zenit Saint Petersburg|Zenit Saint Petersburg]]. Del Piero marked Juventus's return to the competition with a match-winning free kick to seal a home win against Zenit.<ref>{{in lang|it}} ''[http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Juventus/Primo_Piano/2008/09/17/JuveZenit.shtml Del Piero \u00e8 infinito. Lo Zenit si arrende]'' La Gazzetta dello Sport \u2013 Retrieved on 8 January 2008</ref> On 21 October, Del Piero netted a notable goal as Juventus defeated Real Madrid 2\u20131 in Turin, scoring with a first-time, curling strike from distance, in the fifth minute of play.<ref>{{in lang|it}} ''[http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2008/10/21/juvereal.shtml Del Piero-Amauri in gol. La Juve risorge, Real k.o.]'' La Gazzetta dello Sport \u2013 Retrieved on 8 January 2008</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2009/matches/round=15276/match=302736/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Juve enjoy high life at Madrid's expense|publisher=UEFA.com|date=22 October 2008}}</ref>\n[[File:Alessandro Del Piero 2008 cropped.jpg|thumb|left|Del Piero with Juventus in 2008]]\nOn 5 November 2008, Juventus and Real Madrid squared off at [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium|Santiago Bernab\u00e9u]] in the [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]]. The Italians won 0\u20132, their first away win against Madrid since 1962, and Del Piero was a key performer, scoring both goals, and drawing praise from Ranieri, as well as Real Madrid's coach [[Bernd Schuster]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/news/story/2008/11/07/f-real-madrid-fans.html |title=CBC News \u2013 A class act |publisher=Cbc.ca |last=Molinaro |first=John F. |date=7 November 2008 |accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref> As he left the pitch after being substituted, \"fans from both sides gave him a standing ovation.\"<ref>{{in lang|it}} ''[http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Juventus/Primo_Piano/2008/11/05/real-juve.shtml Ale incanta il Bernabeu. La Juve \u00e8 gi\u00e0 qualificata]'' La Gazzetta Dello Sport \u2013 Retrieved on 8 January 2008</ref> Juventus's Champions League campaign ended in disappointment, however, as they were eliminated by [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in the second round. Despite converting a penalty in the second leg in Turin, Del Piero was unable to prevent Juventus from losing 3\u20132 on aggregate.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/mar/10/juventus-chelsea-champions-league|title=Essien and Drogba draw the sting from 10-man Juve|newspaper=The Guardian|date=10 March 2009|location=London|first=Dominic|last=Fifield}}</ref>\n\nOn 29 November 2008, Del Piero scored his 250th goal for Juventus from a penalty, in a 4\u20130 home win over [[Reggina Calcio|Reggina]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Squadre/Juventus/Primo_Piano/2008/11/29/juv-reg.shtml|title=Super Juve sotto la neve Reggina presa a pallate|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Riccardo Pratesi|date=29 November 2008|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> In the league, Juventus were mostly challenging Milan for second place and an automatic Champions League spot. Most notably, Del Piero inspired Juventus to a 3\u20130 win over [[A.C. Siena|Siena]] in their penultimate game of the season, scoring a brace and setting up [[Claudio Marchisio]] for the youngster's third goal of the season to end their run of seven winless matches in Serie A.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/251568?cc=5901|title=Siena 0\u20133 Juventus|publisher=ESPN|date=24 May 2009}}</ref> Juventus then went on to defeat Lazio 2\u20130 and clinch the second place spot in [[2008\u201309 Serie A|Serie A]] over Milan, determined by their head-to-head record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/tables/_/league/ita.1/season/2008/italian-serie-a?cc=5901|title=2008/09 Italian Serie A Table / Table|publisher=ESPN|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 July 2009, Del Piero extended his contract with Juventus by one more year until 30 June 2011 in Pinzolo while training for pre-season, thus practically ensuring that he would retire at the club with which he started his professional career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1082078.html|title=Del Piero inks new Juve deal|publisher=FIFA.com|date=17 July 2009}}</ref> During his renewal, he said, \"I am happy at Juventus and we are competitive. I want to keep playing for as long as I can and I'm certain that for at least two more years I will be at the top level.\" On 14 February 2010, Del Piero marked his 445th Serie A appearance, breaking the all-time club record previously held by Boniperti, with a brace in a 3\u20132 win against [[Genoa C.F.C.|Genoa]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.sky.it/sport/calcio_italiano/2010/02/14/del_piero_record_presenze_juventus.html|title=Del Piero, vittoria e record: \"Punti pesantissimi\"|publisher=Sky|language=Italian|date=14 February 2010|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> Del Piero finished the season as the all-time top scorer for Juventus, having scored over 250 goals in all competitions with the club, and having also made over 600 appearances in official matches for Juventus, breaking Scirea's appearance record.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://bianconeri.tripod.com/records2.html|title=Juventus player records|work=Bianconeri.Tripod.com|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.gazzetta.it/Football/11-04-2012/fairytale-for-piero-goal-his-700th-game-juve-back-on-top-91900708279.shtml|title=Fairytale for Del Piero: a goal in his 700th game; Juve back on top|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport|date=11 April 2012|access-date=15 June 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140202181815/http://english.gazzetta.it/Football/11-04-2012/fairytale-for-piero-goal-his-700th-game-juve-back-on-top-91900708279.shtml|archive-date=2 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nOn 14 March 2010, Del Piero recorded his 300th and 301st career goals during a 3\u20133 draw with Siena, with the first two goals coming in the second and seventh minutes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/22042010/58/22042010154422.html|title=Del Piero celebrates his 300th goal for Juventus|publisher=Eurosport|date=22 April 2010}}</ref> On 30 October 2010, he recorded his 179th Serie A goal, helping his side to a 2\u20131 win at Milan, breaking the record of club legend [[Giampiero Boniperti]] as Juventus's top scorer in Serie A, and further cementing his status as the most prolific goalscorer in Juventus history.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=ita/news/newsid=1554949.html|title=Del Piero record caps Juve win at Milan|publisher=UEFA.com|date=30 October 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 5 February 2011, with his substitution against [[Cagliari Calcio|Cagliari]], Alessandro Del Piero became the most capped Juventus player, edging out former Juventus legend Giampiero Boniperti.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=1633292.html|title=Del Piero's black and white legacy|publisher=FIFA.com|date=20 May 2012}}</ref> Del Piero was the third most capped active player in the Serie A at the time, behind [[Javier Zanetti]] and [[Francesco Totti]], respectively. On 5 May 2011, he signed a new one-year contract to stay at the [[Juventus Arena]]. His previous deal was due to expire on 30 June 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.juventus.com/wps/portal/en/news/5maggio2011_DP_RINNOVO/|title=Del Piero renews contract at new stadium!|work=Juventus F.C.|date=5 May 2011|accessdate=6 May 2011}}</ref> On 24 May 2011, Del Piero and Juventus played against Manchester United at Old Trafford in a friendly match being former [[England national football team|England]] defender [[Gary Neville]]'s testimonial match. Del Piero was substituted after 65 minutes to a standing ovation from the United supporters.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2011/May/manchester-united-1-juventus-2.aspx|title=Gary Neville Testimonial Report: Man United 1 Juventus 2|publisher=Man Utd.com|author1=Adam Bostock|date=24 May 2011|accessdate=19 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n==== 2011\u201312: Champion again in final season with Juventus  ====\n[[File:Alessandro Del Piero - 04-2012 cropped.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Del Piero before a match in April 2012.]]\nJuventus confirmed on 18 October 2011 that the [[2011\u201312 Serie A|2011\u201312 season]] would be Del Piero's last with the club.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.skysports.com/story/0,19528,12876_7249158,00.html|title=Juve not retaining Del Piero|work=Sky Sports|date=18 October 2011|accessdate=19 October 2015}}</ref> The 2011\u201312 season under new manager [[Antonio Conte]], his former Juventus teammate, saw Del Piero being used sparingly, and mainly as a substitute, because of the summer arrival of forward [[Mirko Vu\u010dini\u0107]] from Roma. In the club's opening match of the season against Parma on 11 September, he assisted [[Simone Pepe]]'s goal in an eventual 4\u20131 home win.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=ita/news/newsid=1675081.html |title=Juventus pick off Parma, Palermo stun Inter |publisher=UEFA.com |date=11 September 2011 |accessdate=22 August 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.skysports.com/football/juventus-vs-parma/247621 |title=Juventus 4\u20131 Parma |publisher=Sky Sports |date=11 September 2011 |accessdate=22 August 2019 }}</ref> Del Piero scored his first goal in the new [[Juventus Stadium]] on 24 January 2012, in a 3\u20130 win over Roma in the quarter-finals of the [[2011\u201312 Coppa Italia|Coppa Italia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match/_/id/336404?cc=5901|title=Match report: Juventus 3 Roma 0|work=ESPN Soccernet|date=24 January 2012}}</ref> Later in the season, Del Piero stated that he was surprised at Juventus president [[Andrea Agnelli]]'s announcement regarding the club's decision not to offer him a new contract.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/10/italy/2012/04/17/3042533/del-piero-surprised-at-agnellis-refusal-to-grant-him|title=Del Piero surprised at Agnelli's refusal to grant him Juventus extension|work=Goal.com|date=17 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn the second leg of Juventus's clash with Milan in the Coppa Italia semi-finals, Del Piero finished off a brilliant move by Juventus as they secured a 2\u20132 draw to progress to the final with a 4\u20133 aggregate win.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/337683?cc=5901|title=Report: Juve 2 Milan 2|work=ESPN Soccernet|date=20 March 2012}}</ref> On 25 March, Del Piero helped Juventus defeat Inter by scoring the second goal of the match in a 2\u20130 victory, his first goal of the Serie A season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=326919&cc=5901|title=Report: Juve 2 Inter 0|work=ESPN Soccernet|date=25 March 2012}}</ref> In Juventus' match against Lazio on 11 April, Del Piero replaced Vu\u010dini\u0107 in the second half, making his 700th appearance for Juventus,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/memberassociations/association=ita/news/newsid=1782883.html|title=Del Piero steals the show to send Juventus top|publisher=UEFA.com|date=11 April 2012|accessdate=31 December 2015}}</ref> and then went on to score from a free kick to earn his side a 2\u20131 victory; the result also enabled Juventus to return to the top of the Serie A table.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en/match/65004/juventus-vs-lazio/report|title=Report: Juve 2 Lazio 1|work=Goal.com|date=11 April 2012|accessdate=31 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 May, Del Piero started Juventus's final league game of the season against [[Atalanta B.C.|Atalanta]], marking the occasion and the victory of their 28th Serie A title by scoring a goal.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.legaseriea.it/it/sala-stampa/archivio-dettaglio/-/news/FESTA_SCUDETTO_PER_LA_JUVENTUS/662818|title=Festa Scudetti per la Juventus|work=legaseriea.it|language=Italian|date=13 May 2012|accessdate=31 December 2015}}</ref> Twenty-seven minutes into the match, Del Piero picked the ball up at the edge of the penalty box and placed a shot past [[Giorgio Frezzolini]] to make the score 2\u20130, helping Juventus to go undefeated in Serie A that season.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/news/story/_/id/1069370/serie-a:-decorated-veterans-del-piero,-inzaghi-score-on-final-bows?cc=5901|title=Decorated veterans score on final bows|work=ESPN Soccernet|date=13 May 2012}}</ref> He was substituted off after 59 minutes to an emotional response from both sets of players and supporters, as he made a lap of honour around the pitch. This was Alessandro Del Piero's final Serie A appearance for Juventus.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report/_/id/326825?cc=5901|title=Report: Juve 3 Atalanta 1|work=ESPN Soccernet|date=13 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3276/serie-a/2012/05/13/3100354/del-piero-inzaghi-wave-goodbye-as-winners-in-fairytale|title=Del Piero & Inzaghi wave goodbye as winners in fairytale ending|work=Goal.com|date=13 May 2012}}</ref>\n[[File:DelPiero500.PNG|thumb|left|A commemorative shirt, celebrating Del Piero's 500th Juventus appearance.]]\nDel Piero's final match for Juventus was in the [[2012 Coppa Italia Final|Coppa Italia Final]] on 20 May against Napoli, which ended in a 2\u20130 victory to the Neapolitans. Del Piero was substituted in the 67th minute for Vu\u010dini\u0107 as his Juventus career came to an end; he received a standing ovation from both the Juventus and Napoli fans.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/match/78417/juventus-vs-napoli/report|title=Cavani and Hamsik clinch Coppa Italia and dash double dreams of Turin giants|work=Goal.com|date=20 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www1.skysports.com/football/news/12961/7768322/Cup-glory-for-Napoli|title=Cup glory for Napoli|work=Sky Sports|date=20 May 2012}}</ref> Following the game, he confirmed that after his 19-year spell with Juventus, he did not plan to retire. He then left the club and became a free agent. In total, Del Piero made a club record of 705 appearances for Juventus across all competitions, scoring a record 290 goals, and providing 134 assists in all competitions throughout his career with the club; he also scored 188 goals and provided 105 assists in 478 Serie A appearances with the Turin club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccer-europe.com/Biographies/DelPiero.html|title=Del Piero Statistics|publisher=soccer-europe.com|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/player/12952/alessandro-del-piero?season=2011|title=Alessandro Del Piero: ESPN Profile|publisher=ESPN FC|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> In addition to these records, Del Piero is also Juventus's top scorer and second highest appearance holder in the [[UEFA Champions League]], behind only Buffon, with 44 goals in 92 appearances; he is also the top scorer and appearance holder for Juventus in [[UEFA club competitions|European Competitions]], with 50 goals in 125 appearances, in [[International club football|International competitions]], with 54 goals in 131 appearances, and in the [[Supercoppa Italiana]], with 3 goals in 6 appearances. He is the club's top-scorer in [[Serie B]], with 21 goals, and the club's second highest scorer in the [[Coppa Italia]], with 25 goals, behind [[Pietro Anastasi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myjuve.it/statistiche-giocatori-juventus/riassunto_presenze.aspx|title=Juventus F.C., Statistiche Giocatori: Presenze|publisher=My Juve.it|language=Italian|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myjuve.it/statistiche-giocatori-juventus/riassunto_reti_segnate.aspx|title=Juventus F.C., Statistiche Giocatori: Reti Segnate|publisher=My Juve.it|language=Italian|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> Alongside [[Giuseppe Signori]] and [[Alberto Gilardino]], Del Piero is also the [[Football records in Italy|ninth highest all-time goalscorer in Serie A]], and he is currently the joint all-time top scorer in the Supercoppa Italiana, alongside [[Samuel Eto'o]], [[Andriy Shevchenko]], and [[Carlos Tevez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italsupcuphist.html |title=Italy Super Cup Finals |website=RSSSF |author1=Sorin Arotaritei |author2=Roberto Di Maggio |date=5 November 2015 |accessdate=31 December 2015 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160207154259/http://www.rsssf.com/tablesi/italsupcuphist.html |archivedate=7 February 2016  }}</ref> As of May 2016, he is the thirteenth highest [[UEFA Champions League]] [[List of European Cup and UEFA Champions League top scorers#All-time top scorers|all-time goalscorer]], with 41 goals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rsssf.com/ec/ec1tops.html#overall|title=Champions Cup / Champions League Topscorers|website=[[RSSSF]]|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nDel Piero refused the board's offer to retire the number 10 shirt in his honour, saying that \"I've really had so much that I would never want it to be retired, this way, every child can dream of day of wearing it.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.espnfc.com/print?id=1131297&type=story|title=No. 10 left empty by Juve|publisher=ESPN FC|date=9 August 2012|accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref> On 30 June, Del Piero wrote an open letter to the Juventus fans thanking them for almost two decades of support, stating, \"Above all what remains is the fans, you who are Juventus. That jersey that I loved and will always love, that I desired and respected&nbsp;... From tomorrow I will no longer be a Juventus player, but I will always be one of you. Now a new adventure begins and I am as fired up as I was 19 summers ago.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-gb/news/3265/italy/2012/06/30/3210972/del-piero-sends-open-letter-to-juventus-fans-i-will-always?source=breakingnews|title=Del Piero sends open letter to Juventus fans: I will always be one of you|publisher=Goal.com|date=30 June 2012|accessdate=31 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Sydney FC ===\n[[File:Alessandro del Piero (11846797333) (cropped).jpg|thumb|right|Del Piero training with Sydney FC in 2014]]\n[[File:Del Piero, Sydney FC-Newcastle Jets cropped.jpg|thumb|right|252px|Del Piero playing for Sydney FC in 2013]]\nOn 5 September 2012, Alessandro Del Piero signed a two-year deal with [[Sydney FC]]. He was paid approximately AU$3.5&nbsp;million for each of his first two seasons, and therefore became the highest-paid footballer to ever play in Australia.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/a-league/ciao-4m-del-piero-signs-for-two-years-20120905-25exy.html#ixzz25c44ORwW|title=Ciao 4m Del Piero signs for two years|website=smh.com.au|publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald|accessdate =6 September 2012}}</ref> Del Piero had been linked to [[Liverpool F.C.|Liverpool]] prior to signing for Sydney, but later revealed due to his memories of [[Heysel Stadium disaster|Heysel]] he would not have been able to move to the club.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/oct/12/alessandro-del-piero-liverpool-heysel|title=Alessandro Del Piero rejected Liverpool move 'because of Heysel'|website=theguardian.com|date=12 October 2012}}</ref>\n\nUpon signing for Sydney FC, Del Piero said, \"It's a special day for me. I am happy to announce that I just signed for two years for Sydney FC. This is a very big moment for me because I want to continue my career in a new part of the world where I can make a major contribution and help grow the game I love.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://au.fourfourtwo.com/news/250078,buongiorno-oz-del-piero-signs---official.aspx|title=Buongiorno Oz! Del Piero Signs \u2013 Official|publisher=Four Four Two|date=5 September 2012}}</ref> After the announcement of the transfer to Sydney FC, Juventus wished good luck to their former captain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.juventus.com/juve/en/news/5set2012_dp_eng |title=Good luck Alex! |publisher=Juventus.com |date=5 September 2012}}</ref> [[Francesco Totti]] and [[Filippo Inzaghi]] said they were saddened by his departure.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/calciomercato/2012/09/06-210947/Inzaghi+saluta+Del+Piero%3A+%C2%ABCiao+Alex%2C+tifer%C3%B2+per+te%C2%BB|title=Inzaghi saluta Del Piero: \u00c2\u0164Ciao Alex, tifer\u0102\u02db per te\u00c2\u0165 \u2013 Calciomercato / Calcio|newspaper=Tuttosport|language=Italian|date=6 September 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121110193828/http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/calciomercato/2012/09/06-210947/Inzaghi+saluta+Del+Piero%3A+%C2%ABCiao+Alex%2C+tifer%C3%B2+per+te%C2%BB|archivedate=10 November 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportmediaset.mediaset.it/calcio/roma/articoli/1844/totti-nostalgia-di-del-piero.shtml|title=Zeman: \"Contento della prestazione\"|publisher=Mediaset.it|date=6 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nSydney FC chairman Scott Barlow said, \"The signing of Alessandro Del Piero is a big moment for this club and, we believe, a historic moment for football in Australia, I wouldn't like to go into the details of the contract, but this does represent the largest professional sporting contract in Australian history and the numbers that have been discussed aren't too far off the mark.\"<ref name=\"articles.chicagotribune.com\">{{cite news|author = Nick Mulvenney | agency = Reuters |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/2012-09-05/sports/sns-rt-uk-soccer-australia-del-pierobre88505r-20120905_1_australian-sport-del-piero-australian-rules |title=Del Piero deal most lucrative in Australian sport \u2013 club \u2013 Chicago Tribune |publisher=Articles.chicagotribune.com |date=5 September 2012}}</ref>\n\nFFA chief executive [[Ben Buckley]] said that this signing will be crucial for the growth of Australian Football, both economically and technically.<ref name=\"articles.chicagotribune.com\"/> [[Ian Crook]], manager of Sydney FC, said he would build the forward set-up around the Italian, who would be given \"licence\" to pull the strings. \"We're not going to reinvent the wheel here. He's played 19 years for one of the biggest four or five clubs in the world, as a No. 10 or a No. 9. We're not going to change that.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/soccer/sydney-banking-on-del-piero-20120906-25h83.html|title=Sydney banking on Del Piero |website=Smh.com.au|publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald|author=Sebastian Hassett|date=7 September 2012}}</ref> [[FIFA]] President [[Sepp Blatter]] sent his best wishes to Del Piero and his new club.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttomercatoweb.com/?action=read&id=382845 |title=Blatter fa gli auguri a Del Piero tramite Twitter \u2013 TMW |publisher=Tuttomercatoweb.com |language=Italian |date=5 December 2007}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 October 2012, Del Piero made his [[A-League]] debut with Sydney FC in a 2\u20130 away loss against [[Wellington Phoenix FC|Wellington Phoenix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2012/10/06/phoenix-spoils-del-pieros-sydney-debut|title=Phoenix spoils Del Piero's Sydney debut|publisher=Special Broadcasting Service|date=6 October 2012|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> Del Piero scored his first goal for the club from a free-kick in 3\u20132 loss to [[Newcastle Jets]] on 13 October, in his first home game for Sydney.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/football/a-league/sydney-fc-host-newcastle-jets-in-alessandro-del-pieros-first-home-game-at-allianz-stadium/story-e6frf4gl-1226494991268 |title=Jets ruin Del Piero's home debut &#124; A-League |publisher=Fox Sports |last=Habashy |first=Angela |date=13 October 2012}}</ref> The match against Newcastle featured hero-cam, which allowed the viewer to track Del Piero's movements with one camera throughout the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.foxsports.com.au/football/a-league/follow-alessandro-del-piero-with-exclusive-herocam-pictures-from-sydney-fc-newcastle-jets-game/story-e6frf4gl-1226492021044#.UWDopkpe-F8 |title=Del Piero Hero Cam &#124; A-League |publisher=Fox Sports |date=9 October 2012}}</ref> On 20 October, Del Piero scored the winning goal against [[Western Sydney Wanderers FC]] (1\u20130), making history with the first goal in the first [[Sydney Derby (A-League)|Sydney Derby]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skynews.com.au/sport/article.aspx?id=807997 |title=Sky News Australia \u2013 Sport Article |publisher=Skynews.com.au |date=}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 January 2013, Del Piero scored four goals and also provided one assist in Sydney's 7\u20131 win against Wellington Phoenix; this was the first time he had scored more than three goals in a single match, and after being substituted, the fans gave him a standing ovation.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/a-league/del-piero-bags-four-in-71-rout-20130119-2d05u.html|title=Del Piero bags four in 7\u20131 rout|website=Smh.com.au|publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald|author=David Sygall|accessdate=22 July 2016}}</ref> On 10 February, Del Piero broke the club's record for most goals in a single season, scoring his eleventh goal of the season in a 2\u20131 home win over [[Brisbane Roar FC|Brisbane Roar]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/match/1296861/sydney-vs-brisbane-roar/report|title=Win lifts Sydney into top six|publisher=Special Broadcasting Service|date=10 February 2013|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> Despite his record-breaking tally of 14 goals in 24 appearances, Del Piero was unable to help Sydney qualify for the play-offs at the end of the season.<ref name=\"Del Piero magic inspires Sydney\">{{cite web|url=http://www.eurosport.com/football/hyundai-a-league/2010-2011/del-piero-magic-inspires-sydney-fc-as-a-league-kicks-off_sto3959583/story.shtml|title=Del Piero magic inspires Sydney FC as A-League kicks off|publisher=Eurosport.com|date=11 October 2013|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> On 21 February, Del Piero renewed his contract until 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/sydneyfc/news-display/alessandro-del-piero-and-sydney-fc-commit-to-second-season/61306|title=Alessandro Del Piero and Sydney FC Commit to Second Season \u2013 Sydney FC \u2013 Sydney FC 2014|publisher=Footballaustralia.com.au|accessdate=22 July 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219060237/http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/sydneyfc/news-display/alessandro-del-piero-and-sydney-fc-commit-to-second-season/61306|archivedate=19 February 2014}}</ref>\n\nDel Piero was named Sydney's captain for their 2013\u201314 season.<ref name=\"Del Piero magic inspires Sydney\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldfootball/clubfootball/news/newsid=2175741.html|title=Del Piero named Sydney FC captain|publisher=FIFA.com|accessdate=11 October 2013}}</ref> On 11 October 2013, Del Piero scored the opening goal of the [[2013\u201314 A-League]] season, the game-winner in a 2\u20130 victory over Newcastle Jets, also setting up [[Joel Chianese]]'s goal.<ref name=\"Del Piero magic inspires Sydney\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/aleague/matchcentre/Sydney-FC-v-Newcastle-Jets-Hyundai-A-League/3085|title=Del Piero, Sydney sink Jets|publisher=A-League|accessdate=11 October 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140219060225/http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/aleague/matchcentre/Sydney-FC-v-Newcastle-Jets-Hyundai-A-League/3085|archivedate=19 February 2014}}</ref> Alessandro went on to score 10 goals in total for Sydney FC in the 2013\u201314 season, which earned him the Sydney FC Golden Boot;<ref name=\"Sydney FC Golden Boot\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sydneyfc.com/video/alessandro-del-piero-wins-sydney-fc-golden-boot/eetecg45evpp1mlix088klpk6/187/5|title=Alessandro Del Piero Wins Sydney FC Golden Boot|publisher=Sydney FC|date=5 May 2014|accessdate=9 January 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170110021044/http://www.sydneyfc.com/video/alessandro-del-piero-wins-sydney-fc-golden-boot/eetecg45evpp1mlix088klpk6/187/5|archive-date=10 January 2017|url-status=dead}}</ref> he helped the club qualify for the finals series, setting up both of his team's goals in the final match of the regular season on 13 April 2014, a 2\u20131 home win over [[Perth Glory FC|Perth Glory]], before being released of his contract at Sydney FC.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2014/04/13/del-piero-helps-sydney-fc-league-playoffs|title=Del Piero helps Sydney FC into A-League playoffs|publisher=Special Broadcasting Service|date=13 April 2014|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> His final match with Sydney came in a 2\u20131 loss to [[Melbourne Victory FC|Melbourne Victory]] in an [[2013\u201314 A-League#Finals series|Elimination final]] at [[Docklands Stadium]] on 18 April, courtesy of [[Gui Finkler]]'s injury time winner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2014-04-19/alessandro-del-piero-says-goodbye-to-fans-after-sydney-fc/5399870|title=Alessandro Del Piero says goodbye to fans after Sydney FC's loss to Melbourne Victory|publisher=ABC.net|date=18 April 2014|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn Sunday 10 August 2014, Del Piero captained the [[A-League All Stars Game|Hyundai A-League All Stars]] against his club of almost 20 years, Juventus, in Sydney, in front of over 55,000 people at [[ANZ Stadium]]. Del Piero was substituted off at the 63rd minute of the match for [[David Williams (Australian association footballer)|David Williams]], to a standing ovation.<ref name=\"footballaustralia\">{{cite web|url=http://www.footballaustralia.com.au/sydneyfc/news-display/Sydney-FC-Pays-Tribute-To-Alessandro-Del-Piero/90149|title=Sydney FC Home &#124; Sydney FC|publisher=footballaustralia.com.au|accessdate=31 January 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2015, Del Piero was named to Sydney FC's team of the decade and to the [[AFC (soccer)|AFC]] team of the decade.<ref name=\"Del Piero headlines strong Sydney FC team of the decade\">{{cite web|url=http://theworldgame.sbs.com.au/article/2015/04/29/del-piero-headlines-strong-sydney-fc-team-decade|title=Del Piero headlines strong Sydney FC team of the decade|publisher=Special Broadcasting Service|date=29 April 2015|accessdate=7 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Alessandro Del Piero named on bench in PFA's A-League team of decade\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2015/apr/28/a-league-del-piero-benched-team-decade|title=Alessandro Del Piero named on bench in PFA's A-League team of decade|newspaper=The Guardian|date=28 April 2015|accessdate=7 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Delhi Dynamos===\nOn 23 August 2014, it was reported that [[Delhi Dynamos FC|Delhi Dynamos]], an Indian side that was set to play in the inaugural [[2014 Indian Super League season|Indian Super League]] season, was in talks with Del Piero.<ref>{{cite web|title=Alessandro del Piero to play for ISL side Delhi Dynamos|url=http://sports-nova.com/alessandro-del-piero-play-isl-side-delhi-dynamos/|publisher=Sports-nova.com|accessdate=23 August 2014}}</ref> His brother, Stefano Del Piero said \"During the last (few) weeks, we have received inquiries from several teams, not only from India but also from other countries. There is a lot of interest in Alessandro.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Del Piero set to join Delhi Dynamos|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/222/transfer-zone/2014/08/23/5053887/del-piero-set-to-join-delhi-dynamos?ICID=AR|publisher=Goal.com|date=23 August 2014|accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref> On 28 August 2014, he officially signed for the Indian franchise, signing a four-month deal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/news/7083/isl/2014/08/28/5065328/del-piero-pens-a-four-month-deal-with-delhi-dynamos-fc?ICID=HP_BN_7|title=Del Piero pens a four-month deal with Delhi Dynamos FC|publisher=Goal.com|date=28 August 2014|accessdate=28 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nDel Piero made his debut for the Delhi Dynamos on 14 October in a 0\u20130 draw against [[FC Pune City|Pune City]], a side which featured his former Juventus teammate David Trezeguet.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sports.ndtv.com/indian-super-league-2014/news/231453-isl-delhi-dynamos-and-fc-pune-city-finish-0-0-alessandro-del-piero-dazzles-on-debut|title=ISL: Delhi Dynamos and FC Pune City Finish 0\u20130; Alessandro Del Piero Dazzles on Debut|publisher=NDTV|accessdate=20 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141020182938/http://sports.ndtv.com/indian-super-league-2014/news/231453-isl-delhi-dynamos-and-fc-pune-city-finish-0-0-alessandro-del-piero-dazzles-on-debut|archive-date=20 October 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> On 9 December, Del Piero scored his first and only Delhi Dynamos goal, netting directly from a free kick, in a 2\u20132 draw against [[Chennaiyin FC|Chennaiyin]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-india/match/chennaiyin-fc-vs-delhi-dynamos/1931547/report|title=Del Piero sparks a comeback for the visitors|publisher=Goal.com|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref> Del Piero made 10 appearances throughout the season as Delhi finished in fifth place, failing to reach the play-offs by a single point.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/indian-super-league-wrap-blasters-semi-finals#:t-UiMFU8gY2XKA|title=Indian Super League Wrap: Blasters into semi-finals|publisher=Four Four Two|date=11 December 2014|accessdate=10 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Retirement===\nIn October 2015, after almost a year without a club, Del Piero officially communicated his retirement from professional football, also stating his intention to pursue a coaching career.<ref name=\"Alessandro Del Piero and Roberto Carlos touted for A-League coaching roles\"/>\n\n== International career ==\n\n=== 1995\u20131998: Euro 1996 and 1998 World Cup ===\nDel Piero is currently [[Italy national football team|Italy]]'s joint fourth all-time leading scorer, along with Roberto Baggio, with 27 goals in 91 appearances, with 2 goals for Italy coming in 12 World Cup matches and 1 goal in 13 European Championship matches;<ref name=\"Nazionale in cifre - FIGC: Del Piero, Alessandro\">{{cite web|url=https://www.figc.it/it/nazionali/nazionali-in-cifre/dettaglio-convocato/?calciatoreId=43236&squadraId=12|title=Nazionale in cifre \u2013 FIGC: Del Piero, Alessandro|website=figc.it|publisher=FIGC|language=Italian|accessdate=17 April 2015}}</ref> alongside [[Enrico Chiesa]], he also holds the unique record for the most goals scored by an Italian international as a substitute (5).<ref name=\"GOL DALLA PANCHINA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.italia1910.com/statistiche-marcatori-gol-dalla-panchina.asp|title=STATISTICHE MARCATORI, I GOL \"DALLA PANCHINA\" (TUTTE LE COMPETIZIONI)|publisher=Italia1910.com|language=Italian|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> Del Piero initially played for the [[Italy national under-21 football team|Italian U-21 side]] on 12 occasions, scoring 3 goals, and was a member of the team that qualified for and later won the [[1996 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|1996 European Under-21 Championship]], appearing in the quarter-finals.<ref name=\"Nazionale in cifre - FIGC: Del Piero, Alessandro\"/> Del Piero made his senior debut under [[Arrigo Sacchi]] at the age of 20, on 25 March 1995, in a 4\u20131 win over [[Estonia national football team|Estonia]] in a [[UEFA Euro 1996 qualifying|Euro 1996 qualifying match]].<ref name=\"Nazionale in cifre - FIGC: Del Piero, Alessandro\"/> Del Piero scored his first goal for Italy on 15 November 1995, in a 4\u20130 win over [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] in a Euro 1996 qualifying match.<ref name=\"Nazionale in cifre - FIGC: Del Piero, Alessandro\"/> His tournament debut was at [[UEFA Euro 1996]], where he made his only appearance in the first half of the team's 2\u20131 win in the opening group match against [[Russia national football team|Russia]], playing as a left-winger in midfield, wearing the number 14 shirt, before being substituted at half-time by [[Roberto Donadoni]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=227/match=52507/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Instinctive Casiraghi helps Italy sink Russia|publisher=UEFA.com|date=6 October 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=1996: GERMANIA|url=http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/europei_1996.html|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>\n\nThe next year, Del Piero was part of the Italy team that took part in the friendly \"[[Tournoi de France]]\" tournament from 3 to 11 June 1997 under [[Cesare Maldini]]. Del Piero scored two goals in a 3\u20133 draw against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1997/giugno/09/Italia_Brasile_pareggio_spettacolo_Del_co_0_97060916053.shtml|title=Italia Brasile, un pareggio spettacolo. Ma Del Piero batte Ronaldo 2 gol a 1|website=corriere.it|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|author=Luca Valdiserri|date=9 June 1997|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> and scored from a penalty against [[France national football team|France]] in the 90th minute,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.italia1910.com/partita.asp?idpartita=547|title=Francia-Italia 2\u20132|publisher=Italia 1910|language=Italian|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> finishing the tournament as top-scorer with 3 goals, although Italy finished in last place.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/azzurri/2009/01/26-16277/Per+l%27amichevole+con+l%27Italia,+Dunga+lascia+a+casa+Amauri?print|title=Per l'amichevole con l'Italia, Dunga lascia a casa Amauri|website=tuttosport.com|publisher=Tutto Sport|language=Italian|date=26 January 2009|accessdate=18 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150219080202/http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/azzurri/2009/01/26-16277/Per+l%27amichevole+con+l%27Italia,+Dunga+lascia+a+casa+Amauri?print|archive-date=19 February 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nDel Piero competed with fan favourite Roberto Baggio for an attacking spot in the starting 11 during the [[1998 FIFA World Cup]], while struggling to recover from an injury suffered during the 1998 Champions League final with Juventus; Del Piero missed out on Italy's 2\u20132 opening draw against [[Chile national football team|Chile]], and was temporarily replaced by Baggio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/02_mondiali_calcio_1998.html|title=Francia 1998 \u2013 Capitolo II: Le scelte di Cesare|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=30 January 2016}}</ref> He made his first World Cup appearance in the second group match, a 3\u20130 defeat of [[Cameroon national football team|Cameroon]], coming on for Baggio in the second half, wearing the [[Squad number (association football)|number 10 shirt]], and contributing to [[Christian Vieri]]'s final goal.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition=1013/results/matches/match=8744/report.html |title=Italy \u2013 Cameroon3:0 (1:0) |publisher=FIFA.com |date=17 June 1998 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131204060054/http://www.fifa.com/worldcup/archive/edition%3D1013/results/matches/match%3D8744/report.html |archivedate=4 December 2013 }}</ref> In the final group game against [[Austria national football team|Austria]], Del Piero won his first start, setting up Vieri's opening goal of the match from a free-kick as Italy won 2\u20131 to top their group and seal a passage into the next round, avoiding reigning champions [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]; he was substituted by Baggio in the second half.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/soccer/world/events/1998/worldcup/news/1998/06/23/italy_austria/|title=Vieri, Baggio goals help Italy win 2\u20131, avoid Brazil|publisher=CNN | date=15 September 1998}}</ref> Italy reached the quarter-finals after defeating [[Norway national football team|Norway]] 1\u20130, as Del Piero started the match alongside Vieri once again, coming off for [[Enrico Chiesa]] in the 77th minute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/mondiali_1998_italia_norvegia.html|title=Italia, la vittoria della sofferenza|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> Italy eventually fell to hosts and eventual champions [[France national football team|France]] on penalty kicks, following a 0\u20130 draw; Del Piero was criticised for his performance and was substituted in the second half by Baggio once again.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/mondiali_1998_italia_francia.html|title=Francia avanti, ancora rigori stregati|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref>\n\n=== 1998\u20132004: Euro 2000 runners-up and subsequent struggles ===\n[[File:Totti Euro 2000.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Del Piero with [[Francesco Totti]] [[Goal celebration|celebrating a goal]] for Italy during [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]].]]\nDel Piero was part of [[Dino Zoff]]'s Italy's squad that reached the [[UEFA Euro 2000 Final|final]] of [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]]. Although he was primarily used as a substitute for either [[Francesco Totti]] or [[Stefano Fiore]], Del Piero appeared in every match of the tournament, and he wore the number 10 shirt. On 11 June, Del Piero came on as a substitute for Fiore in the 30th minute in Italy's opening Group B 2\u20131 win against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]], hitting the cross-bar from a free-kick.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2000/matches/round=1458/match=64852/index.html|title=Euro 2000: Turchia-Italia (1\u20132)|publisher=UEFA.com|language=Italian|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> In the final group game, Del Piero started the match and scored the winner with a notable goal against [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]], taking it past two players before curling the ball into the top corner from outside the area with a left-footed strike; Del Piero also set up [[Luigi Di Biagio]]'s opener from a corner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2000/round=1458/match=64856/report=rp.html|title=Italy foil brave Sweden|publisher=UEFA.com|date=6 October 2003|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160110070652/http://en.archive.uefa.com/competitions/euro2012/history/season=2000/round=1458/match=64856/report=rp.html|archivedate=10 January 2016}}</ref> Del Piero made his second start of the tournament for Italy in their semi-final against co-hosts, [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]], which Italy won on penalties following a 0\u20130 draw after extra-time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/euro2000/matchreports/20000629/ita_hol_full.html|title=Euro 2000 Full-time Report: Italy v Holland (0\u20130)|website=espnfc.com|publisher=ESPN FC|date=29 June 2000|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref> In the final, he come on as a substitute in the second half and missed two gilt-edged chances in Italy's 2\u20131 loss to France in extra time, and was criticised by the Italian press.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/news/newsid=116442.html|title=Trezeguet's golden moment makes French history|publisher=UEFA.com|date=6 October 2003|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe returned to the international scene in the [[2002 FIFA World Cup]] under [[Giovanni Trapattoni]], after winning the ''Scudetto'' with Juventus.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/europe/1969550.stm|title=Juventus snatch dramatic title|work=BBC Sport|date=5 May 2002|accessdate=10 December 2015}}</ref> Del Piero scored the decisive goal against [[Hungary national football team|Hungary]], which sealed Italy's [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|qualification]] for the finals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.figc.it/nazionali/TabellinoGara?squadra=1&codiceGara=1808 |title=Italy 1 Hungary 0 |publisher=FIGC|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> Del Piero appeared as a substitute in Italy's opening win against [[Ecuador national football team|Ecuador]], wearing the captain's armband for part of the match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/mondiali2002/itaecu/itaecu/itaecu.html|title=L'Italia parte bene Battuto l'Ecuador 2\u20130|trans-title=Italy starts well Ecuador defeated 2\u20130|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|author1=Massimo Vincenzi|date=3 June 2002|accessdate=14 November 2015}}</ref> He instantly scored with a header against [[Mexico national football team|Mexico]], after coming on as a substitute, an equalising goal which saved Italy from the ignominy of a first round exit in their final group match.<ref name=\"Gruppo G: Italia-Messico 1-1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/diretta/online/italiamessico/|title=Gruppo G: Italia-Messico 1\u20131|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> The goal sent Italy through to the second round, where they were eliminated by a [[golden goal]] in a controversial match against co-hosts [[Korea Republic national football team|South Korea]], a match during which Del Piero started alongside Totti and Vieri.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/3029599/Italy-flop-as-Ahns-golden-goal-atones-for-penalty-miss.html|title=Italy flop as Ahn's golden goal atones for penalty miss|work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|publisher=The Telegraph|date=18 June 2002|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2002/jun/18/minutebyminute.worldcupfootball20021|title=South Korea 2\u20131 Italy \u2013 as it happened|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=18 June 2002|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nDel Piero took part in 6 of Italy's [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying|2004 European Qualifying matches]], scoring 5 goals, and was called up for the Italy squad that would participate in [[UEFA Euro 2004]] in Portugal.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2004/statistics/round=1579/index.html|title=UEFA Euro 2004: Statistiche|website=uefa.com|publisher=UEFA|language=Italian|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/italy/3774283.stm|title=Euro 2004: Italy squad|work=BBC Sport|date=3 June 2004|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> Del Piero started all three matches, wearing the captain's armband in Italy's final win over [[Bulgaria national football team|Bulgaria]], and was involved in [[Antonio Cassano|Cassano]]'s injury time match-winning goal, although Italy were eliminated in the first round on direct encounters, following a three-way five point tie with [[Sweden national football team|Sweden]] and [[Denmark national football team|Denmark]].<ref name=\"Euro 2008: Alex Del Piero\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2004/3787525.stm|title=Italy 2\u20131 Bulgaria|work=BBC Sport|date=23 June 2004|accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.storiedicalcio.altervista.org/europei_2004.html|title=La storia dei campionati europei di calcio \u2013 2004: Grecia|publisher=Storie di Calcio|language=Italian|accessdate=18 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== 2004\u20132008: World Cup champion and post-World Cup ===\n[[File:Alex Del Piero.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Del Piero after Italy's victorious [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]] semi-final against hosts [[Germany national football team|Germany]].]]\nDel Piero took part in the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]] under manager Marcello Lippi,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/2006/05/sezioni/sport/calcio/nazionale/conferenza-stampa-lippi/conferenza-stampa-lippi/conferenza-stampa-lippi.html|title=Lippi ha fiducia, nonostante tutto Convocato Buffon: \"E' sereno\"|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=15 May 2006|accessdate=20 January 2017}}</ref> appearing in five matches, and two out of the three group stage matches; he made his first start of the competition in a 1\u20130 round of 16 win over [[Australia national football team|Australia]] on 26 June.<ref name=\"Euro 2008: Alex Del Piero\"/> On 4 July, Del Piero entered as a substitute near the end of regulation and scored Italy's second goal in a 2\u20130 semi-final win over host [[Germany national football team|Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991640.stm|title=World Cup 2006: Germany 0\u20132 Italy (aet)|work=BBC Sport|date=4 July 2006|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=39zYaMf0AS0 |title=Del Piero's goal against Germany |publisher=Youtube.com}}</ref> In the [[2006 FIFA World Cup Final|final]] against France, which ended 1\u20131 after extra time, Del Piero scored a penalty in the shootout as Italy won the tournament for the fourth time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/world_cup_2006/4991652.stm|title=World Cup 2006: Italy 1\u20131 France (aet)|work=BBC Sport|author1=Jonathan Stevenson|date=9 July 2006|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> He admitted afterwards that winning the World Cup was his childhood dream.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/03/18/football/del-piero-human-to-hero/|title=Alessandro Del Piero: Italy's World Cup hero targets new goals|publisher=CNN|date=19 March 2015|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref>\n\nAs of 2008, Del Piero has captained Italy seven times (including during [[UEFA Euro 2008]]). He also initially regularly wore the number 10 shirt, in particular under Maldini and Zoff, but later gave it to Totti after Euro 2000, and switched to the number 7 for the 2002 World Cup, as it was the first number he wore at the start of his career.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio/numeri/numeri/numeri.html|title=Azzurri, ecco i numeri a Totti va il numero 10|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=15 May 2002|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> Even though the number 10 shirt was vacated after Totti retired from the national team in July 2007, Del Piero denied any interest in taking back the number, saying he was satisfied with the number 7 jersey.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2008/02_Febbraio/01/delpiero_0102.shtml|title=E' un Del Piero da Nazionale|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|author1=Giampiero Timossi|language=Italian|date=1 February 2008|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> In May, he was recalled by popular demand to Italy's UEFA Euro 2008 squad in Austria and Switzerland under manager [[Roberto Donadoni]], after a nine-month absence from international duty, and thus became the second Italian player, after [[Paolo Maldini]], to participate in seven major international tournaments (Euro 1996, 2000, 2004, 2008; World Cup 1998, 2002, 2006).<ref name=\"Euro 2008: Alex Del Piero\"/>\n\nAlthough Del Piero was mostly on the substitutes' bench at Euro 2008, he started in Italy's second group match against [[Romania national football team|Romania]] as the squad's captain.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2008/matches/round=15093/match=300695/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Buffon saves Italy with penalty stop|publisher=UEFA.com|author1=Michael Harrold|date=14 June 2008|accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref> In the first group match against the Dutch, he came on for the under-performing [[Antonio Di Natale]] and made an immediate impact, including several efforts on goal; however, he could not prevent Italy from losing 3\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/euro_2008/7363339.stm|title=Euro 2008: Netherlands 3\u20130 Italy|work=BBC Sport|author1=Phil McNulty|date=9 June 2008|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> Italy qualified through the group stage in second-place behind the Netherlands, eliminating Romania and France.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2008/matches/round=15093/match=300703/postmatch/report/index.html|title=France sunk as Italy grab lifeline|publisher=UEFA.com|author1=Matthew Spiro|date=18 June 2008|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> In the quarter-final against eventual champions [[Spain national football team|Spain]], Del Piero made a substitute appearance during extra-time, and with the game ending in a 0\u20130 draw, it was decided by a penalty shootout in which Spain won 4\u20132.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/euro_2008/7468465.stm |title=Spain 0\u20130 Italy (4\u20132 penalties) |work=[[BBC Sport]] |last=McNulty |first=Phil |date=22 June 2008 |accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 August 2008, Del Piero won his 90th cap for Italy in friendly against Austria under Lippi, becoming only the fifth Italy player to reach this landmark at the time.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2008/08/20/la-nuova-italia-cerca-gol-spettacolo.html|title=La nuova Italia cerca gol e spettacolo|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|author1=Enrico Curro Nizza|date=20 August 2008|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref> Despite announcing his intention to carry on playing until the age of 40, he was excluded from Lippi's [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] squad. Del Piero's final appearance for Italy came in a 2\u20130 win against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]] in a [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2010 FIFA World Cup qualifier]] on 10 September 2008; he came on for Di Natale in the 56th minute and later set up [[Daniele De Rossi]]'s second goal of the match.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Speciali/Mondiale_2010/Countdown_9.shtml|title=Il Mondiale 2010 in pillole|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Massimo Perrone|date=3 June 2010|accessdate=13 May 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/azzurri/2008/09/10-3432/Italia,+Del+Piero+decisivo+nella+sera+di+De+Rossi|title=Italia, Del Piero decisivo nella sera di De Rossi|publisher=Tutto Sport|language=Italian|date=10 September 2008|accessdate=31 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304002503/http://www.tuttosport.com/calcio/azzurri/2008/09/10-3432/Italia,+Del+Piero+decisivo+nella+sera+di+De+Rossi|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, the Italy national team coach at the time, [[Cesare Prandelli]], stated that he would consider calling Del Piero up for the [[2014 FIFA World Cup|2014 World Cup]], although he was ultimately excluded from the Italian squad that participated at the tournament in Brazil.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-au/news/4034/world-cup-2014/2013/08/20/4199368/prandelli-considers-del-piero-for-italy-recall|title=Prandelli considers Del Piero for Italy recall|publisher=Goal.com|date=20 August 2013|accessdate=14 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Player profile ==\n=== Style of play ===\n{{Quote box\n |quote=He [Del Piero] is different to [[Zinedine Zidane]]. He likes to play, he feels it in his soul. Between him and the Frenchman, I choose him.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/en-ie/news/3920/features/2012/05/21/3116024/there-will-never-be-another-del-piero-juventus-say|title=There will never be another Del Piero: Juventus say arrivederci to the most loved player in their history|publisher=Goal.com|date=21 May 2012}}</ref>|source=[[Diego Maradona]]|align=centre\n |quoted=1\n |width=36%\n}}\n\nDue to his creative style of play, eye for goal, flair, and technical skill, Del Piero was known as a \"fantasista\" in Italy.<ref name=\"calcioblog.it\">{{cite web|url=http://www.calcioblog.it/post/3866/del-piero-mai-piu-centrocampista|title=Del Piero e la Nazionale: \"mai pi\u00f9 da centrocampista\"|publisher=CalcioBlog.it|language=Italian|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref> His hard-working playing style was regarded by critics as creative in attacking, [[Assist (football)|assisting]] many goals as well as scoring himself, as opposed to just \"goal poaching\".<ref name=\"Sportstar\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hinduonnet.com/tss/tss2913/stories/20060401008303200.htm |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081223232336/http://www.hinduonnet.com/tss/tss2913/stories/20060401008303200.htm |archivedate=23 December 2008 |title=Seeking glory in blue shirt |work=Sportstar |date=1 April 2006 |accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> Because of his technical characteristics, link-up play, and ability at one\u2013twos, Del Piero usually played as a [[Forward (association football)#Second striker|supporting-striker]], which was his preferred role,<ref name=\"calcioblog.it\"/> although he was a tactically versatile [[Forward (association football)|forward]], with good movement and clinical finishing, who was capable of playing anywhere along the front line, and who also established himself as a prolific goalscorer throughout his career. He was also occasionally deployed between the [[Midfielder|midfield]] and the strikers as a [[Playmaker|playmaking]] [[Midfielder#Attacking midfielder|attacking midfielder]], known in Italy as the ''trequartista'' position, due to his vision, passing range, ball control, [[Dribbling#Association football|dribbling ability]] (in particular in one on one situations) and creativity, although he often stated that this was not his preferred position. As such, Del Piero's former Juventus teammate and manager [[Didier Deschamps]] described him as a \"nine and a half\" in 2006, a description that Michel Platini had previously also used to describe Roberto Baggio, to indicate that Del Piero's favoured role was somewhere between that of a striker (who traditionally wore the number nine shirt) and an attacking midfielder (who traditionally wore the number ten shirt), namely that of a second striker.<ref name=\"7 Alessandro Del Piero\">{{cite web|url=http://www.worldcup365.com/profile/0,16726,8362_994157,00.html |title=7 Alessandro Del Piero |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20061119214434/http://www.worldcup365.com/profile/0%2C16726%2C8362_994157%2C00.html |work=Worldcup365.com |archivedate=19 November 2006 |date=25 May 2006 |accessdate=26 May 2012 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"forgotten goals\">{{cite web |url=https://www.football-italia.net/146247/del-pieros-top-5-forgotten-goals |title=Del Piero's top 5 forgotten goals |publisher=Football Italia |date=9 November 2019 |accessdate=11 November 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio/poledelpiero/poledelpiero/poledelpiero.html|title=Lo sgarbo di Del Piero \"Non gioco trequartista\"|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2000/jun/24/euro2000.sport8|title=Del Piero fuels passionate debate|newspaper=The Guardian|author1=Paddy Agnew|date=24 June 2000|accessdate=25 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espnfc.com/euro2000/italy/player/delPiero.html|title=Profile: Alessandro Del Piero|publisher=ESPN FC|author1=Shaun Botterill|date=13 July 2000|accessdate=22 February 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"9 e mezzo\">{{cite news |url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/2006/agosto/23/Del_Piero_mezzo_Come_Baggio_ga_10_060823083.shtml |title=\"Del Piero \u00e8 un 9 e mezzo\" Come Baggio per Platini |trans-title=\"Del Piero is a 9 and a half\" Like Baggio was for Platini |work=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |last1=Luca |first1=Curino |date=23 August 2006 |accessdate=9 January 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/1810824-10-of-the-best-duos-in-world-footballs-recent-history |title=10 of the Best Duos in World Football's Recent History |publisher=Bleacher Report |last1=Atkins |first1=Christopher |date=14 October 2013 |accessdate=7 April 2020 }}</ref><ref name=\"Goal.com Profile ADP\">{{cite web|url=http://www.goal.com/it/Giocatore.aspx?IdPersona=112&SEOPlayerName=Alessandro+Del+Piero|title=Profilo|publisher=Goal.com|language=Italian|date=30 October 2007|accessdate=7 April 2020|archive-url=https://archive.is/20071030032939/http://www.goal.com/it/Giocatore.aspx?IdPersona=112&SEOPlayerName=Alessandro+Del+Piero|archive-date=23 August 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> Del Piero was also employed occasionally as a [[Midfielder#Winger|winger]] in a 4\u20134\u20132 formation throughout his career, in particular during his time under Sacchi with the Italy national football team,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://it.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=1996/matches/round=227/match=52507/index.html|title=UEFA Euro 96: Italia vs. Russia (2\u20131)|publisher=UEFA.com|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> due to his tendency to drift onto the wings,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.smh.com.au/sport/soccer/alessandro-del-piero-says-sydney-aleague-derby-atmosphere-rivals-europes-best-20140306-34a81.html|title=Alessandro Del Piero says Sydney A-League derby atmosphere rivals Europe's best|newspaper=The Sydney Morning Herald|author1=Dominic Bossi|date=7 March 2014|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref> defensive work-rate,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio2002_serie_a/delpiero/delpiero/delpiero.html|title=Del Piero ko, fuori due mesi rivive il crac di 4 anni fa|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=3 February 2003|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref> and his [[Cross (football)|crossing]] accuracy,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/columnists/henrywinter/2404912/Shevchenko-the-Milan-master.html|title=Shevchenko the Milan master|newspaper=The Telegraph|author1=Henry Winter|date=29 May 2003|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref> as well as his ability to use either foot.<ref name=archive.thedailystar.net>{{cite news|url=http://archive.thedailystar.net/2003/05/28/d30528041033.htm|title=KEY MEN|newspaper=The Daily Star|date=28 May 2003|accessdate=7 November 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Position ===\nIn his youth, Del Piero played in the \"trident-attack\" of Lippi's [[Formation (association football)#4\u20133\u20133|4\u20133\u20133 formation]], along with veterans Vialli, Baggio, and Ravanelli, as a [[Forward (association football)#Striker|striker]], or more frequently as an [[Forward (association football)#Winger|outside forward]] on the left.<ref name=\"9 e mezzo\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/europeran-football-bergkamp-ban-lifted-1440286.html|title=Europeran Football: Bergkamp ban lifted|newspaper=The Independent|date=22 October 2011|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref><ref name=\"Alessandro the Great\">{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/champions_league/2935372.stm|title=Alessandro the Great|work=BBC Sport|author1=Nada Grkinic|date=26 May 2003|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref> With the arrival of Zidane in the advanced midfield playmaking role, Juventus's formation changed to a 4\u20134\u20132 system, and Del Piero partnered alongside a more offensive striker up front, such as [[Christian Vieri]] and subsequently Inzaghi, as either a supporting forward or as an out-and-out striker.<ref name=\"Alessandro the Great\"/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/04/15/sports/15iht-soccer.t_9.html|title=Del Piero Wants Big Money and Wants It Now: Striker With a Goal: Turning Juve's Tables|newspaper=The New York Times|author1=Rob Hughes|date=15 April 1998|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11863/2212813/pippo-milans-man|title=PIPPO MILAN'S MAN|publisher=Sky Sports|author1=Rupert Webster|date=1 January 2007|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.tuttosport.com/news/calcio/ilcuoio/2019/03/13-54506494/juve_tre_triplette_per_la_storia/ |title=Juve: tre triplette per la storia |work=Tutto Sport |language=Italian |date=13 March 2019 |accessdate=11 November 2019 }}</ref> After losing some of his explosive pace, speed of execution, flair, and agility following his injury in 1998, Del Piero performed a muscle strengthening regime, and he took on a more creative role, in combination with playmaker Zidane, functioning in a free position, just in front of the attacking midfielder and behind the main striker Inzaghi, under Ancelotti, in the club's 3\u20134\u20131\u20132 formation;<ref name=\"forgotten goals\"/><ref name=\"Goal.com Profile ADP\"/><ref name=\"Alessandro the Great\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.panorama.it/sport/calcio/zeman-juventus-tutte-le-dichiarazioni-in-14-anni-di-accuse/|title=Zeman-Juventus, tutte le dichiarazioni di \"guerra\"|publisher=Panorama|language=Italian|accessdate=20 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1998/novembre/07/Totti_piu_muscoli_servizio_della_co_0_9811078539.shtml|title=Totti, piu' muscoli al servizio della fantasia|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|author1=Giorgio Rondelli|language=Italian|date=7 November 1998|accessdate=22 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.repubblica.it/online/sport/dodicesima/crosetti/crosetti.html |title=Due lampi di Inzaghi la Juventus prova l'allungo |work=La Repubblica |language=Italian |last1=Crosetti |first1=Maurizio |date=4 December 1999 |accessdate=11 November 2019 }}</ref> although he was accused by some in the media of not living up to his potential following his injury, due to his decrease in goalscoring,<ref name=\"eroi in bianconero\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/gli-eroi-bianconeri/gli-eroi-in-bianconero-alessandro-del-piero-210813|title=Gli eroi in bianconero: Alessandro DEL PIERO|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|author=Stefano Bedeschi|accessdate=9 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://temi.repubblica.it/ilcentro-europei2008/2008/05/23/alex-del-piero/?printpage=undefined|title=Alex Del Piero|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=23 May 2008|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref> he successfully adapted to his new creative attacking role as an assist provider.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/altre-notizie/l-8-novembre-di-12-anni-fa-l-infortunio-ad-alex-del-piero-33608|title=L'8 novembre di 12 anni fa l'infortunio ad Alex Del Piero|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|author1=Federico Bettucci|date=8 November 2010|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio/delpiero/delpiero/delpiero.html|title=La sorte si ricorda di Alex Pinturicchio risorge a Udine|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=5 May 2002|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.lastampa.it/2014/02/21/sport/calcio/qui-juve/le-sette-vite-del-capitano-un-ebook-racconta-alex-del-piero-WU258LwrFalNzBpCJdo8WM/pagina.html|title=\"Le sette vite del capitano\" un ebook racconta Alex Del Piero|newspaper=La Stampa|language=Italian|date=21 February 2014|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref> As Juventus's playing style continued to change during Lippi's second stint with Juventus starting in 2001, Del Piero partnered with Zidane's replacement, Nedv\u011bd, in a free creative role in front of the midfield, or occasionally on the left flank, as a supporting striker in a fluid 4\u20134\u20132 formation, with Trezeguet upfront; he subsequently continued to play a similar role under Capello and later managers, and was even occasionally used in a more offensive role as a main striker, although he became increasingly deployed as a substitute due to his advancing age.<ref name=\"Alessandro the Great\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2002/matches/round=1639/match=1044119/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Madrid fall to brilliant Nedved|publisher=UEFA.com|date=15 May 2003}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/online/calcio_partite/juveven/juveven/juveven.html|title=Del Piero e Trezeguet lanciano la sfida alla Roma|trans-title=Del Piero and Trezeguet launch their duel with Roma|newspaper=[[la Repubblica]]|language=Italian|date=13 December 2004|accessdate=8 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://sport.sky.it/calcio/2018/04/12/lippi-idee-innovazioni-tattiche |title=Lipp-ip hurr\u00e0! Storia di idee tattiche nate da un sigaro |publisher=sport.sky.it |language=Italian |last1=Spinella |first1=Vanni |date=12 April 2018 |accessdate=11 November 2019 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/england/2328644/Five-football-teams-built-by-Fabio-Capello.html |title=Five football teams built by Fabio Capello |work=The Telegraph |last1=Lyttleton |first1=Ben |date=16 December 2007 |accessdate=11 November 2019 }}</ref> Regarding the contrast between Del Piero's precocious performances in his youth and his initial struggle to replicate the heights he achieved prior to his career\u2013threatening injury in 1998, Roberto Beccantini noted in a ''[[Treccani]]'' profile on Del Piero: \"There were two Del Pieros: one was the unmatchable ''fantasista'', capable of scoring unforgettable goals and producing extraordinary assists; the other is the forwrad that, after [[Zden\u011bk Zeman|Zeman]]'s allegations of his use of performing enhancing drugs and the serious injury he suffered to his left knee on 8 November 1998 in Udine, struggled to find himself and went from his 21 league goals of the 1997\u201398 season, a personal record, to only one goal in open play (plus 8 penalties scored) during the 1999\u20132000 season.\" He also noted that Del Piero struggled to replicate his club performances with Juventus at international level with Italy, in particular in major tournaments.<ref name=\"treccani\">{{cite web |url=http://www.treccani.it/enciclopedia/alessandro-del-piero_%28Enciclopedia-dello-Sport%29/ |title=DEL PIERO, Alessandro |publisher=Treccani: Enciclopedia dello Sport (2002) |language=Italian |last1=Beccantini |first1=Roberto |accessdate=7 April 2020 }}</ref> Despite his injury struggles, Del Piero also stood out for his longevity throughout his career, and drew praise in the media for his consistent goalscoring and the high\u2013level of performance he managed to maintain even into his late 30s.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Juventus/17-01-2011/juve-intramontabili-712516709106.shtml |title=Juve, gli intramontabili Ale e Gigi senza tempo |work=La Gazzetta dello Sport |language=Italian |last1=Mauro |first1=Alberto |date=17 January 2011 |accessdate=7 April 2020 }}</ref> In addition to his talent and footballing abilities, Del Piero also drew praise throughout his career for his leadership with Juventus,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/news/calcio/serie-a/juventus/2016/11/24-17779775/parla_lex_medico_juve_del_piero_mente_e_leader_super_boksic/?cookieAccept|title=Parla l\u2019ex medico Juve: \"Del Piero mente e leader. Super Boksic\"|publisher=Tutto Sport|language=Italian|date=24 November 2016|accessdate=2 December 2016}}</ref> and for his fair play and correct behaviour on the pitch.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rainews.it/dl/rainews/articoli/alessandro-del-piero-uomo-riservato-juventus-berlino-nazionale-scudetti-sonia-del-piero-talento-educazione-40-anni-compleanno-18dd62a3-badf-44e6-9743-34a7a5ef6486.html|title=Calcio. Alex Del Piero, un concentrato di talento e fair play|publisher=RaiNews.it|language=Italian|author1=Cristina Raschio|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=2 November 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Set pieces ===\n{{Quote box\n |quote=[Alessandro] Del Piero [is the best Italian player], we're the same age and I've followed his whole career.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11667/7629866/giggs-zanetti-the-toughest|title=Giggs \u2013 Zanetti the toughest|publisher=Sky Sports|author=Simone Bargellini|date=27 March 2012|accessdate=21 April 2016}}</ref>|source=[[Ryan Giggs]]|align=right\n |quoted=1\n |width=36%\n}}\nDel Piero was a [[Direct free kick|free kick]] and [[Penalty kick (association football)|penalty kick]] (62 goals from penalties) specialist.<ref name=\"eroi in bianconero\"/> He is the [[Football records in Italy#Most goals from a penalty kick|third highest scorer of penalties]] in [[Serie A]] history, scoring 50 times out of 61 attempts, behind only Francesco Totti and Roberto Baggio.<ref name=\"90min.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.90min.com/it/posts/369377-i-10-migliori-rigoristi-della-storia-della-serie-a|title=I 10 migliori rigoristi della storia della Serie A|website=90min.com|language=Italian|accessdate=6 January 2015}}</ref> Del Piero's unique free kick technique was usually characterised by a curling strike which rose high over the wall, and then suddenly dropped into the top corner of the goal;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.torinoggi.it/sport/1041-juventus-domenica-i-bianconeri-contro-il-chievo-per-continuare-la-striscia-positiva-.html?pag=290|title=Juventus: una punizione di Del Piero lancia i bianconeri alla vittoria 2\u20130 contro il Chievo|publisher=TorinoOggi.it|language=Italian|accessdate=5 December 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141210075521/http://www.torinoggi.it/sport/1041-juventus-domenica-i-bianconeri-contro-il-chievo-per-continuare-la-striscia-positiva-.html?pag=290|archive-date=10 December 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> he attributes his ability on set pieces to the time spent studying Roberto Baggio in training during their time together at Juventus,<ref name=\"DEL PIERO, FESTA TRADITA\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/altre-notizie/garlando-gazzetta-ferito-e-affamato-del-piero-esempio-anti-crisi-73481|title=Garlando (Gazzetta): \"Ferito e affamato, Del Piero esempio anti-crisi\"|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/1998/gennaio/19/Baggio_meglio_casa_che_panchina_ga_0_9801194973.shtml?refresh_ce-cp|title=Baggio, meglio a casa che in panchina: \"sono schifato\"|trans-title=Baggio, better at home than on the bench: \"I'm disgusted\"|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Alessandra Bocci|author2=Silvano Stella|date=19 January 1998|accessdate=29 October 2015}}</ref> and was also influenced by the free kick technique of one of his idols, Platini. Indeed, in his early years with the Turin club, Del Piero's free kick technique was compared to that of the Frenchman, as he preferred to strike the ball from a distance of around 20 metres from the goal, with a direct kick, rather than having it touched by a teammate first.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1995/ottobre/24/Del_Piero_Tira_alla_Platini_co_0_951024456.shtml|title=Del Piero? Tira alla Platini|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=24 October 1995|p=44|archive-url=https://archive.today/20151106152619/http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1995/ottobre/24/Del_Piero_Tira_alla_Platini_co_0_951024456.shtml|archive-date=6 November 2015}}</ref> Del Piero is currently the Italian all-time top scorer from free kicks in all competitions (52 goals: 46 goals at club level, 6 goals with the Italy national team).<ref name=\"7 Alessandro Del Piero\"/><ref name=\"Alessandro Del Piero\"/> He is also the [[Football records in Italy#Most goals from a free kick|third all-time highest goalscorer of free kicks in Serie A]], with 22 goals, behind only [[Andrea Pirlo]] and [[Sini\u0161a Mihajlovi\u0107]].<ref name=\"Pirlo eyes Mihajlovic record\">{{cite web|url=http://www.football-italia.net/41213/pirlo-eyes-mihajlovic-record|title=Pirlo eyes Mihajlovic record|publisher=Football Italia|accessdate=6 January 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== Del Piero Goal ===\nThe football media refer to a \"Del Piero Goal\" (\"Gol alla Del Piero\" in Italian), a style of scoring involving a dribbling approach from the flank, followed by a precise, [[Curl (football)|curling]] [[Chip (association football)|lob]] into the far top corner of the goal, from outside the area, with a player's stronger foot after cutting into the centre;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/150issue/delpieroicon.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104150909/http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/150issue/delpieroicon.html|archivedate=4 January 2009|title=Calcio Italia 150 issue, Calcio Icons, Del Piero|publisher=Channel4.com|last=Gilbert|first=Dan|date=22 July 2009|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/150issue/delpieroicon.html|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090104150909/http://www.channel4.com/sport/football_italia/150issue/delpieroicon.html|archivedate=4 January 2009|title=Alessandro Del Piero|publisher=Channel4.com|accessdate=26 July 2012}}</ref> as such, this area of the pitch also became known as the \"Del Piero Zone\" in the media (\"Zona Del Piero\" in Italian).<ref name=\"forgotten goals\"/> This association came about as Del Piero had scored several goals in this manner, both in open play and from set-pieces, with his right foot after cutting in from the left flank, during his first two seasons under Lippi, in particular during Juventus's victorious 1995\u201396 Champions League campaign;<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ilpost.it/2012/05/15/i-gol-alla-del-piero/|title=I gol \"alla Del Piero\"|publisher=Il Post|language=Italian|date=15 May 2012|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> Del Piero continued to score similar goals throughout his career,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/1996/12/16/ragazzi-tirate-come-lui.html|title=RAGAZZI, TIRATE COME LUI|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=16 December 1996|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://ricerca.repubblica.it/repubblica/archivio/repubblica/2005/10/17/del-piero-la-voglia-di-futuro-trent.html|title=Del Piero e la voglia di futuro A trent' anni non si \u00e8 decrepiti|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=17 October 2005|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> and the \"Del Piero Goal\" label<ref>{{cite web|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/1997/marzo/02/soldatino_scherza_sul_gol_alla_co_0_9703029601.shtml|title=Il \"soldatino\" scherza sul gol alla Del Piero: \"Alex ha imparato da me\"|publisher=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=2 March 1997|accessdate=5 December 2014}}</ref> has also been used to describe similar goals by other players.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie-A/Inter/16-12-2015/inter-brozovic-gioca-4-ruoli-segna-gol-del-piero-fa-felice-mancini-1301317713161.shtml|title=Inter: Brozovic gioca in 4 ruoli, segna gol alla Del Piero e fa felice Mancini|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|author1=Matteo Brega|date=17 December 2015|accessdate=12 May 2016}}</ref>\n\n=== Goal celebrations ===\nIn his later career, after scoring a goal, Del Piero often celebrated by running to the touchline in front of the fans with his arms out-stretched, and sticking out his tongue, in a similar manner to [[Michael Jordan]], also frequently leaping into the air with a raised fist towards the sky, or sliding onto his knees whilst passionately chanting to the crowd.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/altre-notizie/le-10-perle-pia-belle-di-alessandro-del-piero-69725|title=Le 10 perle pi\u00f9 belle di Alessandro Del Piero|trans-title=The 10 most beautiful pearls [goals] of Alessandro Del Piero|website=tuttojuve.com|publisher=Tutto Juve|language=Italian|author=Camillo Demichelis|date=9 November 2011|accessdate=28 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttosport.com/foto/Calcio/Serie%20A/Juventus/2008/11/09-1132_1/Le+cinque+esultanze+%22magiche%22+di+Del+Piero|title=Le cinque esultanze \"magiche\" di Del Piero|trans-title=Del Piero's five \"magical\" goal celebrations|website=tuttosport.com|publisher=Tutto Sport|date=9 November 2008|accessdate=28 February 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402162456/http://www.tuttosport.com/foto/Calcio/Serie%20A/Juventus/2008/11/09-1132_1/Le+cinque+esultanze+%22magiche%22+di+Del+Piero|archive-date=2 April 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Primo_Piano/2007/10_Ottobre/17/ale.shtml|title=Del Piero per sempre Juve \"Mai pensato di andar via\"|newspaper=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=17 October 2007|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.repubblica.it/rubriche/temposcaduto/2014/12/04/news/del_piero_cos_no-102130495/|title=Del Piero, cos\u00ec no|newspaper=La Repubblica|language=Italian|date=4 December 2014|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> Del Piero also performed a back-flip goal celebration in a 2008 UEFA Champions League match against Zenit,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sport.it/news/juve-zenit-del-piero-sull-esultanza-la-mia-prima-capriola/|title=Juve-Zenit, Del Piero sull'esultanza: \"La mia prima capriola\"|website=sport.it|language=Italian|accessdate=21 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122054112/http://www.sport.it/news/juve-zenit-del-piero-sull-esultanza-la-mia-prima-capriola/|archive-date=22 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> and he also pointed up at the sky after scoring on certain occasions,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.iltempo.it/sport/calcio/2014/11/09/i-primi-40-anni-di-del-piero-anche-totti-gli-fa-gli-auguri-1.1341797|title=I primi 40 anni di Del Piero. Anche Totti gli fa gli auguri|publisher=Il Tempo|language=Italian|date=9 November 2014|accessdate=21 January 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150122050416/http://www.iltempo.it/sport/calcio/2014/11/09/i-primi-40-anni-di-del-piero-anche-totti-gli-fa-gli-auguri-1.1341797|archive-date=22 January 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref> to dedicate a goal to his late father, such as when he scored against Bari during the 2000\u201301 season,<ref name=\"\u00e8 tornato Del Piero\"/> and Mexico at the 2002 World Cup.<ref name=\"Gruppo G: Italia-Messico 1-1\"/>\n\n== Outside football ==\n\n=== Personal life ===\n[[File:Sonia Del Piero, Alessandro Del Piero (11149485886).jpg|thumb|Del Piero and his wife Sonia at the 2013 [[ARIA Music Awards]] in Sydney, Australia.]]\nDel Piero is married to Sonia Amoruso and the two have been together since 1999 and married in 2005.<ref name=\"gazzetta\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/Serie%20A/Primo%20Piano/2005/06-Giugno/13/delpierosposogiusto.shtml|title=Del Piero, dribbling sull'altare|work=[[La Gazzetta dello Sport]]|language=Italian|date=13 June 2005|accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> They have three children, son Tobias (born 2007),<ref name=\"Del Piero, giorni d'oro E' nato il figlio Tobias\"/><ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071113143013/http://www.juventus.com/uk/news/detail.aspx?lml_language_id=0&trs_id=1370000&ID=12566 Congratulations, Captain!] Juventus.com. 22 October 2007.</ref> daughter Dorotea (born 2009)<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.gazzetta.it/Calcio/SerieA/Juventus/05-05-2009/buffon-seredova-bis-50359750968.shtml|title=Del Piero papa|language=Italian|work=La Gazzetta dello Sport |date=5 May 2009 |accessdate=26 May 2012}}</ref> and son Sasha (born 2010).<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20100917052242/http://alessandrodelpiero.com/en/news/12060 \"Five of us\"] Official website. 12 September 2010.</ref>\n\nWhen the [[Olympic Flame]] for the [[2006 Winter Olympics]] passed through [[Turin]], Del Piero was a torchbearer.<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20071014055019/http://juventus.com/uk/news/detail.aspx?lml_language_id=0&trs_id=1370000&ID=6973 \"Also Alex with the Olympic flame\"] Juventus.com. 10 February 2006</ref> He has an interest in sports outside of football, particularly basketball, and in turn has gained fans outside of football; sport icons such as [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] star [[Steve Nash]] and cyclist [[Eddy Merckx]] have stated that they are fans of Del Piero.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://fifaworldcup.yahoo.com/06/en/060705/1/8lj6.html |title=FIFA World Cup @ Yahoo.com |publisher=yahoo.com|accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Del Piero, Italy's Stoical Substitute|url=http://www.geocities.com/juventusfootball/news/archived00/061300.htm|work=[[Reuters]]|date=13 June 2000|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091027162246/http://geocities.com/juventusfootball/news/archived00/061300.htm|archivedate=27 October 2009 }}</ref>\n\nDel Piero has a keen interest in music. He has recorded some of his own albums.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.internetbookshop.it/cd/ser/serdsp.asp?e=0828767896427|title=InternetBookShop.it|publisher=InternetBookShop.it|date=28 May 2010 |accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref> Along with [[Marco Materazzi]], Del Piero appeared on stage at a [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] show in [[Milan]] shortly after Italy's World Cup win.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/rolling-stones/23578 |title=The Rolling Stones cover The White Stripes! |work=NME.com |date=12 July 2006 |accessdate=26 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120208071533/http://www.nme.com/news/rolling-stones/23578 |archivedate=8 February 2012 }}</ref> He is a good friend of musician and singer [[Noel Gallagher]] and a fan of his former band [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]]; Del Piero appears in the Oasis video \"[[Lord Don't Slow Me Down (song)|Lord Don't Slow Me Down]]\".{{citation needed|date=January 2020}} One of Del Piero's inspirations as a youngster was Japanese football manga [[Captain Tsubasa]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nippon.com/en/views/b00103/|title=A Soccer Hero Adored Around the World}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012, he participated in the project \"Save the dream\" (against corruption in the sport) and spoke about this at [[University of Paris|Sorbonne]], during the \"Sport Integrity Symposium\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sport.sky.it/sport/calcio_italiano/2012/09/11/del_piero_professore_sorbona_parigi.html |title=Del Piero professore per un giorno alla Sorbona \u2013 Sport \u2013 Sky.it |publisher=Sport |date=}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alessandrodelpiero.com/news/save-the-dream_292.html |title=Save the Dream |publisher=Alessandro Del Piero |date=}}</ref>\n\nSince March 2018, Del Piero has been running an Italian restaurant in [[Los Angeles]] called No.10, representing his jersey number 10.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.n10restaurant.com/about|title=About N10 Restaurant|publisher=N10 Restaurant|accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/food/dailydish/la-fo-re-newsfeed-n10-20180327-story.html|title=Soccer star Alessandro Del Piero just opened an Italian restaurant in Beverly Grove|publisher=Los Angeles Times|date=27 March 2019|accessdate=11 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Charity work ===\nDel Piero has promoted and supported a number of charities. In 1998, he donated 5.2&nbsp;million lire to \"Fondazione Bambini in Emergenza\" (for abandoned children and victims of AIDS) by auctioning his Juventus shirt.\n<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/1998/maggio/31/Del_Piero_batte_Ronaldo_all_ga_0_9805319923.shtml|title=Del Piero batte Ronaldo all'asta di beneficenza|periodical=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=31 May 1998|accessdate=16 September 2009}}</ref> In 2001, he was ambassador for \"Un gol per la ricerca\" (for the cancer research).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2008/ottobre/31/Airc_maratona_Rai_per_fondi_co_9_081031066.shtml|title=Airc, maratona in Rai per i fondi alla ricerca|periodical=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=31 October 2008|accessdate=16 September 2009}}</ref> In 2006, he was AIRC testimonial for the cancer research and in recognition of this, he has received from the [[President of Italy]] a prize of \"Believe in Research\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sportwide.net/airc06-delpiero.html|title=Premio Credere nella Ricerca|publisher=sportwide.net|accessdate=16 September 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110724081419/http://www.sportwide.net/airc06-delpiero.html|archivedate=24 July 2011}}</ref> In 2008, he participated in a golf tournament organized by the foundation of [[Gianluca Vialli]] and [[Massimo Mauro]] for [[Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis]] research.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gossipnews.it/sport/alex_del_piero_e_pavel_nedved_giocano_a_golf_per_beneficenza_sperw.html?id=b29c7ea8e773a83c5da79d619012c5c6|title=Alex Del Piero e Nedved giocano a golf per beneficenza|periodical=gossipnews.it|accessdate=16 September 2009}}</ref> In 2009, he played a friendly match at [[Stadio Olimpico di Torino|Stadio Olimpico]] with his team \"Ale 10+\"; the proceeds (\u20ac180,000) were donated to solidarity projects.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.corriere.it/2009/maggio/14/Olimpico_esaurito_per_Partita_del_co_9_090514085.shtml|title=Olimpico esaurito per la Partita del cuore|periodical=Il Corriere della Sera|language=Italian|date=14 May 2009|accessdate=16 September 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, he auctioned off his Juventus shirt number 10 for the foundation \"Un Campo per L'Aquila\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tuttojuve.com/?action=read&idnotizia=22107 |title=La maglia di Del Piero all'asta per beneficenza |publisher=Tutto Juve|accessdate=26 July 2016}}</ref> On 1 April 2011, he launched the project \"ale10friendsforjapan\" which he designed to help Japanese earthquake victims creating a [http://www.ale10friendsforjapan.org/ website] to sell T-shirts and collecting $303,880.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alessandrodelpiero.com/news/raccolti-30388000_210.html |title=RACCOLTI $303,880.00 |publisher=Alessandro Del Piero |date=13 September 2011}}</ref> In 2011, he participated in a golf tournament, \"Fondazione Sant'Anna Cup \u2013 Crescere insieme\", for the neonatal intensive care unit of the hospital Sant'Anna.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alessandrodelpiero.com/news/golf-e-beneficenza_185.html |title=Golf E Beneficenza |publisher=Alessandro Del Piero |date=27 May 2011}}</ref> On 21 July 2012, he played a friendly match at [[Kashima Soccer Stadium|Kashima Stadium]] organized by [[J. League Division 1|J. League]] (Del Piero scored one goal and he left the field with a standing ovation); the collection was donated to the Japanese earthquake victims of 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alessandrodelpiero.com/news/gol-a-kashima_285.html |title=Gol A Kashima |publisher=Alessandro Del Piero |date=21 July 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was testimonial of ADISCO, for the donation of umbilical cord blood,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alessandrodelpiero.com/news/una-penna-preziosa_107.html |title=Una Penna Preziosa |publisher=Alessandro Del Piero |date=}}</ref><ref name=\"alessandrodelpiero.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.alessandrodelpiero.com/solidale.html |title=Alessandro Del Piero, solidale |publisher=Alessandrodelpiero.com |date=}}</ref> and testimonial of 1GOAL for the education of poor children.<ref name=\"alessandrodelpiero.com\"/> In 2015, in honour of [[Formula One|F1]] World Champion [[Ayrton Senna]], Del Piero facilitated and inaugurated the \"AYRTON\" exhibition in [[Turin]], open between February and May 2015. The exhibition is curated by, with tickets proceeds going to, the [[Instituto Ayrton Senna]] charity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.alessandrodelpiero.com/news/inauguration-of-the-ayrton-exhibition_475.html |title=Inauguration of the \"Ayrton\" exhibition|work=ADPLOG|date=19 February 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== TV, games, and publicity ===\n[[File:Evento presentazione FIFA 2004.jpg|thumbnail|190px|right|Del Piero during the presentation of ''[[FIFA 2004]]''.]]\nDel Piero has featured in various advertisements and is under contract with German sports equipment manufacturer [[Adidas]], [[Uliveto (company)|Uliveto]] water, [[Fiat]], Japanese motorbike company [[Suzuki]], [[Pepsi]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nVGJBRtlQHI |title=Pepsi Commercial |publisher=Youtube.com |date=}}</ref> Bliss, Cepu, [[The Walt Disney Company|Walt Disney]] and [[Upper Deck]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://archiviostorico.gazzetta.it/1998/maggio/08/Del_Piero_che_faccia_spot_ga_0_9805081924.shtml|title=Del Piero, che faccia da spot|periodical=La Gazzetta dello Sport|language=Italian|date=8 May 1998}}</ref>\n\nIn 2006, he appeared in a television commercial for the Japanese motor scooter Suzuki Burgman together with the sports agent [[Andreas Goller]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SzD6FNVtiVs |title=Alessandro Del Piero Mr. Burgman|publisher=YouTube|date=22 July 2009 |accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nDel Piero is also known for his sense of humour and is a popular guest at Italian comedy shows such as ''Paperissima'' and ''[[Striscia la notizia]]''. He featured in the film \"[[L'allenatore nel pallone 2]]\" and in the show ''La sai l'ultima di Totti'', a series of short comedy sketches created by his good friend and Roma captain [[Francesco Totti]] in which the two of them and national teammates former [[A.C. Milan]] defender [[Alessandro Nesta]], Juventus goalkeeper [[Gianluigi Buffon]] and striker [[Antonio Cassano]] would tell jokes and anecdotes about one another.\n\nDel Piero was featured on the cover of [[EA Sports]] ''[[FIFA Football 2004]]'' video game, alongside [[Thierry Henry]] and [[Ronaldinho]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fifa04.com/ |title=FIFA Football 2004 |publisher=UEFA.com |url-status=dead |accessdate=11 July 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120725082120/http://www.fifa04.com/ |archivedate=25 July 2012 }}</ref> and on the cover of the Italian edition of the ''[[2006 FIFA World Cup (video game)|FIFA World Cup 2006]]'' video game.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.xboxway.com/2006/03/24/xbox-360-alex-del-piero-testimonial-di-ea-sports-mondiali-fifa-2006/|title=Xbox 360 \u2013 Alex Del Piero testimonial di EA Sports Mondiali FIFA 2006|website=xboxway.com|language=Italian|date=24 March 2006|accessdate=25 April 2015}}</ref> He was also named in the Ultimate Team Legends in ''[[FIFA 17]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.easports.com/fifa/ultimate-team/features/new-fut-legends|title=New Legends in FUT 17|publisher=EA Sports|accessdate=26 August 2016}}</ref> He was one of the two stars featured on the cover of the Italian version of ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer 2010|PES 2010]]'' video game, the other being [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]]'s [[Lionel Messi]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://winningelevenblog.com/blog/del-piero-confirmed-as-pes-2010-italian-cover-star/|title=Del Piero Confirmed as PES 2010 Italian Cover Star|work=Winningelevenblog.com|date=16 July 2009|accessdate=13 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Del Piero joined [[Sky Sport (Italy)|Sky Sport Italia]] as a [[pundit]].<ref name=\"Del Piero wants coaching career\"/>\n\nIn 2017, Del Piero appeared in the [[Netflix]] [[docu-series]] called ''[[First Team: Juventus]]''.<ref name=\"Corsa\">{{cite web|url=https://www.esquire.com/it/cultura/film/amp18225511/documentario-juve-netflix/|title=Il documentario sulla Juve di Netflix \u00e8 un esperimento riuscito|publisher=www.esquire.com|language=Italian|author=Antonio Corsa|date=19 February 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, [[Konami]] announced that Del Piero will feature in their football video game ''[[Pro Evolution Soccer 2019]]'', as one of the new myClub Legends.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.konami.com/wepes/2018/eu/en/topic/legend_delpiero_nedved |title=Pavel Nedv\u011bd and Alessandro Del Piero coming to PES! |publisher=www.konami.com |date=19 March 2018 |accessdate=11 September 2018 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.calciomercato.com/en/news/watch-del-piero-is-in-the-legend-team-of-pes2019-27266 |title=Watch: Del Piero is in the legend team of PES2019 |publisher=www.calciomercato.com |date=8 September 2018 |accessdate=11 September 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Career statistics ==\n[[File:Del Piero 250.jpg|thumb|250px|right|Del Piero scoring his 250th goal against [[Reggina Calcio|Reggina]] in the [[2008\u201309 Serie A|2008\u201309 Serie A season]].]]\n\n=== Club ===\n:Source:<ref name=\"Alessandro Del Piero\">{{cite web|title=Alessandro Del Piero|url=http://espnfc.com/player/_/id/12952/alessandro-del-piero?cc=5739|publisher=ESPN FC|accessdate=28 August 2013}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align: center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Season\n!rowspan=\"2\"|Club\n!colspan=\"3\"|League\n!colspan=\"2\"|Cup\n!colspan=\"2\"|Continental\n!colspan=\"2\"|Other{{ref|1}}\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=\"3\"|[[Calcio Padova|Padova]]\n|[[1991\u201392 Serie B|1991\u201392]]\n|rowspan=\"2\"|[[Serie B]]\n||4||0||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||4||0\n|-\n|[[1992\u201393 Serie B|1992\u201393]]\n||10||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||10||1\n|-\n!colspan=\"2\"|Total||14||1||0||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||14||1\n|-\n|rowspan=\"20\"|[[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]]\n|[[1993\u201394 Juventus F.C. season|1993\u201394]]\n|rowspan=\"13\"|[[Serie A]]\n||11||5||1||0||2||0||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||14||5\n|-\n|[[1994\u201395 Juventus F.C. season|1994\u201395]]\n||29||8||10||1||11||2||colspan=\"2\"|\u2014||50||11\n|-\n|[[1995\u201396 Juventus F.C. season|1995\u201396]]\n||29||6||2||1||11||6||1||0||43||13\n|-\n|[[1996\u201397 Juventus F.C. season|1996\u201397]]\n||22||8||4||0||6||4||3||3||35||15\n|-\n|[[1997\u201398 Juventus F.C. season|19